items.title: Thousands flee renewed fighting in eastern Congo
items.description:
1. Wide of dispersed people trying to reach the town of Goma
2. Mid of dispersed women and children walking
3. Mid of woman and men pushing luggage on a wheelbarrow 
4. Mid of dispersed people and zoom to small boy carrying jug for water
5. Wide of UN troops with tanks heading towards where fighting is taking place
6. SOUNDBITE: (Kiswahili) Edwin Lvgork, fleeing Kibumba's displaced peoples' camp:
"The soldiers from the Rwandan side came up from the villages and what people are saying is that these rebels are not from Congo. But what we are seeing is that they are rebels from Rwanda and they have come down towards the village of Kibumba. That is why you can see the mass population of the people from Kibumba running away." 
7, Wide of government soldiers. 
8. Mid of one government soldier carrying rocket launcher 
9. Mid of two women carrying children and government troops with government tanks in background on the road.
10. Mid of displaced girl carrying a baby on her back.
STORYLINE:
U.N. peacekeepers used helicopter gunships against rebels in eastern Congo on Monday, trying to halt a rebel advance as government troops hastily retreated and civilians attacked U.N. headquarters demanding protection.
In what appeared to be a major retreat, hundreds of government soldiers pulled back from the battlefront north
of Goma, the capital of North Kivu province, fleeing in tanks, jeeps, trucks and on foot.
Soldiers honked their horns angrily as they struggled to push through throngs of displaced people poured onto the
main road. 
Tens of thousands of civilians abandoned their homes ahead of the rebel advance.
U.N. spokeswoman Sylvie van den Wildenberg said the peacekeepers in the gunships fired at rebel forces surging
on Kibumba, about 28 miles (45 kilometres) north of Goma.
Rebel leader Gen. Laurent Nkunda has threatened to take Goma in defiance of calls from the U.N. Security Council for him to respect a U.N.-brokered cease-fire signed in January.
It was the second time this year peacekeepers had fired on Nkunda's rebels. 
In December, U.N. officials also used helicopters to repel the rebels, killing hundreds under their mandate to protect civilians in the vast Central African country that has been ravaged by years of dictatorship and civil war.
Rebel spokesman Bertrand Bisimwa told The Associated Press that rebel fighters were within seven miles of Goma.
Residents of Katindo, a neighborhood three miles from downtown Goma, told the AP they heard bombs exploding late on Monday afternoon.
As the crowds reached the city, soldiers blocked access to the northern entrance of Goma, apparently fearing that
rebels could be trying to infiltrate with the displaced civilians.
Earlier on Monday, crowds of protesters attacked four U.N. compounds in Goma with rocks, venting outrage that the U.N. peacekeeping mission - the biggest in the world with 17,000 troops - has been unable to protect them from the rebels. 
Residents opposed to rebels, including Hutus and those who lived in refugee camps after fleeing earlier conflicts,
feel particularly threatened. 
The crowds shattered windows and damaged cars at the main U.N. office, van den Wildenberg said. 
Congo's government has accused the Tutsi-led government that won power in Rwanda after the genocide of sending troops to support Nkunda - a charge Rwanda denies and the U.N. says is unfounded.
The rhetoric strengthens ethnic tensions amid fears Congo's conflict could again escalate beyond its borders. 
Back-to-back wars in DR Congo spilled into half a dozen neighbouring countries and destroyed much of the ravaged nation itself by 2002. 
Rwanda officially withdrew its troops from DR Congo after a peace deal ended the country's 1998-2002 war.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/cdb63c83252855edcb3370a542f84552 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: IDPs head to UN camps, body on road
items.description:
1. Wide shot of displaced people walking on the road, laden with their belongings
2. Various of displaced people walking on the road, laden with belongings
3. SOUNDBITE: (Kiswahili) Nick Ndungo, Kiwanja resident: 
"What we've seen now is rebels stealing people's properties. There is nothing else happening, it's just killing civilians and stealing. If you go just about 300 metres from where we are you can see a lot of bodies in the houses.  Even in the homes there's a lot of bodies of civilians. And the civilians have no argument with anyone." 
4. Wide shot of displaced people walking along the road (heading for UN camp)
5. Wide of shot of UN camp at Kiwanja
6. Mid shot of family seated on ground, cooking pot on the fire
7. Close up shot of two young boys sitting in tent
8. Close up little boy's face
9. Various of big crowd of children gathered
10. UN helicopter flying over the camp
11. Makeshift tents and displaced people in camp, UN trucks in background 
12. Wide shot of a dead body in khaki uniform left on the street 
13. Closer shot of the dead body
14. Wide shot of displaced people walking past a destroyed rebels' jeep 
STORYLINE:
Civilians continued to flee fighting in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) on Saturday, after new clashes erupted  between government forces and government-backed Mai Mai militia, and rebels of General Laurent Nkunda's CNDP (Congres National Pour La Defense Du Peuple).
In the eastern town of Kiwanja, 80 kilometres (50 miles) east of Goma - where about 45,000 people have taken refuge - hundreds of displaced people were on the move, heading for a UN camp near the town.
Nkunda called a unilateral cease-fire last week when his forces reached the outskirts of Goma, but the truce has crumbled.
On Thursday, Human Rights Watch and local villagers accused Nkunda's rebels of killing dozens of men in civilian clothes who were suspected of supporting Mai Mai militia against the rebels.
The dead body of a uniformed man could be seen in front of a house on Saturday.
A local man told AP Television News that rebels had killed civilians and left bodies piled up in houses. 
Nkunda is blamed for a 10-week offensive that has forced 250,000 people from their homes as his fighters captured great swathes of eastern DRC, in a conflict that many fear will spread.
The conflict is fuelled by festering ethnic hatred left over from the 1994 slaughter of a half-million Tutsis in Rwanda, and DRC's civil wars from 1996-2002, which drew its neighbours into a rush to plunder its mineral wealth.
Nkunda defected from the army in 2004, saying he needed to protect his tiny Tutsi minority from Rwandan Hutu militias. He has since expanded his mission to "liberating" the DRC from an allegedly corrupt government.
But experts dismiss as fantasy his ambitions of marching on Kinshasa and deposing DRC President Joseph Kabila - the nation's first freely elected leader in nearly half a century.
The United Nations believes Nkunda has 6,500 men; he says he has 10,000.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/725b4997fc741c7e7891495bc573143d 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Scenes from town behind rebel lines, displaced
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Wide of road block
2. Close up of part of barricade
3. Wide of Kibumba village, zoom into rebel
4. Rebels in village
5. SOUNDBITE: (Swahili) Fridah Furaha, Displaced person:
"I was running away from the fighting in Rimangabo but could not continue with my journey when I got to Kibumba because there was also fighting there. All my belongings have been stolen now so I'm left with nothing."
6. Various of looted house
7. SOUNDBITE: (Swahili) Gatambaza Kariwabo, Chief of Kibumba village:
"We have been living well with the rebels ever since they came here. They have never done anything bad to us. Now we are starting a new chapter with them and we want everything to be good, some residents have even started going back to their homes."
8. Wide of a looted bank
9. Mid of broken door 
10. Various of safe that was broken into and looted
11. Close up of a broken padlock that was used to lock the safe
12. Mid shot of cooking pots that were thrown away
STORYLINE
Thousands of people displaced by the violence in the east of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) set out on foot for their homes on Friday, taking advantage of a ceasefire, as US and UN envoys joined efforts to find a political solution to the region's long-running rebellion.
Rebels from Laurent Nkunda's renegade movement manned checkpoints outside the city, which were littered with plastic and metal canisters from rocket launchers.
Associated Press reporters followed the crush of people fleeing the battlefront between the army and the rebels, walking past bodies of several soldiers on the outskirts of Goma, the rebel-besieged provincial capital of eastern DRC.
Some headed home on Friday to Kibumba, a village about 17 miles (28 kilometres) from Goma.
The top US envoy for Africa, Jendayi Frazer, and Alan Doss, the top UN envoy in Congo, flew into Goma to help find a political solution. 
Nkunda began a low-level rebellion three years ago claiming DRC's transition to democracy had excluded the Tutsi ethnic group. 
Despite agreeing in January to a UN-brokered cease-fire, he resumed fighting in August.
Nkunda alleges the government has not protected ethnic Tutsis from the Rwandan Hutu militia that escaped to DRC Congo after helping slaughter half a million Rwandan Tutsis in 1994.
Congo has charged Nkunda himself with involvement in war crimes, and Human Rights Watch says it has documented summary executions, torture, and rape committed by soldiers under Nkunda's command in 2002 and 2004.
Rights groups have also accused government forces of atrocities and widespread looting.
The cease-fire Nkunda called on Wednesday night appeared to be holding Friday morning. 
He said he had called it to allow humanitarian help to get through and the refugees to go home.
In Kibumba, village chief Gatambaza Kariwabo appeared to be on the side of the rebels and said soldiers had looted homes and the bank..
He said the rebels had "never done anything bad" to the village residents who were now attempting to return to their homes and start afresh.
Nkunda's rebellion has threatened to reignite the back-to-back wars that afflicted DRC from 1996 to 2002, drawing in eight African nations.
President Joseph Kabila, elected in 2006 in the first vote in 40 years, has struggled ever since to contain the bloody insurgency in the east.
The rebel leader said Thursday he wanted direct talks with the government of DRC. 
The United Nations has only 6-thousand of its 17-thousand Congo peacekeepers in the east because of unrest in other provinces. 
It says the force is badly overstretched.
The European Union decided Friday against sending troops into Congo,saying the 27-member bloc will instead focus on a diplomatic solution to end the conflict.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/3196f875e314f588a1af07fb3b6db2d3 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: UN officials, rebels say forces loyal to renegade General seize army camp
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Travelling shot of displaced people walking from direction of Rumangabo and Rugari, heading toward Goma, 50 kilometres (31 miles) away
2. Various of displaced people walking road carrying their belongings 
3. Woman carrying baby on her back 
4. SOUNDBITE (Swahili) Nzabakurukiza, Displaced person from Rugari:
"There is no peace. We are just running while bullets fly from every part of the village."
5. Mid of government soldiers walking down street, in opposite direction to where displaced people are heading
6. Men standing over dead bodies of three teenagers, allegedly run over and killed by a government tank on its way to scene of fighting nearby
7. Mid of dead bodies
8. SOUNDBITE (Swahili) Munyonti Kasigwa, Father of one of boys killed:
"This tank with the soldiers came at high speed and ran over these children. They tried to run into the bush but the tank hit them."
9. Wide people digging grave as dead body is brought to the side 
10. Body being prepared for burial 
11. Body being lowered into grave  
12. Man covering body with earth
13. Wide of government jeep driving down road, displaced people on either side of road 
14. Soldiers walking down street, towards scene of fighting 
15. Wide of mountains where fighting is taking place
STORYLINE
Rebels loyal to a renegade warlord seized an army base in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and the headquarters of a park housing some of the world's last mountain gorillas, in heavy fighting on Sunday that sent thousands of civilians fleeing, United Nations officials and rebels said.
An unknown number of soldiers, rebels and civilians were killed in the renewed fighting in North Kivu province, according to civilians who said the onslaught began around 2 a.m. (0100 GMT). 
Government troops raced down the road north from the provincial capital of Goma to reinforce a counterattack on Sunday morning.
One tank careered into a group of fleeing civilians and killed three teenage boys, eyewitnesses including the father of one if the dead boys said. 
Associated Press reporters who watched the fathers burying their sons in a cabbage patch outside Kibumba could hear the bombing from army tanks about 12 miles (20 kilometres) from Rumangabo army camp.
UN peacekeepers drove from their camp to investigate the deaths, but angry civilians threw rocks at their vehicle, forcing them to turn back. 
The troopers, from India, used riot shields to block the rocks.
Such attacks have become common, with civilians accusing the UN peacekeeping mission - the biggest in the world with 18-thousand troops - of not fulfilling its mandate to protect the population.
"There is no peace. We are just running while bullets fly from every part of the village," said one man as he made his way from his village to Goma, 50 kilometres (31 miles) away. 
The UN force has failed to halt the fighting in the vast region of rural hills and forests, and both sides in the combat also accuse the United Nations of siding with the other.
Sunday's attack marked the second time rebels have seized Rumangabo army base since fighting resumed August 28 when rebel leader General  Laurent Nkunda went on the offensive, charging government troops had attacked and broken a cease-fire agreed in January.
Nkunda's fighters, who claim to be protecting the region's Tutsi minority, have occupied parts of Virunga National Park for nearly a year, but they attacked the headquarters for the first time before dawn on Sunday.
The park is home to 200 of the world's 700 remaining mountain gorillas, which are considered critically endangered. 
Many displaced civilians are malnourished and some are dying of hunger, the UN World Food Programme said on Friday.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/273c4fee43c0edd63346f4cfd135d34a 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Lack of funding threatens WFP relief operation
items.description:
SHOTLIST
Kongolo:
1. Wide shot of Kongolo town
2. Various of Kongolo town
3. Mid shot Kongolo town
4. Close up child licking empty spoon
5. Wide shot Kongolo hospital
6. Interior of doctor treating malnourished child
7. Close up of doctor adjusting intravenous drip
8. Mid shot of malnourished child
9. Pan to doctor treating malnourished child
10. SOUNDBITE: (French) Ayombo Mbungu Internally, Displaced Congolese 
"We left everything and ran. Everything because of the Mayi Mayi."
11. Wide shot of aircraft with relief supplies on airstrip
12. Mid shot of workers loading food aid on to a truck
13. Interior of aircraft of workers unloading food aid
14. Wide shot of food aid
Kalemie:
15. Wide shot of Kalemie Town near Lake Tanganyika
16. Mid shot Kalemie Town around Lake Tanganyika
17. Pan of woman carrying food aid on her head
18. Mid shot of food distribution
19. SOUNDBITE: (French) Sylvan Mosafiri WFP Information Officer:
"The situation of food in Katanga is catastrophic. This is the highest level of malnutrition we have ever seen in this country. For example in Kalemie the level of malnutrition varies between 14 and 16 per cent, but when you go to Manono the level is up to 32 per cent."
20. Wide shot of a hospital ward in Kalemie
21. Close up of malnourished child
22. Nurses sorting medicines
23. Zoom into infant
STORYLINE:
A New York - based human rights NGO has announced that nearly 2.5 million people have died as a result of the three year war in the Democratic Republic of Congo, many from malnutrition and disease. 
Now the World Food Program (WFP) is saying that their humanitarian relief operation is in danger of collapse because of a lack of funding. 
Surrounded by a vast jungle and tribal militia allied to the government, Kongolo town has been cut off from the rest of Congo, its residents suffering from malnutrition, disease and abject poverty.
With the road, bridges and railway destroyed or too dangerous to use because of reportedly ruthless Mayi Mayi tribal militia, Kongolo's 50,000 residents' only link to the outside world are aid agency relief planes.
In the town's small hospital over 50 children are currently fighting a silent battle against malnutrition. 
Escaping from nearby villages many Congolese have come for help in Kongolo, where the WFP has been delivering supplies to the hospital, but the threat of Mayi-Mayi attack on the roads has stopped many from making the journey.
The latest strife in Congo erupted in August 1998, when Rwanda, Uganda and their Congolese rebel allies took up arms against then-President Laurent Kabila, accusing him of nepotism, warmongering and backing Rwandan and Ugandan rebels.
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia poured thousands of troops and military hardware into Congo in support of Kabila. 
Factions of Mayi Mayi, uncoordinated, tribally-based warriors fighting for local autonomy, have fought on both sides. 
Under a peace agreement that has ended the fighting between the regular forces, the government is supposed to disarm and pacify the Mayi Mayi, but they have kept fighting.
The United Nations was only allowed to begin relief efforts in June, after a cease-fire took hold. 
But the total destruction of roads, railways and the continuing Mayi Mayi attacks have forced relief agencies to use expensive airlifts. 
The World Food Program (WFP) claim the operation is in danger of collapsing due to lack of funding.
The agency needs at least 175,000 U-S dollars to pay for the flights, which could help the people of Kongolo and other parts of northern Katanga province.
The airlifts are part of a larger 112 million U-S dollar effort to feed 1.3 million needy Congolese between now and December 2002. 


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/2679962b188e0f0cf73340d616af6e0a 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Cars set of for 20th biennial World Solar Challenge
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Dutch team preparing car
2. University of Michigan preparing car
3. SOUNDBITE (English) Cameron Wyle: University of Michigan Team Manager:
"Things are looking pretty good. We've run over three thousand kilometres of testing, some in Australia, some in the US, track testing, road testing. And with our qualifying position, we feel pretty good about where we are, in terms of the rest of the pack and how our car will perform."
4. Man spreading French flag out on car
5. SOUNDBITE (English) Chris Selwood, World Solar Challenge director:
"But the real winner in this is humanity. Because these young people are pushing the boundaries of clean vehicle technology, presenting us and making us think about what we drive and what fuels the cars that we use."
6. Clare Martin, Northern Territory chief minister, waves off Ashiya University car
7. Car leaving start
8. Clare Martin waving the start of another entrant
9. Various of car on road
10. Pan from sign with distances to solar car driving past
11. Driver of car waves
12. Southern Taiwan University car driving
13. Pan from termite mound to car driving past
14. SOUNDBITE (English) Peter van Geel, Umicore team leader:
"It's good that we're in first position. But we had the pole position in Darwin, so yeah, it's good. Very good."
15. Belgium University Umicore team putting roof on car
16. Various of Umicore team car on road
STORYLINE
Cars in the 20th biennial World Solar Challenge left Darwin on Sunday for the three thousand kilometre (1,864 miles) journey to Adelaide.
Thirty eight solar cars and 19 energy efficient vehicles will spend most of the week on the road, with the winner expected to reach Adelaide on Thursday.
"The real winner in this is humanity. Because these young people are pushing the boundaries of clean vehicle technology, presenting us and making us think about what we drive and what fuels the cars that we use," event director Chris Selwood said.
Entrants came from 17 countries.
The team from the University of Michigan was confident of a strong performance before they left.
"With our qualifying position we feel pretty good about where we are, in terms of the rest of the pack and how our car will perform," said team leader Cameron Wyle.
Unfortunately, the Americans ran into trouble only three kilometres (1,8 miles) from the start, when they collided with a support vehicle and were forced to retire.
Belgium's Umicore team, which started the race on pole position, was an early leader as cars headed to the first checkpoint at Katherine, 330 kilometres (205 miles) south of Darwin.
However, at the end of the first day, it was the Japanese team from Ashiya University who led the pack.

items.title: Australia, Indonesia boost ties to fight smuggling
items.description:
STORYLINE:
The leaders of Australia and Indonesia agreed on Tuesday to strengthen maritime ties as part of a bid to combat people smuggling, after two boats carrying Australia-bound migrants capsized and left dozens dead in the past two weeks.
The debate over how to cope with the increasing flow of asylum seekers has intensified in Australia since the boat disasters, in which more than 90 people are believed to have been killed. 
Their boats sank in the Indian Ocean between Indonesia and the Australian territory of Christmas Island, where Australia runs an immigration detention centre. 
Australia's Prime Minister Julia Gillard and Indonesian President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono met in the Northern Territory capital of Darwin to discuss how to handle the politically-charged problem, along with economic and trade issues.
Gillard said Australia would work with Indonesia's maritime search and rescue agency to help strengthen its communication abilities with vessels during sea disasters and would look into an exchange programme of search and rescue specialists.
"I welcome the strong cooperation we have with Indonesia on people smuggling, including Indonesia's law enforcement efforts against people smuggling syndicates," Gillard told reporters.
Yudhoyono said he and Gillard had discussed the importance of the Bali Process, an Asia-Pacific body against people smuggling and human trafficking, and noted that Indonesia was also suffering.
Neither leader took questions from journalists.
Australia is a common destination for boats carrying asylum seekers from Afghanistan, Iraq, Sri Lanka and other poor or war-ravaged countries. 
Many asylum seekers travel first to Indonesia and then try to complete the journey to Australia aboard rickety, overcrowded fishing boats. 
The boats generally head for Christmas Island, which is closer to Indonesia than to the Australian mainland.
Following his meeting with Gillard, Yudhoyono told an Australia Indonesia Business Council gathering that he was optimistic about Indonesia's economic development course, "despite the gloomy world economic situation."

items.title: Raw Video | About 90 Killed In Blast At Ghana Gas Station
items.description:
Raw Video | About 90 Killed In Blast At Ghana Gas Station
Raw Video | About 90 Killed In Blast At Ghana Gas Station
Raw Video | About 90 Killed In Blast At Ghana Gas Station


An explosion at a petrol station in Ghana's capital killed around 90 people sheltering from a storm early on Thursday, emergency services said, in the worst disaster to strike the West African state in more than a decade.

https://youtu.be/L6M9YZMZy-4

The force of the blast gave few a chance to escape. People were burnt beyond recognition where they stood under the station's awning, or trapped in the charred wreckage of cars and minivans parked on its forecourt.

The accident was caused by a fire at a nearby lorry terminal. Flames spread to the state-run GOIL petrol station via spilt fuel floating on flood water, fire brigade spokesman Prince Billy Anaglate said.

"It was an explosive fire and so the people sheltering at the filling station did not have an opportunity to escape," Anaglate said.

It was Ghana's worst disaster since more than 120 people died in May 2001 in a stampede at the national stadium during a football match, a police spokesman said.

The incident exposed Accra's vulnerability to storms, given poor drainage and weak infrastructure that has failed to keep pace with population growth after years of rapid economic expansion.

Low-wage workers struggling to get home through the storm, with roads closed and minivan buses not running, formed the bulk of those caught in the explosion, witnesses said.

Several other people were swept away by the seasonal storm in the coastal city and thousands more were made homeless as flood waters rose, officials said.

items.title: UN INCENDIE GRAVE AU GHANA TUE + DE 90 PERSONNES
items.description:
UN INCENDIE GRAVE AU GHANA TUE + DE 90 PERSONNES
Au moins 90 personnes ont péri à Accra dans l'incendie mercredi soir d'une station-service où les victimes étaient venues s'abriter de pluies diluviennes, une catastrophe qui a conduit le président ghanéen à décréter trois jours de deuil national à compter de lundi.

L'incendie a ravagé une station-service dans le centre de la capitale ghanéenne, à proximité du rond-point Kwame Nkrumah. Il se serait déclenché dans une résidence à proximité, puis se serait propagé aux pompes à essence qui ont explosé, selon des témoins.

La grande majorité des victimes s'étaient réfugiées dans la station-service pour s'abriter de pluies torrentielles à l'origine d'importantes inondations dans la capitale ghanéenne ces derniers jours.

«Pour le moment, le chiffre confirmé atteint environ 90 (morts), mais je sais que ce sera plus que cela. Les agences concernées sont en train de faire le décompte», a déclaré le porte-parole de la police nationale, Arthur Cephas.

Le président du Ghana, visiblement très ému, s'est rendu sur place et n'a pu que déplorer le très lourd bilan du sinistre.

De nouvelles précipitations sont attendues à Accra jeudi et vendredi.
la presse.ca

items.title: Adventures in Ghana: Week One
items.description:
WEEK ONE: I've arrived in Accra, the capital of Ghana! Watch how my first week of volunteering unfolded.

Thank you to CUSE and FYS of the University of Notre Dame for making my research and volunteerism possible! Scroll down for a short overview of my research. Thank you to Professor Mary Kearney for advising my research and helping shape my approach to similar topics!

-
Welcome to my YouTube channel, home to the Edupreneurship podcast with Zack Baker and my research video blogs. Want to get on the show or ask a question about education or my research? Tweet @mrpetefreeman!

Global Mamas Internship Overview: Global Mamas is a 12-year-old NGO that began with six women and know impacts almost 600 Ghanaian women! My volunteerism/internship with Global Mamas involves me teaching IT/computer skills to the Mamas, marketing their products, storytelling their brand, and helping them achieve prosperity!

Ghana Research Overview: This study on “Effects of Fair Trade Entrepreneurship” aims to research the role of fair trade entrepreneurship in helping female Ghanaian fair trade entrepreneurs achieve financial security. This study contributes to larger body of research on the feminization of poverty. The feminization of poverty describes a phenomenon in which women represent disproportionate percentages of the world's poor. UNIFEM describes it as "the burden of poverty borne by women, especially in developing countries." 

According to the Rural Poverty Portal, over 25 percent of Ghanaians live in poverty, and the majority are women. It is the goal of my research to understand how fair trade entrepreneurship impacts the financial well-being of Ghanaian female fair trade entrepreneurs. The study utilizes ethnographic research methods including literature review and interviews. The interviews are conducted in the shops and homes of female Ghanaian fair trade entrepreneurs, as well as in buildings that facilitate their entrepreneurial pursuits. The anonymous information collected from the study will be summarized into a report in order to provide insights and advice for the entrepreneurship discipline at the University of Notre Dame. The study will also serve to prepare the researcher (me!) for full-scale research in the future.


LINKS:
My website - http://petefreeman.com
CUSE's website: https://cuse.nd.edu/
FYS's website: http://firstyear.nd.edu/

--
Pete Freeman is a Lilly Scholar from the great state of Indiana. Discover Pete's social media consulting company, nonprofit and more at http://petefreeman.com

items.title: Ghana launches drinks-can sized model of satellite
items.description:
AP Television
Koforidua - 14 May 2013
1. Various of students preparing balloon to carry out test launch of model satellite  
2. Various of Manfred Quarshie, Director of Space Intelligent Systems Laboratory (ISSL), speaking 
3. SOUNDBITE: (English) Manfred Quarshie, Director of Space Intelligent Systems Laboratory (ISSL), All Nations University College:
"As Ghanians we have not really dealt into reaping the full benefit of satellite technology. So we actually as a lab, as a university, thought to go into it will actually help the society in other aspect to be able to really reap the benefit of satellite technology." 
4. High shot of Koforidua skyline, telecommunications masts on hill in background
AP Television
Koforidua - 15 May 2013
5. Various of vehicles and people in street
6. Close-up of Ghanian flag 
7. Wide exterior shot of All Nations University College
8. Wide of woman standing near banner reading: (English) "Deployable CanSat"
9. Mid of students checking model satellite attached to balloon
10. Various of model satellite components 
11. Wide of model satellite being raised into air on balloon 
12. Wide of local officials and school administrators looking on
13. Wide of balloon in air
14. Wide of man catching model as falls to ground on parachute
15. Wide of students looking at balloon 
16. Close-up of screen showing data received from model satellite
17. SOUNDBITE: (English) Benjamin Bonsu, Project manager, Space Intelligent Systems Laboratory (ISSL), All Nations University College:
"You know it wasn't easy at all, sometimes you call people here and there, sometimes you face those challenges but at the end we were able to get the data during the launching of the miniaturised satellite that is the CanSat."
18. Wide of balloon in rain soaked field 
19. Various of rain water being released from roof of tent area
20. Various of Emanuel Oti Boateng, Chancellor of All Nations University
21. SOUNDBITE: (English) Emanuel Oti Boateng, Chancellor of All Nations University:
"Without data society can not move. You know we have floods and so forth. If you take disaster risk reduction, the satellite will collect data about flooding and so on and then give us the early warning systems which will help us in other to minimise the disaster risk and this is very important."
22. Wide of balloon in field area
23. Mid of Boateng addressing assembled crowd 
24. SOUNDBITE: (English) Emanuel Oti Boateng, Chancellor of All Nations University :
"Where the mosquitoes are hiding and so forth we can get them and then break the pathway of the disease transmission, helping in the disease profile. So the satellite data processing and data collection they are all conjoined."  
25. Student wearing T-shirt reading: (English) "Exploring the beauty of space"
26. Wide of model space rockets on display in front of stand 
27. Close-up of components and person using laptop computer
AP Television
Koforidua - 14 May 2013
28. SOUNDBITE: (English) Manfred Quarshie, Director of Space Intelligent Systems Laboratory (ISSL), All Nations University College:
"We are actually looking at sophisticated equipment for our laboratory. Currently we don't have much of the equipment that we need within, to be able to work and work effectively. So that is one of the main challenges that we are actually, the challenge that we are currently facing within the laboratory."
29. Various of students preparing balloon 
30. Wide of balloon in sky
LEADIN 
It seems the sky is the limit for students at a university in Ghana.
They are involved in a nascent space programme, which they hope will eventually lead to the launch of satellites. 
Organisers think the technology could help tackle things like health problems and natural disasters.
STORYLINE

items.title: President VladimirPutin to add 40 ballistic missiles to nuclear arsenal /NATO denounces
items.description:
President VladimirPutin to add 40 ballistic missiles to nuclear arsenal /NATO denounces  'saber-rattling'
President VladimirPutin to add 40 ballistic missiles to nuclear arsenal /NATO denounces  'saber-rattling'
President VladimirPutin to add 40 ballistic missiles to nuclear arsenal /NATO denounces  'saber-rattling' |Devid news
KUBINKA, Russia (Reuters) - President Vladimir Putin said on Tuesday that Russia was concerned about an anti-missile defense system near its borders, after announcing that Russia would add more than 40 intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBM) to its nuclear arsenal this year.

"We will be forced to aim our armed forces ... at those territories from where the threat comes," Putin said.

Putin made his comments a day after Russian officials denounced a U.S. plan to station tanks and heavy weapons in NATO member states on Russia's border. Putin said it was the most aggressive act by Washington since the Cold War a generation ago.

U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry expressed concern over Putin's missile announcement and said no one wanted to see backsliding "to a kind of a Cold War status."

Thank you for supporting the creative commons movement !!

The permafrost is the layer of ice permanently on the surface levels of the floor of the very cold regions or glacial, such as the tundra. It can be found in circumpolar areas of Canada, Alaska, Siberia, Tibet, Norway and in several islands of the Atlantic Ocean south as South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands. We have also found this phenomenon on the surface of Mars. Permafrost can be divided into permafrost, the frozen layer deeper, outermost layer usually thaw. For hundreds of thousands of years, the Arctic permafrost has accumulated large reserves of organic carbon.

Permafrost form where the annual average temperature is -1 ° C and the annual precipitation does not exceed 1000 mm. Thus, the large permafrost areas in the world are in the polar regions to the Arctic and Antarctic tundra, in large parts of the boreal forest areas, but also in all areas which meet the conditions for permafrost, such as high mountains. As permafrost zone is called "the circumpolar region eternal frozen ground, the tundra of northern continents, the large forest areas and offshore areas of the seabed.

Geographically, there are large parts of northern Canada, Alaska, Greenland and Eastern Siberia. Approximately 20 to 25% of the land area of the earth is permafrost, and Greenland to 99%, Alaska at 80%, Russia 50%, Canada up to 20% are 40 to 50% and China from permafrost. Permafrost areas is also available in high mountain regions such as the Alps. You are the last ice age, when the ground froze places up in several 1000 meters depth. In addition to these fossil permafrost areas in the Alps will take place today - albeit very limited - even recent permafrost formation instead.

In addition, there are also submarine permafrost, so permafrost at the bottom of the seas. By density anomaly of the water actually physically impossible to explain this as follows: by the static sea level variation in the last ice age were many continental shelves, which are now back under water, above sea level, making the soil up to several 100 meters depth were able to develop permafrost. 

In the wake of global warming a northward migration in recent decades has been the permafrost in North America and to a lesser extent in Eurasia observed. The consequences are damage to roads and houses, now where the permafrost thaws only on morass stand. Moreover, in this case in permafrost-bound large amounts of methane into the atmosphere from escaping. This process would be a strengthening of the warming since the global warming potential of methane is about 25 times as large as that of CO 2.

The thawing of permafrost makes short term and locally for already significant and threatening changes in topography. In areas with permafrost therefore buildings are built primarily on stilts that reach down into the permanently frozen areas of the soil and thus stand on firm ground. A geothermal -use heat pump heating can cause an artificial permafrost if the withdrawn heat energy can no longer be adequately replenished by the environment. In this case forms around the heat exchanger coils in the ground a block of frozen ground, which significantly reduces the heating power.

The layer or thaws and freezes again, the active layer mentioned. In the active layer can grow plants in the permafrost layer is not. The thickness of the active layer depends on the weather and changes with the years, but it is usually between 60 and 360 cm. The thickness of the permafrost could amount to tens of meters (at Barrow in Alaska was once measured more than 400 meters). Except to the mainland, permafrost also for Antarctic and Arctic islands like Bouvet Island.

A major city that is built on the permafrost is the Russian city Yakutsk in northeastern Siberia with more than 200,000 inhabitants. The average annual temperature is around -9. The permafrost layer is according to locally obtained data (the Permafrost Institute, July 2010) is approximately 300 meters thick.

Measurement of the depth and extension of the permafrost could be a clue to study the greenhouse effect can be and in recent times (1999 and 2001) records are established for the thawing of permafrost in Alaska and Siberia. Accurate data, however, collected only since circa 1970, so that no final conclusions can be drawn.

items.title: Centcom, Russian reax as diplomats come under fire during Baghdad evacuation
items.description:
APTN
Moscow, Russia -  April 6, 2003
1. Exteriors Ministry of Foreign Affairs building  
2. US Ambassador Alexander Vershbow leaving the building 
3. Cutaway Ministry of Foreign Affairs sign
4. SOUNDBITE (English) Alexander Vershbow, US Ambassador to Russia: 
"We still are gathering the information about the incident that took place a few hours ago. We are obviously very concerned about those who have been wounded. We still do not know which forces were involved, we don't know anything about the circumstances of the incident, but I undertook to get more information from our commanders and to share immediately with the minister, with the Russian government."      
5. Cutaway press
6. SOUNDBITE (English) Alexander Vershbow, US Ambassador to Russia: 
"It is very difficult situation, it is a war zone. We did coordinate with the Russian side on this departure but Iraqi forces are active and there are many military exchanges  going on but we will do as much as we can to facilitate their safe departure."
7. Vershbow gets into his limo, leaving

POOL
Central Command
Doha, Qatar -  April 6, 2003
8. Wide shot CENTCOM briefing
9. Mid shot  reporter asking a question
10. SOUNDBITE (English) Brigadier General Vincent Brooks, deputy director of operations:
"We have some initial reports from are embassy in Russia that there may have been some sort of accident that occurred with respect to that set of vehicles leaving Iraq. We were aware of them leaving Iraq, we certainly had information about that and  an anticipation of how they might move and with that  we wanted to ensure were providing as much protection as we could.  We don't know the circumstances surrounding this or even the factual basis of it yet, we understand they are still moving at this point in time and as we get more information, we absolutely want to get to the bottom of  that particualry report. We don't have any specifics yet. We understand that this group of vehicles is still moving."

APTN File. 
Baghdad -  Recent
11. Exteriors of Russian embassy

STORYLINE:

A convoy of Russian diplomats, including the ambassador to Iraq, came under fire on Sunday as they were evacuating from Baghdad, the Kremlin said. 

The vehicles came under fire as they were moving towards the Syrian border and several people were wounded, said the Russian Foreign Ministry.

Russian officials had long ago evacuated most of the embassy's staff, but a core team had remained until Sunday, including the ambassador.

President Vladimir Putin has been informed about the incident, the Kremlin press service said.

The Foreign Ministry said it urgently called in the U.S. and Iraqi ambassadors and asked them to take all measures necessary to guarantee Russian citizens' safety in Iraq, to investigate the circumstances of the attack and punish those responsible.

The ministry said there were wounded but had no information on how many. 

As he left the Foreign Ministry building, Ambassador Alexander Vershbow said the U.S. government was investigating the incident and trying to gather information from allied commanders in the area. He said the U.S. side would do its best to expedite the diplomats' evacuation.

Vershbow confirmed that the United States had been aware of the planned evacuation ahead of time.

At Central Command, Vincent Brooks, deputy director of operations, said details were unclear but they wanted to, "absolutely get to the bottom" of the reports.

On Wednesday, Russia protested against American airstrikes that allegedly targeted a Baghdad neighbourhood where the Russian Embassy was located. Russia did not report any casualties in connection with the strikes.

items.title: Russia-How Kremlin's Special Soldiers Are Trained
items.description:
T/I 10:21:14


HOW KREMLIN'S SPECIAL SOLDIERS ARE TRAINED

Russia          Natural Sound          Duration: 2.08"

The Tamanskaya special division of the Russian army, the Kremlin's
own crack forces, recently opened its doors for a rare glimpse of
its military training exercises. Located 60 kilometers west of
Moscow, the Tamanskaya division has some of the best-trained and
best-equipped troops in the Russian armed forces. Other army
divisions have to cope with shortages of coal, food, bullets and
other crucial supplies, but the Tamanskaya troops are relatively
well off. The Tamanskaya division is known for being an arm of the
government. More than once it has come to the Kremlin's rescue.
During the August 1991 attempt to overthrow Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, Tamanskaya troops surrounded Russia's White House in
Moscow in a symbolic move to demonstrate their loyalty. They were
called into Moscow again in October 1993 and refused to use their
weapons to bring down President Boris Yeltsin. Public attention is
once again turning to the Tamanskaya division in view of the
approaching presidential elections in June. There is speculation
that Yeltsin might call off the election if his chances of
emerging victorious appear threatened. Should the opposition
decide to challenge a cancellation, the Tamanskaya division would
likely play a crucial role.


SHOWS: 

(RUSSIA) 

Snow-covered military training field west of Moscow. Army tanks rolling by. Tank. Young Russian soldiers in the Tamanskaya division during training exercises. Anti-aircraft weapon. Artillery fire. Army officers gathered at command point.
Tank firing its cannon. Soldier firing a rocket-propelled grenade.
Soldier running up to gun, throwing himself flat on ground and
firing his weapon. Pan across field to distant explosion. Exchange
of gunfire. Explosion across field. Officers gathered under tent
at command point. Commander Vyacheslav Borisov giving orders over
short wave radio. Explosions. Tank. Soldiers standing in line.
Young soldier's face. SOT Commander Borisov in Russia, saying
"We're going to capitalise on our experience in Chechnya and also
Afghanistan to create a new, special, mobile force. We're
currently working on special preparations and military exercises
for this programme."

items.title: Russia - KGB Agents
items.description:
T/I: 10:31:15

KGB AGENTS FIND NEW ROLE IN LIFE - AND DEATH   

Russia                   Natsot                 Duration: 3.22"   

Crime and assassination have turned the Russia's bodyguard industry into big business. Over the past three years several Russian bank managers, businessmen, deputies and journalists have been murdered. Not only stars or politicians need a bodyguard, but businessmen as well. One of the Western clients is Frank M. Brentnell, president of The American Russian Foundation. He admitted that for him security was one of the most important issues when in Moscow. Recently, Moscow bodyguards were able to demonstrate their skill in a special contest to determine the "best bodyguard". Women are also muscling into the market and they are working on a new concept, the "secretary-bodyguard". Even veteran Soviet spies from the KGB have redefined themselves in the security business.   

SHOWS:

I believe by having a controlled place you solve your problem and I don't have time to fly by the seat of my pants not to have security, it's a must." items.title: Russia - New Oil Spill Near Usinsk
items.description:
A major new oil spill has occurred in an area of northern Russia
already polluted by a large oil leak several months ago, the
environmental group Greenpeace said on Sunday (6/11). Greenpeace
 said a ruptured oil pipeline near the town of Usinsk in the
Komi region, 1,600 km (1,000 miles) northeast of Moscow, has
spilled at least 13,000 tons (3.8 million gallons) of oil since
Thursday.  Lakes of burning oil 60 cm (24 inches) deep are flowing into a stream almost two metres (4.4 feet) deep and black smoke filled the sky.

items.title: Army RUSSIA
items.description:
►►► Russian Troops on FULL ALERT ◄◄◄
READY for BIGGEST MILITARY DRILL "Troops on FULL ALERT" | Defense |
"Russian Army Goes East With BIGGEST 2014 WAR DRILL"

MOSCOW, November 30, 2013 

The Russian military will hold its biggest drill of 2014 in the country's east, First Deputy Defense Minister Arkady Bakhin said Saturday.

The East-2014 exercise will involve several army branches, Bakhin said on Ekho Moskvy radio.

He did not elaborate on the program or the exact time and venue for the event.

This year's biggest drill, West-2013, took place in the Russian western exclave of Kaliningrad and the neighboring Belarus, Russia's major European ally.

The Russian army held about 3,000 drills in 2013, including some 400 involving multiple army branches, Bakhin said.

Russia has 29 international military exercises lined up for next year, Bakhin also said.

Moscow announced last week plans to hold joint drills with China and Mongolia in 2014.


•••

& Russia Plans to Have 4 'Massive' Military Training Ranges...

Each of Russia's four military districts will have its own training range capable of hosting large-scale exercises involving all branches of the armed forces, a senior defense official said Saturday.

First Deputy Defense Minister, Gen. Arkady Bakhin, said in an interview with Echo Moskvy radio that the first such training range, dubbed Mulino, is being constructed in the Nizhny Novgorod region for the Western Military District.

According to Bakhin, construction of the Mulino training range is expected to be completed in summer next year.

"A contract for the construction of the second range, based on the Ashuluk training facility in the Southern Military District, has been signed," Bakhin said.

Its size and advanced equipment will allow the Defense Ministry to train and inspect combat capabilities of large military units, including entire armies, the official said.

The third training range will be built near the town of Tsugol in Siberia for the Eastern Military District, while the site for the training facility in the Central Military District has not yet been determined, the general said.

items.title: Britain, France sign deal to step up joint security operations at Eurotunnel
items.description:
Britain and France announced new measures on Thursday (August 20) to prevent undocumented migrants entering the Channel Tunnel, while stepping up joint police operations against the people-smugglers who profit from their desperation to reach Britain.

Both countries will contribute police resources to a shared "command and control" centre in the northern French port city of Calais, Britain's Home Office said in a statement.

The new joint command will "find and disrupt organised criminals who attempt to smuggle migrants into northern France and across the Channel", it said.

For Britain and France, Calais is the focus of a wider migration crisis fuelled by conflict, persecution and poverty that has sent hundreds of thousands out of Syria, Libya and other Middle Eastern and African states.

Tens of thousands of migrants are arriving in Italy and Greece each week, while Germany expects the number of asylum applications to quadruple to a record 800,000 this year, the government said on Wednesday.

Thousands of migrants are holed up in makeshift encampments in Calais, with many trying each night to jump onto trucks or trains, or even walk the 31-mile (50-km) undersea tunnel to Britain. Some are killed in the attempt.

Led by senior French and British police commanders, the new centre will report to both interior ministers.

New measures include increased French police numbers and British-funded fencing, CCTV and other security equipment to protect the tunnel entrance in Calais, the Home Office said.

Operator Eurotunnel (GETP.PA) will receive unspecified "support" to deploy more security guards at the site, it added.

The growing refugee crisis will also feature in talks between French President Francois Hollande and German Chancellor Angela Merkel on Monday, as southern European states bearing the brunt of the influx press for a concerted EU-wide response.

France wants to set up processing centres for speedier treatment of asylum applications at Europe's main entry points and use development policy to enlist better cooperation from transit countries, Fabius said.

items.title: Suspected grenade thrower caught on camera in Kiev
items.description:
Footage released by Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty on Monday (August 31) appears to show a suspect hurling a grenade which killed one and injured nearly 90 outside Ukraine's parliament.

A Ukrainian national guardsman died on Monday (August 31) during violent protests outside parliament in Kiev, as lawmakers voted to give more autonomy to rebel-held areas in the east of the country.

Interior Minister Arsen Avakov said in a tweet that nearly 90 national guardsmen had been hurt, four of them with serious wounds to the eyes, stomach, neck and legs, by several explosive devices that were lobbed at them from crowds massed outside.

National guardsmen and police officers were seen attending to the wounded amid clouds of tear gas. Puddles of blood and discarded equipment were strewn on the ground.

The violence came after the deputies voted by 265 in favour of the first reading of the bill - 39 more than that required to pass - at a boisterous session with many deputies shouting "Shame!" and rhythmically beating parliamentary benches.

Shamanism is based on the premise that the visible world is pervaded by invisible forces or spirits that affect the lives of the living. Unlike organized religions such as animism or animatism that are led by pastors and that all members of a society practice, shamanism requires individualized knowledge and special abilities. Shamans act outside established religions, and traditionally act alone. Shamans can come together in associations, as have practitioners Tantric Indians.

According to Kehoe, Eliade Shamanism is an invention synthesized from various sources unsupported by any direct research. Believes that what he and other scholars define as characteristic of shamanism, trances, chants, communication with spirits, cures, are practices that exist in shamanic cultures do not like some Judeo-Christian rituals. Just as shamanism itself, music and songs related to it in various cultures are diverse, far from being similar. In some cultures and in some cases, some songs related to shamanism also try to imitate natural sounds, sometimes through onomatopoeia.

Shamanism is considered by some to be the history of all organized religions, since it was born before the Neolithic. The pagan Greek was influenced by shamanism, as reflected in the stories of Tantalus, Prometheus, Medea and Calipso among others, as well as the mysteries, like those of Eleusis. Some of the shamanic practices of the Greek religion were copied later by religion of Romans.

Today, shamanism survives mainly in indigenous peoples. His practice continues in the tundras, jungles, deserts and other rural areas, and also in cities, towns, suburbs, and villages around the world. It is particularly widespread in Africa, and also in South America, where there is called "shamanism mestizo ".

items.title: Russian helicopter crashed, 15 people killed in Siberia
items.description:
Fifteen people were killed in Russia on Thursday
when a civilian helicopter crashed in Siberia,
regional authorities said.
The Mi-8 helicopter, which was transporting 22
passengers and four crew members, crashed
outside the town of Igarka in Western Siberia,
some 2,800 kilometres (1,750 miles) northeast of
Moscow.
"Fifteen people were killed and 10 people were
hospitalised as a result of the crash," regional
transportation authorities said in a statement.
Contact with the helicopter -- which was headed to
an oil pumping station -- was lost just after 0400
GMT, some 15 minutes after takeoff from Igarka
airport, authorities said.
The regional branch of the emergencies ministry
said the helicopter had performed an emergency
landing but did not elaborate on what might have
caused the crash.
Prosecutors said they would investigate possible
safety violations.

items.title: Tropical Storm Bill Charges Across Texas and Weakens
items.description:
For more WORLD NEWS "SUBSCRIBE" US

HOUSTON:  Tropical Storm Bill headed further into central Texas with heavy rains and high winds today before losing its punch and no serious injuries were reported, relieving officials and residents just three weeks after floods killed about 30 people in the state.

The National Hurricane Center said the storm had weakened into a tropical depression.

The second named tropical storm of the 2015 Atlantic hurricane season made landfall on Tuesday near the sportfishing town of Matagorda, then lost much of its power, the US National Weather Service said.

There were no reports of substantial damage, and oilfields in the Gulf of Mexico and near the coast were not impacted by the storm.

Refineries and a nuclear power plant, the South Texas Nuclear Generating Station in Bay City, also operated normally.

But about 300 flights were canceled at the two airports serving Houston, the fourth-largest US city, according to tracking service FlightAware.com. Vessel traffic was also halted in the HoustonShip Channel, the waterway to the biggest US petrochemical port, and the ports of Galveston and Texas City.

items.title: Residents begin to return to Houston following hurricane
items.description:
1. Various of highway with little traffic on it
2. Various of drivers filling cars up at petrol station
3. Various of buses in central Houston
4. Family putting belongings into their car
5. SOUNDBITE: (English) Denitria Meluise, Evacuee from Houston:
"We're packing up, heading home.
Q. Why?
A. Why, it's over,my house is safe, my kids are safe, we just need to go East Texas near Jackson, where my grandmother lives and check on her."
6. Wide shot of downtown street
7. Various of church
8. SOUNDBITE:(English), Brian Solven, Resident
"I'm really happy everything going back to normal, it is a relief, everybody is panicking, but thank God, thank God, I have faith in God that the hurricane turned around the way around."
9. Various of people buying wood
10. Wide exterior of grocery store
11. Various shots of food at grocery store
12. Wide shot of flags
13. Man puts USA flag on fence

STORYLINE:

Residents have begun returning to Houston, Texas - relieved that their city did not take a direct hit from hurricane Rita.

Rita roared ashore early Saturday close to the Texas-Louisiana state line as a Category 3 hurricane with top winds of 120 mph and warnings of up to 25 inches of rain. By early Sunday, it was a tropical depression with top sustained winds of 20 mph located about 20 miles southeast of Hot Springs, Ark.

While Rita didn't match the destructive power of Hurricane Katrina, it still left a massive trail of destruction in Texas and Louisiana. 

The storm caused "tens of millions of dollars" in structural damage in the Houston area alone, Harris County Tax Collector-Assessor Paul Bettencourt estimated.

Still some residents are anxious to return to their homes.

Texas officials set up regions that would reopen to evacuees on Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, and Texas Governor Rick Perry urged Houston residents to respect the schedule laid out for an "orderly migration."

Commercial airline service to the city also resumed Sunday; many flights in were booked.

Houston Mayor Bill White, wanting to avoid the gridlock that occurred as people fled from Rita, asked gas station attendants, convenience store clerks and grocery store workers to come back quickly. "There is some fuel available in tankers, but they can't deliver it if you're not there," he said.

In some areas of Houston, workers heeded the mayor's advice returning to work at convenience stores and gas stations. 

KEYWORD - HURRICANE RITA

items.title: Firefighters gain ground against Texas wildfire; residents gear up for rebuild
items.description:
1. Pan of charred vehicles and rubble of building burnt in wildfire
2. Mid pan of burnt vehicles
3. Burnt bike on the ground, tilt up to rubble in distance 
4. Tilt up of vehicle wreckage
5. People checking bulletin boards for information about status of their homes
6. Close-up of structure loss sheet on bulletin board
7. SOUNDBITE: (English) Bill Kruger, lost his home in the wildfires
"Our house is not on the list. But, we know that it wasn''t good. We''ve got friends that were trying to put out hot spots and they''ve confirmed it, that there''s nothing there. But it''s not on the list. But that doesn''t give me no hope. It''s sad. It''s sad for everyone. I don''t feel sorry just for for myself. I feel sorry for everybody that this has happened to."
8. People checking fire information list
9. Lance Fosdick, who lost his home in the wildfires, checking information list
10. Close-up of woman clasping her hands
11. SOUNDBITE (English) Lance Fosdick, lost his home in the wildfires:
"Well, you know, kind of lost in space, I guess. Just wandering around waiting for something to happen. You know, it''s not a good feeling, I can tell you that. But like I said, now that we know, we know where we''ve got to go, what we''ve got to do. So, we''ll make it."
12. Women checking fire information list
13. SOUNDBITE: (English) Judge Ronnie McDonald, Bastrop County official:
"The weather has changed the last two days to give us a better opportunity to fight. Now, we''re gearing up for the weather to change again. So the firefighters are going in and trying to make sure that we are drawing and digging our lines, and making sure the fire is not spreading."
14. Close pan of structure loss sheets
STORYLINE:
As fire crews gain ground against one of the most destructive wildfires in Texas history, some residents of Bastrop county, who lost their houses to the flames, were gearing up on Wednesday to rebuild their homes.
The blaze has left at least two people dead, blackened about 45 square miles (116.55 square kilometres) around Bastrop and cast a haze over Austin, 25 miles (40 kilometres) to the west. 
The state reports the number of homes lost has reached almost 800. An elite team is searching the smoking ruins to see if there are more victims.
"Well, you know kind of lost in space, I guess," said Lance Fosdick, who lost his home in the wildfires. "Just wandering around waiting for something to happen. You know, it''s not a good feeling, I can tell you that."
Firefighters report that the flames are at least 30 percent contained after burning uncontrolled for three days.
"The weather has changed the last two days to give us a better opportunity to fight. Now, we''re gearing up for the weather to change again. So the firefighters are going in and trying to make sure that we are drawing and digging our lines, and making sure the fire is not spreading,"said Bastrop County Judge Ronnie McDonald. 
Local officials credit an easing of the winds from Tropical Storm Lee that had caused the fire to explode over the weekend. 
Still, thousands of Texans have been evacuated from Central Texas and forced to put their lives on hold, as they wait find out if their homes are still standing.
"Our house is not on the list. But, we know that it wasn''t good," said Bill Kruger. He and his wife lost their home in the wildfires.
"We''ve got friends that were trying to put out hot spots and they''ve confirmed it, that there''s nothing there," said Kruger. "It''s sad. It''s sad for everyone. I don''t feel sorry just for for myself. I feel sorry for everybody that this has happened to."
In addition to the two victims in the Bastrop area fire whose bodies were found Tuesday, the outbreak is blamed for two deaths elsewhere.

items.title: 2015 Lake Texoma Flood   104 Days at Lighthouse Marina
items.description: The following is a time-lapse video created over 104 days of the 2015 flood of Lake Texoma. This was filmed at Lighthouse Resort and Marina. On the 7th of May 2015, it started raining at Lake Texoma. At the time, the lake elevation was ~612' MSL, or about 3' below normal. It kept raining and raining. We saw the lake rise over 34' in less than 3 weeks.   Prior to this year, Lake Texoma has gone over the spillway (640' MSL) just 3 times since 1944... 1957, 1990, and again in 2007. This year (2015) we went over the spillway twice. We also broke the record for the highest lake elevation in history, which was 645.66 on the 1st of June 2015. Shortly thereafter the lake started to recede and we were on our way to recovery... we thought. Then Tropical Storm Bill headed our way from the Gulf of Mexico. It dumped torrential rain across our entire watershed. Lake Texoma began to rise again, and this time quickly. Some days the lake would come up over 2' in one day. That's a lot of water if you consider the size of Texoma, which is about 139 sq miles. We crested again on the 22nd of June after all the rains from T.D. Bill made its way into the lake. Finally, July and August weather cleared up and the lake worked its way back down to normal. As you can see in the video, the traffic on the lake significantly picks up as the water gets below 620' MSL. Thanks for watching, support Lake Texoma!

items.title: Firefighting Helicopter Water Pick-ups - "Lake Fire" - June, 2015
items.description:
To use this video in a commercial player or in broadcasts, please email licensing@storyful.com

Thursday, June 18, 2015

“Lake Fire” - San Bernardino National Forest. Near Angelus Oaks, California -- Approximately 70 miles east of Los Angeles.

Jenks Lake is near Angelus Oaks, CA and is only a short distance from the fire. Sikorsky Air Crane and Huey helicopters coordinated their water pick-ups in a precise air traffic pattern.

This footage was taken with a camera placed on the shore of the lake. I didn't want my presence to interfere with their operations or distract the flight crews. To do this, I placed my camera at the edge of the lake and would scramble up the steep hillside between arrivals. The intense rotor wash from the Sikorsky Air Crane helicopters blew away large amounts of water, sending a windy mist in every direction. My equipment was soaked -- the blurriness you see in the video is caused by water on the lens. It was an incredible experience!

Several days after filming this, air crews spotted commercially-available drones in the area. The incidents received a great deal of press attention, and brought to light important issues regarding public usage of drones.

I'm a freelance photographer based in Rancho Cucamonga, CA. You can view more of my work here:

items.title: Feature on California residents building near areas of high fire risk
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of burning homes
2. Halloween display in garden, surrounded by smoke
3. Pan from Walmart truck to evacuees waiting in a parking lot
4. SOUNDBITE: (English): Theresa Alamo, evacuee:
"We came up and rented a house until we could afford one and this is our very first house. We've been married 27 years, our first house, and this is how we are. We won't give it up, we'll stay."
5. Local with his dog and motorbike in van
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Gary Garrison, evacuee:
"When you live in the mountains, you put up with the danger of the fire because it's a small price or a small trade for very little crime, very good neighbours, being able to live and raise your children where you want." 
7. View of evacuee with her cat
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Merilee Bishop, evacuee:
"It's very scary, it's just my daughter and I. I have a son but it's not a good relationship right now but we are going to make it through. I've got my friends; I've got my daughter and I've got my animals and we have God on our side."
9. Various of fire
10. Fire officials talking
11. Pan of vehicles driving through smoke and haze
12. SOUNDBITE: (English) Bob Poole, United States Forrest Service:
"This is what we call a wind-driven event. The fire is being pushed by Santa Ana north winds. Right now we're in the town of Running Springs; we're at the southern tip of Running Springs. It appears at this point that the worse of the fire has pushed through but as you can see we still have a lot of active fire."
13. Various of firefighters battling fire
14. Various charred vehicle
15. Mid of burned barbecue grill
16. Charred car with small fire still burning in the foreground
STORYLINE:
As fires continue to rage throughout Southern California, officials in Running Springs say fire destroyed at least 1-hundred homes, leaving many residents uncertain about their future.
Four years ago, fire destroyed hundreds of homes in nearby Lake Arrowhead and also affected Running Springs.
Residents of the mountain resort community east of Los Angeles were evacuated last night to Highland, a town near San Bernadino.
About a dozen people turned a Walmart parking lot into a makeshift shelter, with the superstore giving out food and water to evacuees.
Despite the devastation, many vow to rebuild.
"This is our very first house. We've been married 27 years, our first house, and this is how we are. We won't give it up, we'll stay," local Theresa Alamo told AP Television.
"When you live in the mountains, you put up with the danger of the fire because it's a small price or small trade for very little crime, very good neighbours, being able to live and raise your children where you want," another local evacuee, Gary Garrison, said.
By day three, the dozen wildfires had burned more than 1,300 homes and businesses in Southern California, and the destruction may only be the start for the region. 
At least 346-thousand homes, roughly one in three, according to census data, were evacuated in San Diego County alone, sheriff's officials said. 
But the total number could be much higher, and state officials were still struggling to estimate how many people had fled.
Since they began on Sunday, the fires have burned at least 373,000 acres, or 583 square miles (1,510 sq. kilometres). 
Fully a quarter of the California coast was ablaze. 
Flames climbed halfway toward the Nevada line, chewing through chunks of seven counties and devastating numerous communities.
As the fires spread, most out of control, smaller blazes were merging into larger, more fearsome ones. 
Evacuations were being announced in one community after another as firefighters found themselves overwhelmed by gale-force Santa Ana winds, some gusting to 70 miles per hour (113 kilometres per hour).

items.title: Wildfires destroy homes, hundreds ordered to evacuate
items.description:
1. Wide of wild fire smoke cloud rising over Yucca Valley area
2. Medium of brush fires
3. Wide of fire fighters working along fire line 
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) Captain Barry Parker, Ventura County Fire Department:
"This terrain is very steep, it's very rocky, very dangerous. We're looking at high heats, very low humidity. When you couple these all up, you see what the affect is...and it's ultimately, you know, a fire that rages right now still out of control."
5. Close of brush fire in Pioneer Town 
6. Close of fire fighters fighting brushfire 
7. Wide of old Pioneer Town section (former Hollywood film set) 
8. Medium of Pioneer Town 
9. Medium of Pioneer Town structures 
10. Close of sign on building 
11. Wide of burned out area near Pioneer Town 
12. Wide of wild fire 
13. SOUNDBITE: (English) Daniel Polk, Morongo Valley resident.
"As my mom says, you should take your pets, people and your papers. So all-important documents, birth certificates, all stuff like that. We've got our two kennels with our cats, bring some cat food, and just throw a bunch of our clothes together in the back and bunch of pictures and stuff...that's the main thing."
14. Medium of wildfire 
15. Medium of burned out area and structure on desert property
STORYLINE:
Dark clouds of smoke hang over California's Yucca Valley as wildfires continue to rage across thousands of acres, leaving homes destroyed and hundreds of residents under orders to evacuate. 
Desert winds and blistering heat continued to challenge firefighters on Wednesday as they battled the wildfire some 100 miles (160 kilometres) east of Los Angeles. 
Officials said the blaze has scorched across 37-thousand acres of the desert area, destroying buildings and forcing hundreds of people to leave their homes. 
More than three-thousand fire fighters were on the line into the day on Wednesday, attacking the flames with back fires, trying to divert the flames away from structures. 
Heat, rough terrain and high winds continued to be a triple threat for fire fighters trying to get a handle on what officials said was the largest blaze currently in the state of California. 
Flare ups also were threatening communities like Pioneertown, a small community where flames swept through on Tuesday night.
Firefighters used picks and shovels against hotspots near Pioneertown, where the fire raged Tuesday.
But there was no damage to an historic area in Pioneertown dating to the 1940s when Hollywood cowboys establishing it as a filming site.
In nearby Morongo Valley, residents there on Wednesday were keeping an eye on smoke and flames on a nearby ridge. 
Homes in the area are surrounded by highly combustible greasewood, Joshua trees, and brush, and officials were asking residents in the area to prepare for evacuations if needed.
Officials worried that if the blaze continued to move toward the San Bernardino National Forest, it could grow rapidly, threatening the resort community in the area.

Extreme Lake Levels - Big Bear Lake presents the results of a 2003 geological study of the Prehistoric Environmental conditions in the Big Bear Lake valley, California.

items.title: Vista Sunrise Apartment Fire 11 5 2015 by Nicholas Snow
items.description: A car went up in flames in the parking lot of the Vista Sunrise Apartments in Palm Springs, California, in the early morning (around 2:40 a.m.) November 5th, 2015.  There are no known injuries or immediate visible damage to other cars or even the covered parking, as the car had been moved out into an open area. Nicholas Snow, who happens to be a journalist, resides in the complex, and from his second floor bedroom about 250 feet into the complex heard, "Someone call 911," which he did before throwing on clothes to shoot this video. items.title: Tile Roof Fontana CA, Call (626) 784-1100 SD Young's Roofing
items.description:
Tile Roof Fontana CA, Call (626) 784-1100 SD Young's Roofing

Considering a tile roof? As you may know the roof is the most important part of a building. There are many types of roofs for all types of climate and geographical conditions. Whatever the type or size or structure of the roof, as a roof system forms a very important part of a building. It not only protects the building against the weather and other conditions but also adds to the style and beauty of the house. Tile roofing is favoured by most people, as tiles are available in different colours and textures and is also easy to replace or repair.
Tile roof repair or tile roof replacement can be easily done whether you have a flat roof or a sloping roof. Its material can be ceramic or concrete cement. They are actually clay which is fired at a very high temperature. Sometimes cement concrete is added or cellulose is added to produce light or heavy type of tile roofing. Most people don't think of it as a clay roof.
Tile roofing is available in different type of colours and you could initiate a change in your house or your office by going for a tile roof replacement. You may be considering a color change from brown to charcoal or a brown blend. It not only gives your home or office a new outlook altogether but also protects your building from the snow, the rain, the heat etc.
Another advantage is that it allows more air circulation and keeps you cool during the hot summer season. They are also non combustible and provide you protection against fire. Tile roof replacement can be easily done and it is cost effective too. Tile roof repair involved hardly an hour and can be easily done by any worker.
This can also be done as an added protection from severe heat and cold. In some countries, either the heat is unbearable or the cold. This roofing would not only give the building a new look, but also protect you from the unbearable heat or cold and acts like a filter. Tile roof repair can be easily done instead of generic tile replacement if it is just a small crack thereby saving you money and time. You can mix some mortar and fill in your crack and just coat it with the tile colour paint from a list of colours that are available.

items.title: Aurora Borealis Over California and Nevada!
items.description:
Time-lapse video of the geomagnetic storm which reached earth early this morning, shot from California over the lights of Minden/Gardnerville, Nevada.  I went south to the Coleville/Walker area, mostly to get away from smoke form the 17,000-acre Washington fire. It would be more productive to move north, closer to the aurora, and east, further from city lights. The forecast for the next 3 nights indicates another solar storm: https://www.facebook.com/AuroraAlerts?fref=ts
Tonight and especially tomorrow night are the best of the three nights. The best (dark) viewing hours will get shorter and shorter each night as the moon stays up closer and closer to the oncoming light of morning twilight, around 3:40 am. 

Get away from city lights and look directly north. The aurora borealis may be happening 600 or more miles north, but 65 miles high, so look on the horizon from a place with a low horizon north, like a mountain top or large dry lake bed. (The Black Rock Desert for example would be a good place to view an aurora from.)

items.title: Nevada into California on US 395: Carson City, Topaz Lake
items.description:
This drive takes you from the Carson City area (Interstate 580) southbound through Gardnerville and Minden, then across the state line at Topaz Lake into California, past Walker, then ending somewhere along the road, when it got too dark to shoot.  

MyDrivelapse.com and Takemytrip.com provide driving videos and stories to help you plan your trip.  Check out hundreds of videos on my YouTube channel.  Subscribe if you like it!  Dozens of new videos are on the way in the coming weeks.

I made this trip in August, 2015.  Video shot with a Brinno TLC-200 Pro time-lapse camera, mounted on my roof with a homemade magnetic case.  I travel with two Brinno cameras - one facing forward, the other in reverse.  Sometimes the reverse camera captures better video (fewer raindrops and bugs hit the rear-view lens).
