items.title: Flood situation in Cox's Bazar improves (01-07-2015)
Millions driven from homes amidst monsoon flooding, AP pix
items.description:
1. Tracking shot of eastern edge of Dhaka where the most severe flooding is 
2. Flood victim Majid Mia and his family marooned in their house 
3. SOUNDBITE: (Bangla) Majid Mia, flood victim:
"I can't do anything now, everyday the water is rising four fingers in height, I've been staying at home, now the water is up to the chest in my house."  
4. Various of children with goat on bamboo platform inside the house 
5. Wide of flooded house 
6. Close-up of flood victim, Mohammad Mannan
7. SOUNDBITE: (Bangla) Majid Mia, flood victim:
"I don't know my future, whether I will live or die, I don't know how I will have money to eat tomorrow, I could die in this water." 
8. Tracking shot through flooded area
9. Mid of Saiful Hossain, executive engineer, Flood Forecasting Warning Centre (FFWC) Bangladesh 
10. Close-up of map dated August 4 showing flooded areas 
11. SOUNDBITE: (Bangla) Saiful Hossain, Executive engineer of the Flood Forecasting Warning Centre: 
"Because Dhaka has no protection on its eastern side, in the east there is saturation, there are problems, and this will continue for the next 24 to 48 hours." 
12. Various of Hossain
STORYLINE:
Seasonal flooding in Bangladesh has displaced (m) millions of people and at least 39 people had been killed over the weekend, bringing the country's overall death toll to 120, according to government figures on Sunday.
Raging floodwaters have battered 38 out of 64 districts in the Delta nation of 145 (m) million people.
Major rivers had started to recede in worst-hit eastern and central Bangladesh with monsoon rains weakening, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre (FFWC) said on Sunday in a bulletin from Dhaka, the Bangladesh capital.
But the low-lying areas around the nation's capital, were still under neck-deep water, and many residents were using boats to get around and others feared for their lives, with no respite for another two days.
Flood victim Mohammad Mannan told AP Television he did not know whether he was going to " live or die, I don't know how I will have money to eat tomorrow."
Majid Mia whose family and livestock had been forced to seek refuge on bamboo platforms said that "everyday the water is rising four fingers in height."
"I've been staying at home, now the water is up to the chest in my house. I can't do anything now," he added.
Saiful Hossain, a FFWC government forecaster said the flooding was "because Dhaka has no protection on its eastern side.
"In the east there is saturation, there are problems, and this will continue for the next 24 to 48 hours," he said. 
The head of Bangladesh's military-backed interim government, visited the northwestern district of Sirajganj on Saturday. 
Despite the devastation, he said the government had enough food and medicine to distribute and foreign assistance wasn't yet needed.
So far this year, some 14 (m) million people in India and five (m) million in Bangladesh have been displaced by flooding, according to government figures.
Flooding in neighbouring India has killed 240 people and driven 19 (m) million from their homes in recent days.
The South Asian monsoon season runs from June to September as the rains work their way across the subcontinent - a deluge that scatters floods and landslides across the region and kills hundreds of people every year.

"It is to save Dhaka's western areas from flooding that we have closed the sluice gates and are now pumping the water out of the city limits. This will also prevent the floodwaters from entering the city."

"The big challenge will now be to ensure food and water for all the displaced people who have sought temporary shelter and ensuring the public health aspects of these floods." 
15. Close of computer screen showing map of Bangladesh 


STORYLINE:

Seasonal flooding in Bangladesh has displaced (m) millions of people and at least 39 people had been killed over the weekend, bringing the country's overall death toll to 120, according to government figures on Sunday.

Raging floodwaters have battered 38 out of 64 districts in the Delta nation of more than 150 (m) million people.

Major rivers had started to recede in worst-hit eastern and central Bangladesh with monsoon rains weakening, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre (FFWC) said on Sunday in a bulletin from Dhaka, the Bangladesh capital.

Low-lying areas around Dhaka were under neck-deep water, and many residents were using boats to travel around.

In Dhaka on Sunday, authorities were pumping water from some parts of the city.

"It is to save Dhaka's western areas from flooding that we have closed the sluice gates and are now pumping the water out of the city limits. This will also prevent the floodwaters from entering the city," an engineer, AKM Shahiduddin, from Dhaka water department told AP Television. 

Farid Hassan Ahmed, who manages Bangladesh Oxfam's Rural Livelihoods and Disaster Risk Reduction programme, told AP Television the biggest challenge now was to provide food, water and medical attention for people living in temporary accommodation. 

Flooding has also devastated neighbouring India, killing 169 people in the past week.

Some 19 million people have been driven from their homes in the two countries in recent days.

The South Asian monsoon season runs from June to September as the rains work their way across the subcontinent - a deluge that scatters floods and landslides across the region and kills hundreds of people every year.

items.title: Former PM Hasina addresses large anti-govt protest
items.description:
1. Mid of Sheikh Hasina, Leader of a 19-party alliance, on rostrum surrounded by male supporters
2. Mid of Hasina sat with supporters
3. Wide of crowd
4. Close of Hasina sat looking at audience during rally
5. Cutaway to close of woman in crowd
6. Mid of crowd sat listening
7. Mid pan (right to left) of crowd listening to speeches
8. Mid pan (right to left) of crowd punching the air with fists during a speech
9. Mid of former Bangladeshi President, General Ershad addressing the crowd
10. Wide of crowd
11. Mid of Sheikh Hasina, leader of the grand alliance (Mohajote) declaring fresh protests in her address to the crowds
12. Wide of crowd
STORYLINE:
A key political alliance on Wednesday announced a series of fresh street protests to demand national elections be postponed, as tens of thousands of troops fanned out across Bangladesh ahead of the January 22 polls.
Sheikh Hasina, leader of a 19-party alliance, told a huge rally in the heart of the nation's capital that it would start non-stop demonstrations
around the presidential palace on January 14 and, enforce a nationwide blockade on January 14-15 and another on January 17-18 to force its demands.
Hasina accused the country's interim President Iajuddin Ahmed of bias toward former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, Hasina's archrival.
She asked Ahmed "not to be the part of a conspiracy" to rig the polls.
The latest protest plans came after a three-day nationwide transport blockade that ended on Tuesday and saw violent clashes between police and
demonstrators who want the polls postponed, citing alleged flaws in the voter list and other problems.
On Wednesday, about 60-thousand troops began spreading across the country to perform election duties and an Interior Ministry statement said the army had been empowered to make arrests without warrants anywhere, to ensure security during elections. 
Bangladesh has spent 15 years under military rule since gaining independence from Pakistan in 1971. 
Two of its presidents have been slain in military coups, and there have been 19 failed coup attempts.

items.title: REFUGEES ARRIVING IN BANGLADESH FROM MYANMAR
items.description:
The UN refugee agency said on Friday that Bangladesh was turning back boatloads of ethnic Rohingya Muslims fleeing violence in neighbouring Myanmar.
A spokesman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said there were "a number" of boats now adrift in the mouth of the Naf river.
Violence in western Myanmar between Buddhists and minority Muslims who call themselves Rohingyas has over the past week killed 29 people and inflicted similar damage on both of the contending ethnic communities, figures from local authorities showed on Thursday.
Among those who managed to slip into Bangladesh was 15-year-old Mamunur Rashid.
He said he was wounded by gunfire from Myanmar security forces.
Local villagers also said a group of Rohingya refugees who had taken shelter in the village had been detained by border guards.
This was confirmed by Lieutenant Colonel Zahid Hasan, Commanding Officer of 42nd Border Guard Battalion.
"Following intelligence reports, we have captured 18 Rohingyas last night. They had taken shelter at ModdhoMazer Para of Shapori Dip area. They had entered Bangladesh illegally on June 10."
Myanmar considers Rohingyas to be illegal immigrants from Bangladesh and denies them citizenship. 
Bangladesh says Rohingyas have been living in Myanmar for centuries and should be recognised there as citizens.
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Dipu Moni said on Tuesday that the impoverished country's resources already are strained.
The UN's refugee agency estimates that 800-thousand Rohingyas live in Myanmar's mountainous Rakhine state. 
Thousands attempt to flee every year to Bangladesh, Malaysia and elsewhere.
UN officials said on Friday that the agency was in contact with the Bangladesh government and hopes it will give the Rohingya refuge.
They said Myanmar officials estimate up to 30-thousand people could be fleeing the violence that has claimed several lives in recent days.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/43bf1cc0a630010e490aa0f47fa0473d 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Fears typhoon could wipe out IDP camps for muslims fleeing sectarian violence
items.description:
1. Mid of internally displaced (IDP) Rohingya Muslim, from the Thea Chaung camp, looking at anti riot police in front of the camp
2. Various of armed police in front of the camp
3. Tracking shot of IDPs and armed police
4. SOUNDBITE (Burmese) Khin Khin Thant, 42-year-old Rohingya IDP at Thea Chaung camp:
"The place that they want us to move to is at the edge of the village and there is no protection for us. That place is very dangerous and frightening to stay. In case of a cyclone that place can be flooded. Everything can be flooded."
5. Wide of Ohn Taw Rohingya IDP camp
6. Various of children inside the camp
7. SOUNDBITE (Burmese) Tun Win, 46-year-old IDP at Ohn Taw camp:
"We are worried that there is no protection for us here. The government has just announced that there will be a storm coming soon. But there is no support from them."
8. Various of IDPs inside the camp
9. Tracking shot of children playing
10. Various of people outside their tents
STORYLINE
Amid concerns about a possible disaster, Myanmar state television said on Monday that thousands of people displaced by communal violence last year have been evacuated from makeshift camps to safer ground ahead of a cyclone expected later this week.
Around 140-thousand people - mostly Rohingya - have been living in flimsy tents and makeshift shelters in the region after two outbreaks of Buddhist-Muslim violence there last year, according to the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs.
The report said authorities had moved 5,158 people from low-lying camps in the Rakhine state capital, Sittwe, to safer shelter. 
Ahead of the move, discussions over where to locate the Rohingya had been complicated by widespread anti-Muslim sentiment, which still runs high nearly a year after unrest between the areas ethnic Rakhine Buddhists and the Rohingya erupted in June 2012.
The violence has largely segregated Rakhine state along religious lines, with prominent Buddhists - including monks - urging people to boycott Muslim businesses. 
Tens of thousands of Rohingya have been confined to cramped camps, their movement heavily restricted. 
Unable to go home, most cannot work or attend school.
"The place that they want us to move to is at the edge of the village and there is no protection for us. That place is very dangerous and frightening to stay. In case of a cyclone that place can be flooded. Everything can be flooded," said 42-year-old Khin Khin Thant ahead of the move.
According to the report, displaced people were also moved in 10 other townships in western Myanmar. 
It did not give the number of people evacuated in those locations.
The United Nations estimates that nearly 70-thousand of those displaced are in low-lying areas along the coast that are highly susceptible to tidal surges and flooding.
In 2008, Cyclone Nargis killed more than 130-thousand people in Myanmar.
Cyclone Mahasen is expected to hit neighbouring Bangladesh on Thursday or Friday. 
Spillover rain could cause landslides and flooding in Myanmar.
Aid groups have issued warnings for weeks that annual monsoon rains could wreak havoc for displaced people in their camps and spark disease outbreaks.
"The government has been repeatedly warned to make appropriate arrangements for those displaced in Rakhine state. Now thousands of lives are at stake unless targeted action is taken immediately to assist those most at risk," Isabelle Arradon, Amnesty International's deputy Asia Pacific director, said in a statement on Monday.
The Rohingya have suffered discrimination for decades. 
Long viewed as illegal immigrants from Bangladesh, most are denied citizenship despite the fact that many have lived in Myanmar for generations.

Bangladesh, east of India on the Bay of Bengal, is South Asian country of lush greenery and many waterways. Its Padma (Ganges), Meghna and Jamuna rivers create fertile alluvial plains, and travel by boat is common. On the southern coast, the Sundarbans, an enormous mangrove forest shared with India, are home to the Royal Bengal tiger.

Capital: Dhaka
Dialing code: +880
Currency: Bangladeshi taka

"Language Movement" redirects here. For other uses, see Language movement (disambiguation).
 
he Bengali Language Movement, also known as the Language Movement (Bengali: ভাষা আন্দোলন Bhasha Andolôn), was a political movement in former East Bengal (today Bangladesh) advocating the recognition of the Bengali language as an official language of the then-Dominion of Pakistan in order to allow its use in government affairs, the continuation of its use as a medium of education, its use in media, currency and stamps, and to maintain its writing in the Bengali script.

When the Dominion of Pakistan was formed by the partition of India in 1947, it was composed of various ethnic and linguistic groups, with the geographically non-contiguous East Bengal province (that was renamed in 1956 as East Pakistan) having a mainly Bengali population. In 1948, the Government of the Dominion of Pakistan ordained Urdu as the sole national language, sparking extensive protests among the Bengali-speaking majority of East Bengal. Facing rising sectarian tensions and mass discontent with the new law, the government outlawed public meetings and rallies. The students of the University of Dhaka and other political activists defied the law and organised a protest on 21 February 1952. The movement reached its climax when police killed student demonstrators on that day. The deaths provoked widespread civil unrest. After years of conflict, the central government relented and granted official status to the Bengali language in 1956. In 1999, UNESCO declared 21 February as International Mother Language Day,[1] in tribute to the Language Movement and the ethno-linguistic rights of people around the world.

The Language Movement catalysed the assertion of Bengali national identity in East Bengal and later East Pakistan, and became a forerunner to Bengali nationalist movements, including the 6-Point Movement and subsequently the Bangladesh Liberation War and Indo-Pakistani War of 1971 in 1971. In Bangladesh, 21 February is observed as Language Movement Day, a national holiday. The Shaheed Minar monument was constructed near Dhaka Medical College in memory of the movement and its victims.



****************************************************
The Bangladesh Liberation War 1971[a] (Bengali: মুক্তিযুদ্ধ Muktijuddho), also known as the Bangladesh War of Independence, or simply the Liberation War in Bangladesh, was a revolution and armed conflict sparked by the rise of the Bengali nationalist and self-determination movement in East Pakistan and the 1971 Bangladesh genocide. It resulted in the independence of the People's Republic of Bangladesh. The war began after the Pakistani military junta based in West Pakistan launched Operation Searchlight against the people of East Pakistan on the night of 25 March 1971. It pursued the systematic elimination of nationalist Bengali civilians, students, intelligentsia, religious minorities and armed personnel. The junta annulled the results of the 1970 elections and arrested Prime Minister-elect Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.

Rural and urban areas across East Pakistan saw extensive military operations and air strikes to suppress the tide of civil disobedience that formed following the 1970 election stalemate. The Pakistan Army created radical religious militias - the Razakars, Al-Badr and Al-Shams- to assist it during raids on the local populace.[11][12] [13] Members of the Pakistani military and supporting militias engaged in mass murder, deportation and genocidal rape. The capital Dacca was the scene of numerous massacres, including the Dacca University killings. An estimated 10 million Bengali refugees fled to neighboring India, while 30 million were internally displaced.[14] Sectarian violence broke out between Bengalis and Urdu-speaking immigrants. An academic consensus prevails that the atrocities committed by the Pakistani military were a genocide.

Have More History, Search wikipedia ,,,,,,

"Language Movement" redirects here. For other uses, see Language movement (disambiguation).
 
he Bengali Language Movement, also known as the Language Movement (Bengali: ভাষা আন্দোলন Bhasha Andolôn), was a political movement in former East Bengal (today Bangladesh) advocating the recognition of the Bengali language as an official language of the then-Dominion of Pakistan in order to allow its use in government affairs, the continuation of its use as a medium of education, its use in media, currency and stamps, and to maintain its writing in the Bengali script.

When the Dominion of Pakistan was formed by the partition of India in 1947, it was composed of various ethnic and linguistic groups, with the geographically non-contiguous East Bengal province (that was renamed in 1956 as East Pakistan) having a mainly Bengali population. In 1948, the Government of the Dominion of Pakistan ordained Urdu as the sole national language, sparking extensive protests among the Bengali-speaking majority of East Bengal. Facing rising sectarian tensions and mass discontent with the new law, the government outlawed public meetings and rallies. The students of the University of Dhaka and other political activists defied the law and organised a protest on 21 February 1952. The movement reached its climax when police killed student demonstrators on that day. The deaths provoked widespread civil unrest. After years of conflict, the central government relented and granted official status to the Bengali language in 1956. In 1999, UNESCO declared 21 February as International Mother Language Day,[1] in tribute to the Language Movement and the ethno-linguistic rights of people around the world.

The Language Movement catalysed the assertion of Bengali national identity in East Bengal and later East Pakistan, and became a forerunner to Bengali nationalist movements, including the 6-Point Movement and subsequently the Bangladesh Liberation War and Indo-Pakistani War of 1971 in 1971. In Bangladesh, 21 February is observed as Language Movement Day, a national holiday. The Shaheed Minar monument was constructed near Dhaka Medical College in memory of the movement and its victims.



****************************************************
The Bangladesh Liberation War 1971[a] (Bengali: মুক্তিযুদ্ধ Muktijuddho), also known as the Bangladesh War of Independence, or simply the Liberation War in Bangladesh, was a revolution and armed conflict sparked by the rise of the Bengali nationalist and self-determination movement in East Pakistan and the 1971 Bangladesh genocide. It resulted in the independence of the People's Republic of Bangladesh. The war began after the Pakistani military junta based in West Pakistan launched Operation Searchlight against the people of East Pakistan on the night of 25 March 1971. It pursued the systematic elimination of nationalist Bengali civilians, students, intelligentsia, religious minorities and armed personnel. The junta annulled the results of the 1970 elections and arrested Prime Minister-elect Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.

Rural and urban areas across East Pakistan saw extensive military operations and air strikes to suppress the tide of civil disobedience that formed following the 1970 election stalemate. The Pakistan Army created radical religious militias - the Razakars, Al-Badr and Al-Shams- to assist it during raids on the local populace.[11][12] [13] Members of the Pakistani military and supporting militias engaged in mass murder, deportation and genocidal rape. The capital Dacca was the scene of numerous massacres, including the Dacca University killings. An estimated 10 million Bengali refugees fled to neighboring India, while 30 million were internally displaced.[14] Sectarian violence broke out between Bengalis and Urdu-speaking immigrants. An academic consensus prevails that the atrocities committed by the Pakistani military were a genocide.

items.title: AP coverage, standoff at Russian Embassy ends as man surrenders
items.description:
1. Exterior of the Russian embassy with police special forces (while hostage situation continued)
2. Various of police special forces and Red Cross personnel in front of embassy
3. Hostage taker Roman Bogdanyants and another man being escorted out of the embassy by police
4. SOUNDBITE: (Spanish) Allan Fonseca, spokesman for the investigation team, Costa Rican police
"I was instructed to inform you that, thank God, everything ended well. The negotiations gave good results and the perpetrator gave himself up. My superiors will be providing more details."
5. Pushing and shoving between press and police in front of the embassy  
6. Exterior embassy
7. Various of police in front of embassy
8. Car driving away with Bogdanyants and the other man
9. Arrival of Bogdanyants at the police station
10. Window of room where Bogdanyants being questioned by police 
STORYLINE:
A 20-year-old Kazakhstan native turned himself over to police on Friday, ending a three-hour standoff and safely releasing a man he had been holding at the Russian Embassy in San Jose, capital of Costa Rica, police said. 
Roman Bogdanyants covered his face as he was escorted by police from the building, followed by a Russian man that police spokesman Francisco Ruiz identified as the released hostage. 
Officials originally reported an armed gunman had seized eight hostages, quickly releasing five. 
But Russian Ambassador Valery Nikolayenko told Channel 7 Telenoticias in a phone interview during the standoff that he and three other officials had remained in the building to help negotiate a peaceful end to the conflict. 
Bogdanyants was taken to a cell in a San Jose courthouse, where he was being held late on Friday. 
Prosecutors were investigating what charges would be filed against him. 
According to a immigration spokesperson the Bogdanyants arrived in Costa Rica in 2005. 
Police earlier had described him as an Uzbek. 
A Bogdanyants family friend told Channel 7 Telenoticias how the Bogdanyants family had sold up everything in Russia to come to Costa Rica and start a new life, but they had been swindled by a Russian citizen and lost a lot of money.
It appeared that this was the provocation for the hostage taking, but further exact details were not available.

items.title: Leaders meet to commemorate signing of peace pacts 20 years ago
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Wide, San Jose
2. Costa Rica flag 
3. Summit venue, "Children's Museum"
4. Pull out, from leaders entering conference room and sitting down at table
5. Tracking shot of man handing out programmes
6. Conference room
7. Conference table with (left to right) Presidents Oscar Arias (Costa Rica), Oscar Berger, (Guatemala) and Martin Torrijos Espino (Panama)
8. SOUDNBITE: (Spanish) Oscar Arias, President of Costa Rica:
"This meeting that brings us here today is strange and also blessed because we didn't come here to celebrate one country's victory over another one, or one armed group over another one. We do not come to celebrate the annihilation of the enemy nor the destruction of a rival. This is not a commemoration of victory in the battlefield because in Central America no-one won the war. We beat the war."
9.  Berger and Torrijos listening
10. Medium shot of Manuel Zelaya, President of Honduras
11. Various wide shots of conference
12. Arias listening
STORYLINE
The presidents of five Central American countries met on Wednesday in the Costa Rica capital San Jose to celebrate the 20th anniversary of the Esquipulas II Peace Plan, which put an end to the civil wars that tore through the region two decades ago.
Costa Rican President Oscar Arias hosted the event, along with his counterparts Martin Torrijos (Panama), Oscar Berger (Guatemala), Manuel Zelaya (Honduras) and Antonio Saca (El Salvador).  
The presidents remembered the anniversary of the peace plan which allowed the beginning of negotiations to end the bloody military conflicts in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala that left over 300,000 dead.
The peace plan, which was named after the Guatemalan city of Esquipulas, comprised three basic principles: the end of the wars, a commitment to democracy and free elections, and economic development.
Arias, who was president at the time the agreement was signed, emphasised the importance of the peace plan.
"We do not come to celebrate the annihilation of the enemy nor the destruction of a rival. This is not a commemoration of victory in the battlefield because in Central America no-one won the war. We beat the war," he said.
Nicaraguan president Daniel Ortega was the only leader from the region not to attend Wednesday's meeting.
Arias and Ortega have remained distant in recent years and have not met since Ortega assumed power in Nicaragua in January of this year.

items.title: Plan to close country's two public zoos after demands by  animal rights groups
items.description:
SHOTLIST
AP TELEVISION
1. Close of scarlet macaw (South American parrot)
2. Wide of two scarlet macaw parrots
3. Wide exterior of Simon Bolivar zoo in central San Jose
4. Mid of family looking at animals inside the zoo 
5. Close of monkeys
6. Wide of monkey habitat 
7. Close of coati
8. Mid of moving crocodile
9. Mid of turtles near water
10. Wide of environment ministry exterior
11. Wide of Environment Vice Minister Lorena Guevara in her office 
12. SOUNDBITE: (Spanish) Environment Vice Minister Lorena Guevara:
"Animals in captivity, for us, are those that for health reasons, or because they have been abandoned by their parents or separated from them by humans, or because they've suffered injuries or have special circumstances, are required to be in captivity."
13. Mid of jaguar
14. Close of snake
15. Mid of zookeeper cleaning the inside of a cage with a hose
16. Wide of woman preparing meals for the animals 
17. Mid of back of lion
18. Pan left of tapir walking inside its cage
19. SOUNDBITE: (Spanish) Randal Arguedas, Vet at the zoo:
"We do not have more animals than (the available) suitable space. The smaller cages are being renovated and are being made bigger. The park is cleaned daily. The animals are fed every day. The park has a nutritionist, a veterinarian and biologists."
20. Close up of sleeping coati
21. Wide of entrance to tropical plant house
22. Close up of snake's head 
STORYLINE
In an unprecedented move, Costa Rica said it plans to close its public zoos so that animals can be freed from their cages. 
Costa Rica, which has longed focused on protecting its biodiversity, has said the zoos will close in 2014. 
The 97-year-old Simon Bolivar zoo in central San Jose will become a botanical park, the Environment Ministry said. 
"Animals in captivity, for us, are those that for health reasons, or because they have been abandoned by their parents or separated from them by humans, or because they've suffered injuries or have special circumstances, are required to be in captivity." said environment vice-minister Lorena Guevara.
Animals not healthy enough to be released into the wild will be sent to rescue centres.
According to the Environment Ministry, another zoo west of the city, the Santa Ana Conservation Centre, will be closed down as well. 
Together they hold 400 animals of 60 species, including a lion, crocodiles, monkeys and a tapir.
But the foundation that runs the animal parks say they will fight to keep them operating. 
Fundazoo has asked an administrative tribunal to block the closure, arguing that it has a contract to run the zoos through 2024. 
Randal Arguedas, a vet at the zoo, says the animals are already well cared for at their facility.  
"We do not have more animals than (the available) suitable space. The smaller cages are being renovated and are being made bigger. The park is cleaned daily. The animals are fed every day. The park has a nutritionist, a veterinarian and biologists," he said.
Fundazoo also said they worry about the health of the animals since Simon Bolivar and the Conservation Centre are the only ones that have an animal nutritionist and 
a veterinarian specialised in forest species.
Costa Rica banned circuses with animals in 2002 and has also barred sport hunting.

items.title: Egypt - Progress Threatens To Destroy The Pyramids
items.description:
T/I 10:16:15
PROGRESS THREATENS TO DESTROY THE PYRAMIDS
Cairo, Egypt                Natsot            Duration: 2.34"
The Great Pyramids of Giza have weathered 46 centuries; of wars, earthquakes, floods, and dust storms, but the 47th century is
looking like being one of their worst. The pyramids are in the pathway of man-made "progress". Built in the desert, they are now flanked by Cairo's outer suburbs, and haphazardly, and often illegally, built apartment houses are blocking the pyramids from view. Tourist shops sprawl to within a few hundred metres of the Sphinx, which shares the limestone plateau at Giza with the pyramids. A factory with chimney stacks that belch black smoke, a military barracks and a housing complex
for 15,000 people crowd the monuments. Some of the colossal limestone blocks of the three pyramids have crumbled away, eroded by pollution. The pyramids are on UNESCO's list of protected world heritage sites, but that status has failed to halt the pollution, or the growth of the urban sprawl around the monuments. And it couldn't prevent the construction of an eight-lane ring road around Cairo, part of which is only 2.5 kilometres from the pyramids. Dr. Zahi Hawas, Head of Archeological excavations at the pyramids, predicts a rush to build along the ring road, more pollution, overcrowding, and traffic around the pyramids. Recent public awareness of the threat of the ring road, and pressure from UNESCO, have brought a temporary stop but it appears that it has not been quite enough.
SHOWS: 
Giza pyramids. VS of Nazlet El Seman, a town nudging pyramids. New construction encroaching on sphinx. Cranes at building site, Giza pyramid behind. Rubbish dump in front of pyramids. Beer cans at dump. Burning rubbish, pyramid glimpsed through smoke. Partly completed elevated area of ring road. Trucks on ring road. Archeological dig with pyramids behind. Workers at archeological excavation site. Freshly discovered tombs at site. Dr. Zahi Hawas, SOT: "The ring road will kill the pyramids, particularly inviting more building in area, also bringing more pollution. The planned road defies UNESCO rules on protecting the pyramids". VS of urban sprawl. Nile delta villages and pyramids.

items.title: Rebels battle Gadhafi''s forces for control of key city
items.description:
Central Zawiya
1. Rebels on the street looking behind corner of building
2. Wide shot of a central square in Zawiya, AUDIO: Gunfire
3. Mid shot of square
4. Tank firing 
5. Top shot of square, AUDIO: Gunfire
6. Wide of tank firing
7. Pull out from damaged building with ripped rebel flag fluttering in the foreground
8. Wide of a square  AUDIO: Gunfire
9. Close of rebels praying
10. Various of rebels praying
11. Mid of Libyan government flags
12. Wide of damaged buildings
Zawiya Refinery
13. Rebel walking inside refinery 
14. Oil storage facility
15. Wide of refinery plant
16. Refinery workers outside gates
STORYLINE:
Libyan rebels took cover from mortars, rockets and anti-aircraft fire on Friday as they were pinned down in the centre of Zawiya while NATO''s bombing campaign helped slow Moammar Gadhafi''s ability to send reinforcements to the strategic western city.
The fierce onslaught by regime troops in Zawiya, just 30 miles (50 kilometres) west of Tripoli, signalled a slow and bloody push for opposition fighters as they try to advance toward the capital.
Still, Gadhafi''s troops seemed increasingly isolated, scrambling to use all force available to hold back rebels at the western front.
NATO has stepped up bombings in Tripoli in recent days, while rebels blocked Gadhafi''s supply route from Tunisia.
Fighting in Zawiya has focused on two main streets, Omar Mokhtar and Gamal Abdel-Nasser streets. 
At the front line, rebel field commander Rida Shaeb said Gadhafi forces held the main Zawiya hospital, as well as a hotel and a bank on the main square. 
Shaeb''s unit of about two dozen men was pinned down about 200 yards (meters) from the main square, and left its position after a particularly heavy barrage of mortars and rockets.
Libyan rebels also seized the western city of Zlitan after clashes with regime forces that left 31 rebels dead and 120 injured, a spokesman said. The claim couldn''t be independently verified.
Government troops have been fighting rebels in the area for months. The town is a major obstacle in the path from the nearby city of Misrata trying to make their way to Tripoli.
NATO has maintained a bombing campaign on Gadhafi military targets after instituting a no-fly zone decision in March.
The coalition said it took out four military facilities and a surface-to-air missile in Tripoli, as well as a command centre, two armoured vehicles and five tanks on Thursday in Zawiya.
The alliance also said NATO warplanes sunk a tugboat carrying troops loyal to Moammar Gadhafi away from Zawiya on Wednesday.    
An officer at NATO''s operational headquarters in Naples, Italy, said a rescue attempt was made after aircraft spotted several survivors of the sinking swimming toward a nearby buoy. The officer could not be identified under standing rules.
The rebels claimed on Thursday they had captured the 120,000-barrel-per-day refinery in fighting that could be a turning point in the six-month civil war between Gadhafi and forces seeking to oust him.
The flow of crude to the refinery from fields in the southwest of Libya had largely been halted since midsummer and its capture was unlikely to have a major impact on Gadhafi''s ability to secure fuel, but it was seen as a significant step in the rebel advance toward the capital.
Zawiya was one of the first cities to rise up against the Gadhafi regime when the Libyan revolt began in mid-February on the heels of the Tunisian and Egyptian revolutions.

items.title: Arab League Chief Elaraby says what is happening in Aleppo amounts to war crimes
items.description:
STORYLINE:
Arab League chief Nabil Elaraby said on Tuesday that the massacres taking place in Syria "amount to war crimes under international law".
Elaraby made the comments during a meeting with the Bulgarian Foreign Minister, Nickolai Mladenov, at the League's headquarters in the Egyptian capital, Cairo.
Elaraby spoke particularly of Aleppo, from where 200-thousand Syrians have fled over the past 10 days as the government trains its mortars, tank and helicopter gunships on neighbourhoods seized by the rebels.
The battle for Aleppo, Syria's commercial hub with around 3 million inhabitants, has now lasted longer than the rebel assault on the capital Damascus that regime troops crushed earlier in July.
Once a bastion of support for Assad, Aleppo is critical for both the regime and the opposition. Its fall would give the opposition a major strategic victory with a stronghold in the north. A rebel defeat, at the very least, would buy Assad more time.
Despite pledges by the government and opposition to implement the six-point peace plan for Syria brokered by Kofi Annan, a cease-fire never happened, and fighting has continued to escalate to a point where the conflict was recently declared a civil war. 
For many diplomats and military experts, Annan's plan is all but dead.
Bulgarian Foreign Minister, Nickolai Mladenov, on Tuesday called on Syrian opposition groups to unify and agree on a leadership in preparation for a post-Assad Syria.
"I hope that we can see our friends in the Syria opposition organise more quickly to implement what under the auspices of the Arab league that they have achieved," Mladenov said. "This is the National Compact and the transition plan, because this will send a strong message to the people in Syria about the future of their country after the end of the Assad regime," he added. 
Participants at a meeting of opposition groups in Cairo earlier this month (July) did agree on fundamental principles for a post-Assad Syria and a general outline to guide the opposition through a transitional period - but scuffles and fistfights during the session and a walkout by a Syrian Kurdish group visibly demonstrated the opposition's disarray.
The fighting in Aleppo stretched into its 11th day on Tuesday. 
Despite regime claims of success and repeated forays by tanks and ground forces into rebel-controlled areas in the northeast and southwest of the city, the rebels appear to have held their ground,
prompting government forces to resort to more shelling by artillery and mortars. Rebel positions are also being attacked with helicopter gunships.
The Syrian government has defended its assault on Aleppo to the U.N., describing a city in the grip of "terrorist mercenaries" funded by Qatar, Saudi Arabia and Turkey, that are holding people hostage as human shields and committing "horrifying crimes."



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/44e510ccd711a728a17f1975bce7b218 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Howling winds push devastating wildfire in new directions
items.description:
Pushed by howling, erratic winds, a massive wildfire in the north-central part of the US state of Washington was growing rapidly and burning in new directions on Saturday.
Road closures and evacuations were changing rapidly, as hot weather and winds with gusts up to 30 miles per hour (48 kilometres per hour) were
pushing the fire over ridge tops and toward a cluster of small towns northeast of Seattle.
Officials said there were no reports of injuries and only one more home was destroyed overnight by the lightning-caused wildfire.
The fire has blackened hillsides, destroyed homes and downed power lines. 
Many towns were without electrical power or phone service on Saturday.
The lightning-caused fire had scorched nearly 340 square miles (880 square kilometres) in the scenic Methow Valley. 
The fire was measured at 260 square miles (673 square kilometres) on Friday.
The fire consumed utility poles from two major power lines, knocking out power.
Vic Stokes, a rancher who lives in Twisp, a town in Methow Valley northeast of Seattle, said the local residents put out some of the spot fires themselves since Thursday, getting little sleep.
By Saturday, a fire had jumped to a nearby creek bed. 
Stokes, his son and his daughter-in-law spent the morning clearing brush. 
"Anything that hasn't burned has a chance of burning yet," Stokes said.
So far, his home is intact, but he's lost hay and a barn and is worried for livestock he had grazing in an area that's now scorched.
"We need to get up there and see what we can find that's alive. We know we've lost cattle," he said.

items.title: Live - Governor Jay Inslee & USFS Chief Tom Tidwell on Twisp, WA Fatalities
items.description:
Watch Live Press Conference with Washington Governor Jay Inslee and United States Forest Service Chief Tom Tidwell at the Chelan Fire Station on 11:00am Thursday August, 14th 2015. Governor  Inslee & USFS Chief Tidwell discuss the three USFS firefighter fatalities that occurred yesterday during initial attack of a wildfire near Twisp, Washington. Governor Inslee and Chief Tidwell were in Chelan, Washington on a tour of the Pacific Northwest Team #2 Incident Command Post at Chelan Falls Park. PNW2 under Incident Commander Chris Schulte and Deputy Rob Allen are managing the Chelan Complex, Reach Complex, Wolverine Fire, First Creek Fire, Blankenship Fire, McFarland Fire and Black Canyon Fire.

Raw footage by Public Information Officer Kale Casey. Media are welcome to use the footage in their news reports. Please credit Pacific Northwest Team 2 and PIO Kale Casey.

The PUD lost 100 power poles during the August, 14th 2015 firestorm - Reach Fire, Cagle Fire, Antoine Fire, Chelan Complex, Wolverine Fire, First Creek Fire, Black Canyon Fire, McFarland Fire.

items.title: Thank You FireFighters/Chelan, WA First Creek/August 2015
items.description:
08/14/2015 lightning started fires in Chelan, WA. On 08/15 the Yacht Club was evacuated and by 08/19/15 the fire moved very close to the Yacht Club Villa with 100 homes. New Fire lines were cut and old ones were cleared and widened. Many retardant drops were made above the homes and firefighters spent 24 hours a day keeping watch on our property. In the early hours of 08/20/15 the fire exploded and it looked like our homes would be gone. Firefighters stationed themselves throughout the Villa and watered things down to help keep our property safe. The fire stopped right where the fire line was made and where retardant was dropped. The fire moved its way north. Without all the firefighters and National Guard we would have lost all 100 homes.  The club members and other area residents began serving evening meals to all the fire crews as they changed shifts. As many as 180 firefighters have been fed each evening to thank them for saving our homes and working to get this fire out. The dinners were served for a week starting 08/23/2015.  THANK YOU ALL FIREFIGHTERS !!!
Thanks to The Coleman Brothers for recording the song and Thank You to Judy Kellersberger and Mike Black for writing this great song!!!

items.title: Ijen Volcano Crater Lake (Video 4 of 4)
items.description:
Ijen volcano has a one-kilometer-wide turquoise-colored acidic crater lake. The lake is the site of a labor-intensive sulfur mining operation, in which sulfur-laden baskets are carried by hand from the crater floor. The work is paid well considering the cost of living in the area, but is very onerous. Workers earn around Rp 50,000 - 75,000 ($4 to $5.4) per day and once out of the crater, still need to carry their loads of sulfur chunks about three kilometers to the nearby Paltuding Valley to get paid.

In addition, the electric-blue flame of Ijen phenomenon has occurred for a long time, but beforehand there was no midnight hiking. A two-hour hike is required to reach the rim of the crater, followed by a 45-minute hike down to the bank of the crater. The blue fire is ignited sulphuric gas, which emerges from cracks at temperatures up to 600 degrees Celsius (1,112 degrees Fahrenheit).

The Ijen volcano itself is part of the Ijen volcano complex, a group of stratovolcanoes in East Java, Indonesia. It is inside a larger caldera Ijen, which is about 20 kilometers wide. The Gunung Merapi stratovolcano is the highest point of that complex. The name "Gunung Merapi" means "mountain of fire" in the Indonesian language.

items.title: Lightning and House Fire - Flagstaff, Arizona - 15 August 2015
items.description:
On my way home after photographing monsoon thunderstorms northeast of Flagstaff, I noticed smoke rising over the hills along Townsend-Winona Road. I thought it might be another tree fire, but as I rounded a bend, it turned out to be a terrible house fire. Checking radar, it looked like there were 3 lightning strikes over that location from 2:45-3:00 PM and FlagScanner now reports that neighbors "heard a very large thunderclap along with lightning right before the fire started." Several fire trucks were on the scene but the fire was intense and they had to work hard to control it. Unfortunately, it looks like the house was a total loss. 

http://flagscanner.com/fsmajor-fully-involved-house-fire-foster-road/

items.title: 20150826 Sheriff Presser
items.description:
Published on Aug 26, 2015
This is a press conference statement by Polk County, Sheriff Grady Judd makes a statement that his officers are available to ensure that Press is safe while doing their jobs. Even if it is a negative story about his department.

Sheriff Judd made this statement after WDBJ Reporter Alison Parker and Photographer Adam Ward were shot and went to God during a live shot at 06:45 hrs on August 26, 2015 racist who was trying to start a race war in the United States.

When the Racist was spotted after switching vehicles Police recognized him and attempted to make a traffic stop on Route 66 in Virginia. The shooter ended up wrecking the vehicle and killed himself. When the vehicle was searched they found several license plates, typed to do list, Shawl, wig, umbrella and sunglasses indicating that he planned on evading capture and that this was pre-planned.

items.title: Black Mountain Crest Trail, Mt Mitchell, Pisgah National Forest, NC
items.description: A difficult hike along the entire Black Mountain Crest Trail starting at Bowlens Creek and ascending 3,000+ ft to Horse Rock Meadows below Celo Knob. From there the trail roller coasters over 4 of the tallest summits in NC before terminating at Mt Mitchell, the tallest peak east of the Mississippi River. This was performed as a shuttle hike. It is ~12.5 mi and ~5,500 ft elevation gain. The trail starts in Pisgah National Forest and ends in Mt Mitchell State Park, traversing the crest of the Black Mountains crossing Winter Star Mt, Potato Hill, Balsam Cone, Big Tom, Mt Craig, and Mt Mitchell. Thanks to Mike and Joyce for driving me back down the mountain to my car!

items.description:
People ran for their lives as a huge forest fire swept over a freeway packed with vehicles, in California's Cajon Pass, Friday. The wildfire had been spreading across drought-stricken San Bernardino County since Friday morning and had already charred a large area of the surrounding foothills before reaching the freeway.

Currently, 20 vehicles have been destroyed by the blaze, with at least 10 more left badly damaged, as people abandoned their cars on the freeway to escape the flames. Five homes have also been destroyed in the fire.

items.title: Dramatic pix as fires rage close to LA homes
items.description:
SHOTLIST
ABC - No Access N.America/Internet
Los Angeles County, California - 14 October 2008
1. Aerial of fire line and smoke in mountains at Porter Ranch in the San Fernando Valley ++ COMMENTARY VOICEOVER ++
AP Television
Los Angeles County, California - 14 October 2008
2. Brush burning on hill, tilts up to fire on a ridge line at Porter Ranch in the San Fernando Valley
3. Close up of flames engulfing trees
4. Medium shot of flames burning up trees and brush
5. Close up of tree in foreground, flames behind, camera tilts up to show flames shooting upward
6. Pan from fire engine to Nita Mahajan watching flames from her house
7. Close up of Mahajan
8. SOUNDBITE (English) Nita Mahajan, LA County resident:
"It's unbelievable. It's unbelievable. I am here by myself taking care of this house, and this fire is out of control and unbelievable. It's been going on for the last 24 hours and just when you think it's done it starts up all over again." 
9. Close up of fire on the ridge
10. Shot of family watching 
11. Reverse shot of family watching the fire
12. Wide shot of valley filled with smoke and helicopter in air
13. Chopper flies past firefighters on ground and then drops water
14. Wide shot of flames
15. Medium shot of flames
16. Chopper drops water on flames
17. Wide of line of firefighters marching up hillside
18. Firefighters walking though charred hillside
19. Firefighters clearing brush with tools and chainsaws
STORYLINE:
Flames whirled dangerously close to homes on Tuesday as gusty Santa Ana winds sent the biggest of southern California's wildfires flaring in hilly brushlands on Los Angeles' northern edge and along subdivisions to the west.
Firefighters with hoses guarded houses as helicopters unleashed loads of water on hot spots of the more than 20-square-mile (32 square kilometre) blaze charring slopes above the San Fernando Valley communities of Porter Ranch and Granada Hills.
Flames then pushed west to the rolling grasslands of Ventura County and made runs toward Simi Valley neighbourhoods of modern homes defended by a broad firebreak, helicopters, airplanes and ground crews.
The fire is one of three major blazes that have burned more than 34 square miles (55 square kilometres) of Southern California, destroyed dozens of homes and forced thousands of people to evacuate their homes this week.
One man died in the flames, and a motorist was killed in a crash as a fire neared a freeway.
Sixty-two structures, 15 of them homes, have been destroyed in the Porter Ranch area, said Los Angeles County fire officials. 
Officials said on Tuesday night they did not know how much of the fire was contained.
Ten miles away, there was major progress against Los Angeles' other big wildfire.
A blaze bigger than 7 square miles (11 square kilometres) in the northeastern San Fernando Valley was 70 percent contained and some evacuees were allowed to go home. 
But people who lived in an area where 38 mobile homes were destroyed were not permitted to return.
The outbreak of fires followed the weekend arrival of the first significant Santa Ana winds of the fall.
The National Weather Service said the intensity of the winds was diminishing but warned there would still be strong gusts. 
Warnings for critical fire weather conditions were to remain in effect until Wednesday night.
The Santa Anas usually sweep in between October and February as cold, dry air descending over the Great Basin flows toward Southern California and squeezes through mountain passes and canyons. 
The extremely low humidity levels, which make vegetation easier to burn, and high windspeeds combine to whip fires into infernos.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/8e2ddc4adb39944eba929a88febdf21f 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Feature on California residents building near areas of high fire risk
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of burning homes
2. Halloween display in garden, surrounded by smoke
3. Pan from Walmart truck to evacuees waiting in a parking lot
4. SOUNDBITE: (English): Theresa Alamo, evacuee:
"We came up and rented a house until we could afford one and this is our very first house. We've been married 27 years, our first house, and this is how we are. We won't give it up, we'll stay."
5. Local with his dog and motorbike in van
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Gary Garrison, evacuee:
"When you live in the mountains, you put up with the danger of the fire because it's a small price or a small trade for very little crime, very good neighbours, being able to live and raise your children where you want." 
7. View of evacuee with her cat
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Merilee Bishop, evacuee:
"It's very scary, it's just my daughter and I. I have a son but it's not a good relationship right now but we are going to make it through. I've got my friends; I've got my daughter and I've got my animals and we have God on our side."
9. Various of fire
10. Fire officials talking
11. Pan of vehicles driving through smoke and haze
12. SOUNDBITE: (English) Bob Poole, United States Forrest Service:
"This is what we call a wind-driven event. The fire is being pushed by Santa Ana north winds. Right now we're in the town of Running Springs; we're at the southern tip of Running Springs. It appears at this point that the worse of the fire has pushed through but as you can see we still have a lot of active fire."
13. Various of firefighters battling fire
14. Various charred vehicle
15. Mid of burned barbecue grill
16. Charred car with small fire still burning in the foreground
STORYLINE:
As fires continue to rage throughout Southern California, officials in Running Springs say fire destroyed at least 1-hundred homes, leaving many residents uncertain about their future.
Four years ago, fire destroyed hundreds of homes in nearby Lake Arrowhead and also affected Running Springs.
Residents of the mountain resort community east of Los Angeles were evacuated last night to Highland, a town near San Bernadino.
About a dozen people turned a Walmart parking lot into a makeshift shelter, with the superstore giving out food and water to evacuees.
Despite the devastation, many vow to rebuild.
"This is our very first house. We've been married 27 years, our first house, and this is how we are. We won't give it up, we'll stay," local Theresa Alamo told AP Television.
"When you live in the mountains, you put up with the danger of the fire because it's a small price or small trade for very little crime, very good neighbours, being able to live and raise your children where you want," another local evacuee, Gary Garrison, said.
By day three, the dozen wildfires had burned more than 1,300 homes and businesses in Southern California, and the destruction may only be the start for the region. 
At least 346-thousand homes, roughly one in three, according to census data, were evacuated in San Diego County alone, sheriff's officials said. 
But the total number could be much higher, and state officials were still struggling to estimate how many people had fled.
Since they began on Sunday, the fires have burned at least 373,000 acres, or 583 square miles (1,510 sq. kilometres). 
Fully a quarter of the California coast was ablaze. 
Flames climbed halfway toward the Nevada line, chewing through chunks of seven counties and devastating numerous communities.
As the fires spread, most out of control, smaller blazes were merging into larger, more fearsome ones. 
Evacuations were being announced in one community after another as firefighters found themselves overwhelmed by gale-force Santa Ana winds, some gusting to 70 miles per hour (113 kilometres per hour).

items.title: Blaze devastates mobile home park
items.description:
1. Wide of remains of burnt-out trailer
2. Close of hand sifting through burnt documents
3. Mid of fire victim Miriam Villareal looking through documents
4. Fire victim Reverend Pedro Villareal looking through burnt documents, UPSOUND: (English) "Good memories."
5. SOUNDBITE (English) Reverend Pedro Villareal, fire victim:
"Everything is gone. I even... My old papers, my documents... Nothing. I have nothing anymore but, what I can do?"
6. Various of burnt-out cars
7. SOUNDBITE (English) Miriam Villareal, fire victim:
"And the greatest blessing is knowing God. Because when the hard times come, he's always there for us and he gives us comfort, through people." 
8. Family sifting through remains of burnt-out trailer 
9. Close on legs from burnt sewing machine 
10. Woman pointing to legs UPSOUND: (English) "Her mother's legs to her sewing machine."
11. SOUNDBITE (English) Mike Gomula, fire victim:
"It's amazing how for 5 years you can save and have things and then 5 minutes it's all gone. It all disappears just like that."
12. Wide of burnt out housing block
13. Various of burnt palm tree against blue sky
14. Wide of burnt remains in lot 
15. Woman sifting through debris, UPSOUND: (English) "I don't even know what I'm looking for."
16. Burnt letter box 
17. Fire engine parked on the street
18. Firefighters talking to residents
STORYLINE:
Some residents at a Los Angeles mobile home park returned to their burnt out homes on Wednesday, despite a ban from authorities. 
Trailers in the devastated Sky Terrace Lodge mobile home park, situated in the Lake View Terrace section of Los Angeles were reduced to lumps of melted plastic and buckled wood by a wildfire that tore through the region on Monday.
Residents were seen sifting through the charred remains of their homes as they struggled to come to grips with what they'd lost.
More than 30 mobile homes were destroyed in the blaze.
The fire was one of a series of blazes that have flared in hilly brushlands on Los Angeles' northern edge and along subdivisions to the west.
Firefighters said on Wednesday they were close to containing a fire Southwest of the San Fernando Valley, after it erupted in Point Mugu State Park's La Jolla Canyon and grew to 20 acres (8 hectares) just above Pacific Coast Highway. 
On the north coast of San Diego County, a 6-square-mile (15-square kilometre) fire at the Marine Corps Camp Pendleton was 75 percent contained. 
Meanwhile, most evacuation orders were lifted for residents of about 1,500 homes in neighbouring Oceanside and for many Marine Corps personnel and family members in military housing, but some remained in emergency shelters.
The outbreak of fires followed the weekend arrival of the first significant Santa Ana winds of the season.
The notorious Santa Ana wind's usually sweep in between October and February as cold, dry air descending over the Great Basin flows toward Southern California and squeezes through mountain passes and canyons.
The extremely low humidity levels, which make vegetation easier to burn, and high wind speeds then often combine to whip fires into infernos.

Hand crews at the top are going to work their way down. We've got hand crews at the bottom. They're going to work their way up and they're hopefully going to pinch it off."

STORYLINE:

Firefighters near Los Angeles used water-dropping helicopters to help beat back a stubborn wildfire burning 30 miles (48 km) north of the city.

Local fire officials say the foothill fire burning near the city of Santa Clarita is now approximately 39 per cent contained, after scorching more than five-thousand acres of parched brush land over the weekend. 

More than 1,500 firefighters were battling the foothill fire, with three treated at hospital for minor injuries. 

Fire crews were working along a mountain ridge on Monday morning to prevent a flare up along the front lines where the fire was halted. 

They were working to save hundreds of homes threatened by the stubborn wildfire that broke out in tinder-dry brush and raced over hillsides and through canyons in northern Los Angeles County.

Although no structures have been lost, nearly 1,600 homes have been evacuated since the fire began on Saturday. 

The fire was ignited when a hawk flew into a power line, was electrocuted and its flaming body fell into brush left dry by years of little rain.

The foothill fire was one of several burning across more than 40,000 acres of California from eastern San Diego County to Yosemite National Park.

items.title: Olympic torch arrives in LA
items.description:
1. Wide of Olympic flame being carried in lantern to podium, torch being handed to Los Angeles Mayor James Hahn
2. SOUNDBITE: (English) James Hahn, Mayor of Los Angeles:
"As mayor of Los Angeles, home to the 1932 and 1984 Olympic Games, I welcome the Olympic torch to the City of the Angels."
3. Mid shot of torch being lit and mayor raising it to crowd 
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) Sylvester Stallone, actor:
"I never expected this and it proves anything can happen and I just hope I can live up to what this flame represents, which is honour, dignity, and that never-say-die spirit. Thank you very much."
5. Mid shot from above of Stallone running through crowd with torch as Olympic fanfare music plays
6. Mid shot from ground of Stallone running with torch

STORYLINE:

The Olympic flame began its journey through the United States Wednesday, with people from all walks of life carrying the torch on its relay to the summer Olympic Games in Athens.

The flame arrived in Los Angeles in the morning from Mexico, and at a ceremony on California's famed Venice Beach, Mayor James Hahn lit the torch that would carry the fire through the city.

Actor Sylvester Stallone was the first to run with the torch and called it the proudest moment of his life.

Stallone handed the flame off to Frank McCourt, the owner of the Los Angeles Dodgers baseball team, beginning a relay through Los Angeles that was to culminate with the torch being used to ignite a flame at Dodger Stadium before Wednesday night's game.

Others scheduled to carry the torch included actor Tom Cruise, heavyweight boxing champion Vitali Klitschko, quadruple Olympic gold medal-winning swimmer Janet Evans, and Olympic decathlon champion Rafer Johnson.

Los Angeles hosted the summer Olympic Games in 1932 and 1984.

The flame is to visit other former Olympic cities in North America including St. Louis on Thursday, Atlanta on Friday, New York on Saturday, and Montreal on Sunday.

The flame's 46,800-mile journey began June 4 and is due to end in Athens at the Opening Ceremony on August 13.

items.title: UK marines on live-fire exercise in California desert
items.description:
1. Wide shot of British Royal Marines in desert combat training 
2. Mid shot of Marine giving orders
3. Close shot of Marines advancing 
4. Wide shot of Marines running 
5. Mid shot of Marines firing weapons 
6. Wide shot of Marines running  
7. Close shot of Marine firing weapon and running 
8. Close shot of Marine firing weapon  
9. Wide shot of Marines moving forward 
10. Close shot of Marine shouting orders  
11. Close shot of Marine firing weapon 
12. Wide shot of Marines firing weapons 
13. Close shot of Marine firing weapon 
14. Close shot of Marines running and kneeling to fire 
15. Wide shot of Marines running 
16. Mid shot of Marines jumping into trench 
17. Mid shot of Marine jumping into trench
18. SOUNDBITE: (English)  British Royal Marine, 40 Commando:  
"You don't really think about it to tell the truth. If you think about it it's pretty nerve racking, the chance of getting shot. It's not what's running through your mind. You just want to get the job done. So you don't think about stuff like that."
19. Wide shot of Marines walking back to base after exercise 
20. Close shot of Marines walking 
21. Close shot of Marine with ammunition
22. Close shot of Marine with weapon 
23. Mid shot of Marine with weapon
24. Wide shot of Marines walking in formation 

STORYLINE:

Units of the British Royal Marines continued their desert combat training in southern California this week.

Some 560 of the British commandos are guests of the US Marine Corps at their Twentynine Palms Base about 150 miles south of Los Angeles. 

It's the largest US Marine base and home to their Air-Ground Combat Centre. 

And it's where marines come to train for desert warfare, using real bullets and bombs. 

The Royal Marines are a mix of seasoned veterans, some having served in Afghanistan, and newcomers.

The Brits will remain in California for three weeks of what they call "live-fire training", using real ammunition and staging mock attacks on enemy positions. 

Some of the Marines of 40 Commando unit say they're too busy focusing on getting the job done to worry about getting hit with a stray bullet. 

Their commanders say this kind of training gives soldiers the essential feel of battle conditions, without the inconvenience of a real enemy firing back.

Some of the desert training may also involve the use of tanks, attack helicopters and jet fighters during combined exercises with the US Marines. 

For now, the Royal Marines are busy fine tuning the skills of small-arms tactics.

After they're finished at Twentynine Palms later this month, they'll head North in another region of California for some high-altitude mountain training, before heading home to Britain sometime in late November.

items.description:
AP TELEVISION

"It kicked off in one unit, one housing unit. The other seven housing units, or I should say six housing units, began to simultaneously fighting within the units."
AP TELEVISION - NO ACCESS NORTH AMERICA

AP TELEVISION
August 11, 2009

12. Close up of bloody sock

14. Wide shot of debris on lawn
15. Medium shot of guards using metal detectors across lawn
16. Various shots of mattress with writing "8-8-09 history" on it
17. Wide shot of damaged housing unit
18. Wide shot of prison
19. Medium shot of guard towers
20. SOUNDBITE: (English) Lieutenant Mark Hargrove, California Dept. Corrections and Rehabilitation   
"When fighting or altercations or rioting begin in prisons they do segregate among racial lines, and that is generally how the fighting goes."
21. Pan of destroyed housing unit
22. Medium shot of bed with prisoner's shirt on it
23. SOUNDBITE: (English) Lieutenant Mark Hargrove, California Dept. Corrections and Rehabilitation   
"This is a challenge. Other institutions are going to have to take these inmates in. We have intake waiting to come into our reception centre from the country jails. It creates a backlog and that is a challenge to deal with."
24. Medium shot of guard tower
25. Medium shot of burned out housing unit
26. Medium pan from burned housing unit to debris outside
STORYLINE:
Blood-soaked mattresses, singed bedding and abandoned medical supplies littered the campus of a southern California prison on Tuesday - a testament to the mayhem and violence of a weekend riot that shut down part of the institution and injured about 175 inmates, some critically.
Prison officials staged a tour of the devastation at the California Institution for Men in Chino to reveal the extent of an apparently racially motivated riot that broke out on Saturday evening and raged for four hours before guards could bring it under control.
Seven units in the prison's Reception Centre West were left uninhabitable and more than 1,100 inmates have been moved to other facilities. 
One of the dormitories was completely gutted by flames.
Eleven inmates remained in hospital on Tuesday, state prisons spokesman Terry Thornton said.
The area where the riot broke out was eerily empty and silent, with only a skeleton staff of corrections officers manning checkpoints. 
A half-dozen officers scanned the exercise yard with metal detectors, searching for homemade weapons that inmates might have buried.
The riot began in a dorm during dinner hour and quickly spread, temporarily overwhelming staff, said Lt. Mark Hargrove, a prison spokesman.
Prisoners pried heavy metal grates from windows to escape and scrambled up and over the dorm roofs to get around 10-foot (3-metre)-tall hurricane fencing intended to keep them from the main exercise yard. 
The fence was installed after a previous riot in 2006.
The prison was built in 1941 to house 3,000 inmates but held 5,900 men at the time of the riot. 
About 95 percent of the prisoners are parole violators.

items.title: Twin NASA spacecraft slam into lunar mountain
items.description:
++16:9++ 
++MUTE++
1. NASA animation of Ebb and Flow, or the Gravity Recovery and Interior Laboratory (GRAIL), travelling above the surface of the moon
2. NASA animation of GRAIL orbiting the moon on its final orbit before crash landing
3. NASA animation of Ebb and Flow disappearing into moon's surface
++16:9++
Pasadena, California - 17 December 2012
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) David Lehman, GRAIL Project Manager:
"It is dark right now on the moon, but we picked the site to make sure we did not hit the historic sites, the heritage historic sites, and we wanted to get good tracking date before we impacted. So, it turns out that this mountain 75 degree north latitude is where it fell out that we were going to hit."
++16:9++
++MUTE++
5. Recent computer image of Ebb and Flow as seen from Earth, a blue and red line indicating their travel paths
6. NASA animation showing Ebb and Flow orbiting the moon and communicating with the Earth
++16:9++
Pasadena, California - 17 December 2012
7. SOUNDBITE: (English) Maria Zuber, GRAIL Principal Investigator:
"We've determined the thickness of the lunar crust. Finally we have a crustal thickness model of the moon globally that matches the point measurements that have come from Apollo seismics, and this shows us that the moon's crust is actually much thinner than we thought before."
++4:3++
Lunar surface - Date unknown
8. Black and white footage of moon's outer crust as taken by cameras on Ebb and Flow 
STORYLINE:
A pair of NASA spacecraft were deliberately crashed into a mountain near the moon's north pole on Monday, ending a mission that peered into the lunar interior.
Engineers commanded the twin spacecraft, Ebb and Flow, to fire their engines and burn their remaining fuel.  
Ebb plunged first followed by Flow about 30 seconds later. 
Afterward, NASA said it had dedicated the impact site in honour of mission team member, Sally Ride, the first American woman in space who died earlier this year.
By design, the spot was far away from the Apollo landings and other historical sites. 
With their fuel tanks almost on empty, NASA devised a controlled crash to avoid contacting any of the treasured sites. 
Since the crash occurred in the dark, it was not visible from Earth. 
The Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter circling the moon will pass over the mountain and attempt to photograph the skid marks left by the washing machine sized-spacecraft as they hit the surface at 3,800 miles per hour (6,115 kilometres per hour).
After rocketing off the launch pad in September 2011, Ebb and Flow took a roundabout journey to the moon, arriving over the New Year's holiday on a gravity-mapping mission. 
More than 100 missions have been flung to Earth's nearest neighbour since the dawn of the Space Age including NASA's six Apollo moon landings that put 12 astronauts on the surface.
Ebb and Flow focused exclusively on measuring the moon's lumpy gravity field in a bid to learn more about its interior and early history. 
After flying in formation for months, they produced the most detailed gravity maps of any body in the solar system.
Secrets long held by the moon are spilling out. 
Ebb and Flow discovered that the lunar crust is much thinner than scientists had imagined. 
And it was severely battered by asteroids and comets in the early years of the solar system, more than previously realised.
Data so far also appeared to quash the theory that Earth once had two moons that collided and melded into the one we see today.

items.title: Paul Walker's Daughter,  Meadow Rain Walker Sues Porsche
items.description:
Paul Walker's daughter sues Porsche for wrongful death

LOS ANGELES - Paul Walker's daughter sued Porsche for wrongful death Monday, claiming the sports car that her father was in when he was killed suffered from numerous design defects.

The lawsuit filed by Meadow Rain Walker seeks unspecified damages for defects that her lawyers claim kept the actor trapped in the Porsche Carrera GT when it crashed and burst into flames in November 2013.

Walker was on a break from filming the seventh film in the "Fast & Furious" franchise when he was killed. He was riding in the Carrera GT driven by friend and business associate Roger Rodas when the car spun out of control, struck three trees and burst into flames on a street in Santa Clarita, California.

The wrongful-death suit claims the car, which was marketed as a street-legal race car, lacked a proper stability control system and safeguards to protect occupants and keep it from catching fire after a collision.

"Absent these defects in the Porsche Carrera GT, Paul Walker would be alive today," the lawsuit states.

An email sent to representatives of Porsche Cars North America was not immediately returned.

The 18-page lawsuit includes a detailed recounting of the crash and contends that the Porsche was traveling 63 to 71 mph (101 to 114 kph) when it spun out of control.

Investigators concluded the Porsche was going much faster -- up to 94 mph (151 kph) -- when it crashed.

The investigation by the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department and California Highway Patrol concluded that it was unsafe speed and not mechanical problems that caused the crash. That investigation was aided by engineers from Porsche, who evaluated the wreckage of the rare car.

Meadow Walker's lawsuit contends Porsche didn't include a stability control system in the Carrera GT model Rodas was driving but includes it in other models. It also claims the car lacked proper reinforcements in its doors and used rubber fuel lines that didn't break free to prevent a fire in a crash.

Similar allegations of design and safety defects were included in a wrongful death lawsuit by Rodas' widow, Kristine Rodas, that remains pending in a federal court in Los Angeles. Rodas was trained as a race car driver and was only driving 55 mph (89 kph), according to his wife's lawsuit. He left behind two young children when he died.

Walker, the star of the "Fast & Furious" film franchise, co-owned an auto racing team with Rodas named Always Evolving. Meadow Walker, 16, is the sole heir of his estate.

Walker's two brothers helped complete action scenes in "Furious 7," which earned more than $1.5 billion globally after it was released in April.

Source:http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/paul-walker-s-daughter-sues-porsche-for-wrongful-death-1.10902917

items.description: Victim reports that she attended a party briefly with a former boyfriend in the city of Long Beach near her residence. The ex-boyfriends new girlfriend assaulted her without cause. The victim called the police and left the residence. Victim reports that she was not allowed to be released from custody until she cleaned up her own vomit. Victim reports that she was hyperventilating and ill during the entire incarceration but was denied medical care repeatedly by jail staff.
