items.title: Disneyland Frontierland Rides & Complete Area POV Tour 2015
items.description:
Disneyland 60th Anniversary STABILIZED Frontierland Complete Area POV Tour at Disneyland in California 2015: infaMOUSEproject is mostly Disney Rides, Shows, & POV Attraction videos taken at Disneyland Park & Disney California Adventure Park in the Disneyland Resort in Anaheim, Epcot & Magic Kingdom at Walt Disney World in Florida, and Universal Studios Theme Parks all of them are in America so far. Frontierland is one of the "themed lands" at the many Disneyland-style parks run by Disney around the world. Themed to the American Old West of the 19th century, Frontierlands are home to cowboys and pioneers, saloons, red rock buttes and gold rushes. Every instance of Frontierland has a Big Thunder Mountain Railroad, and a stretch of riverfront. Other attractions sometimes found in this land include Big Thunder Mountain, the Country Bear Jamboree, Tom Sawyer Island and a steam-powered riverboat.
Dedication

    Frontierland. It is here that we experience the story of our country's past. The color, romance and drama of frontier America as it developed from wilderness trails to roads, riverboats, railroads and civilization. A tribute to the faith, courage and ingenuity of our hearty pioneers who blaze the trails and made this progress possible.
    — Walter E. Disney, July 17, 1955

Frontierland first appeared in Disneyland as one of five original themed lands. Conceived by Walt Disney, the land did not initially contain many attractions, but centered on open expanses of wilderness which could be traversed by guests via stagecoach, pack mules, Conestoga wagon,and walking trails. The Mine Train Thru Nature's Wonderland opened in 1960, consisting of a sedate train ride around various western landscape dioramas. The Mine Train closed in 1977 to make way for a new attraction; the Big Thunder Mountain Railroad, which opened in 1979.

Disneyland's Frontierland gateway is constructed of ponderosa pine logs. The land's long shoreline along the Rivers of America is considered a prime viewing location for the nighttime Fantasmic! show. The docks to both the Mark Twain Riverboat and the Sailing Ship Columbia, (a replica of American explorer Robert Gray's 18th century ship that circumnavigated the globe) are located here, and Tom Sawyer Island in the river's center is also considered a property of Frontierland

Frontierland's buildings have lots of detail too. On the roof of the Westward Ho Trading Co., there are elk or deer antlers. Elk antlers were commonly placed on general stores in the old west so cowboys coming into town immediately knew where to get supplies. Also in Frontierland is a building that has a large sign that says "Laod Bhang Co. Fireworks Factory". Plus, at the storefront marked "Crockett and Russel Hat Co.", you'll find a window honoring Fess Parker, who played Davy Crockett in Walt Disney's Davy Crockett. Frontierland borders Fantasyland (via the Big Thunder Trail), New Orleans Square and Adventureland, and connects to the Central Plaza through an iconic set of fort-style gates.

items.title: Bushnell Shield Series 15' x 9' I
items.description:
~ Ok, We just returned from camping in Yucaipa Regional Park in California, and it was our first time using the Bushnell Shield Series 15' x 9' Instant Cabin Tent, Sleeps 9 ( You can only get it from Walmart).

- We went camping with the in-laws couple of months ago and they let us use their 6 person Coleman tent, after that weekend I decided We needed to get our own,  I did a little research and found this tent.  The main reason why I bought it, it is because it's an instant tent, it took us less than 9 minutes to set up, we weren't in a hurry, we just wanted to do it right, I didn't read any instructions, because I previously watched the product video demo, and it was pretty easy to setup.

~ We spent  3 days and two nights in Yucaipa Regional Park, during the day it was too hot, We were most of the time in the cooking area and occasionally We went to the tent to get our stuff and the tent was a bit hot because there was no shade or anything, which was just normal,  but at night it was just perfect, we left one windows open to have some air flow and we slept like babies.

~ We are 5 in the family, so this tent was just perfect, there was enough room for all of us (2 queen mattresses) and still plenty of space to put our clothes/luggage, sleeping bags, etc.
~ I really like the materials, it has two entrances so we used the sided one, We also put a heavy duty tarp on the bottom of the tent to protect it, I bought a 6' x 8
green grass rug and on top of that an Easy up (Canopie) and it was a perfect setup.

~Overall a great experience no complaints or anything, We are just very happy with this investment, Can't wait to go camping in the next few weeks!

items.title: Regal 3060 Express Cruiser Deck & Cabin Tour by South Mountain Yachts
items.description:
Come join me for this "Looks & Features" video tour on this 2007 Regal Express cruiser. We start at the starboard bow noting the fore deck features such as the covered windlass, deck wash-down and spotlight. Moving aft note the large forward and side windows which brightens up the cabin's interior. We got a full Camper Canvass enclosure, to offer year around protection. At the transom we check out the dinghy ( which may be included), storage and other features on this part of the deck.
Once aboard, we can see the bi-level cockpit and note the fold-a-way transom seating.
At the helm we get the "captain's view " from the command center and can easily see all of the controls are with in easy reach of the pilot.
We enter the cabin thru a "smoky" opaque door with a full screen underneath. To port we have a galley with a hidden glass top stove which is covered when not in use for lots of counter space.
Regal has used upgraded materials here with a textured upholstery on the seating area; has finished the floor so you can remove the carpet and has a solid wood table that lowers into the deck with the push of a button to form the forward sleeping area. The head is remarkably large for this size vessel: besides the vac-u-Flush system, it has  separate shower area with curtain to keep the rest of the facility dry. That's a Ladies Like It Feature!
The mid cabin is full beam and double wide and the mirrored bulkheads give the impression of roominess. There is lots of storage in the boat: the stairs lift up, there are multiple lockers and the bottom of the sofa has drawers that pull out so you do not have to move the cushions. This vessel has all the amenities: with AC in the cabin, a generator for full power, a well lite cabin and rich furnishings you'll feel right at home!.
Visit the www.SOUTHMOUNTAINYACHTS.com site now for full specs, lots of photos and all of our fun boats for sale. Give up a call at (949) 842-2344 to find out how you can have this boat today.

items.title: Goodbye Big Thunder Ranch Barbeque at Disneyland California (Star Wars Land) 2016
items.description:
disneyland 60th anniversary Big Thunder Ranch Disneyland Tribute Halloween 2015: infaMOUSEproject is mostly Disneyland Rides in California, Shows, & POV Attraction videos,  Disney World Rides,  and Disney California Adventure Rides in the Disneyland Resort in Anaheim, Epcot & Magic Kingdom at Walt Disney World in Florida, and Universal Studios Theme Parks  (Orlando & Anaheim) all of them are in America so far. Big thunder ranch at Disneyland will be closing to make way for Star Wars Land. I took one last trip through Big thunder ranch in frontierland to film. Big Thunder Ranch is an attraction at Disneyland. It includes an outdoor petting zoo, a walk-through cabin, and a variety of scenery meant to create the atmosphere of a Western ranch. It is located in Frontierland, close to Big Thunder Mountain Railroad. Inside you can find sheep, goats, cows, and other farm animals. Among these animals are the two turkeys who received presidential pardons in honor of Thanksgiving in 2008.[1] The attraction is hosted by Brawny.

Big Thunder Ranch will close permanently on January 10, 2016, as the attraction (and some nearby backstage areas) will be the future site of a 14-acre Star Wars-themed land.

Big Thunder Ranch has an eating area, once called the Big Thunder Barbecue, as well as an outdoor stage that once served as a home for the Hunchback of Notre Dame dinner show. The show ended in the late 1990s, with Big Thunder Barbecue closing soon after. It also hosted the Billy Hill and the Hillbillies show from after they left the Golden Horseshoe Saloon until they were fired by Disney and went to Knotts Berry Farm, on January 6th 2014. After being used on occasion for special events and seasonal attractions for several years, the outdoor dining area reopened in spring 2009 serving seasonal confections and an all-you-can-eat American-style barbecue menu, which includes: chicken, pork, sausage, beans, corncob, cornbread, coleslaw, lemonade and fruit cobbler. Traditional American country and folklore sing-along are performed by musicians on stage and interact with dining-guests.

The log cabin is called "Miss Chris's Cabin" and has two large tables stocked with baskets of crayons and coloring pages.
Decorations

The entire ranch rotates through seasonal-appropriate decorations:

    Summertime Roundup decorations features summer flowers, eagles, and red/white/blue color motifs.
    Autumntime Roundup decorations features fall flowers, carved pumpkins, and orange/brown/yellow color motifs.
    Wintertime Roundup decorations features winter flowers, snow, and red/green/blue color motifs.
    Springtime Roundup decorations features spring flowers, baby animals, and purple/yellow/green color motifs.

The ranch often hosts seasonal and holiday-themed shows, including "Woody's All-American Roundup" during Fourth of July events, "Woody's Halloween Roundup"' during Halloween events, and "Santa's Reindeer Roundup" during Christmas events. disneyland rides,big thunder mountain railroad disneyland 2015,disneyland rides 2015,disney rides,disneyland california,disneyland 2015,disneyland rides in california,rides,disneyland,disneyland california rides,scary rides,thunder mountain disneyland,disneyland videos,disneyland attractions,disneyland thunder mountain 2015,disneyland 2015 rides,disneyland california 2015,disneyland new rides 2015,rides at disneyland,disneyland rides in california 2015,disneyland big thunder mountain railroad 2015,thunder mountain disneyland 2015,disney land rides,disneyland paris rides 2015,

items.title: Elkhorn – A Montana Ghost Town HD – near Boulder, Montana MT
items.description:
Elkhorn, a Montana ghost town in HD, is near Boulder, Montana. 
 
Join me as I explore Elkhorn ghost town in the southwestern part of our state of Montana.  Silver was initially discovered in the Elkhorn Mountains and over $14 million in silver was carried from the mines in the area. In 1890, the Sherman Silver Purchase Act passed, creating a high demand for Elkhorn's silver.

During this peak period, Elkhorn boasted 2,500 inhabitants, a school, hotel, church, stores, saloons, and brothels. Unlike most mining towns, Elkhorn was populated mostly by married European immigrants.  In 1893 the Fraternity Hall was constructed for social gatherings, and still remains as one of the most well-preserved buildings in Elkhorn.

In the years following, the silver boom and Elkhorn's prosperity began to lessen as the desire for silver decreased. A diphtheria epidemic also struck Elkhorn, resulting in many deaths, particularly of children.  Soon after, railroad service to Elkhorn was halted and only a fraction of the original inhabitants remained.

This was my second journey to Elkhorn ghost town.  The first expedition was in 2001.  I took a few pictures and made a slideshow https://youtu.be/f8fP7Yglon8   Thinking back, I believe the town had only a couple of hardy souls living there. 
 
Boy was I surprised when I arrived in town.  Not only did I have a flat tire, but many cabins have been renovated and the year-round population is now up to ten!  Most residents are descendants of early miners and shopkeepers. 
 
Everyone I met was extremely friendly and related stories of relatives who worked, built cabins or were buried in the cemetery.
  
Elkhorn John was the first resident I met.  He lives across the street west from the Elkhorn State Park, the smallest state park in Montana.  The park consists of two buildings, the Gillian Hall and the Fraternity Hall.  

Elkhorn John lives in a cabin built by his grandfather in 1892!  He, along with his two friendly dogs, opened up the fire hall and aired up my flat tire.  This did not fix the problem but it did tell us where the rock hole was!  Replacing the flat with my spare was my next project.

I also met Tom and a friend of his.  Tom lives across the street north of the state park.  He assisted me in replacing my flat tire with my spare tire.  His friend actually went looking for a spare when we were having difficulties removing my spare from under the truck.  Tom filled the spare with his portable compressor since it was also low on air (a new tire but had not been checked for air since it was new, six years ago!)
  
Tom related a few stories about Elkhorn.  As a teenager, he assisted in the Elkhorn Mine delivering dynamite to the blasters (at 500 to 1800 feet underground!)  His grandfather built a cabin on the land where he now lives.  

Tom recommended I visit the cemetery and also the old railroad water tower built in 1889 by the Northern Pacific Railroad.  The water tower and short-line railroad from Boulder were active until rail service was discontinued in 1914.  

The 48,000 gallon water tower is the last-known example of a first-generation Northern Pacific wooden water tank which, because of its 6,000-ft. altitude, included a wooden skirt around the tank supporting structure.

Another person I met was just leaving the cemetery when I arrived.  She is from Helena and her great grandfather was buried here.  He died during the Diphtheria epidemic that hit the town especially hard from 1884-1889.

Now, THAT’S a lot of history in my short four hour stay in Elkhorn ghost town!  I just wish I had budgeted more time.  The next sojourn will be sooner than 15 years from now, for sure!
 
This sequence was captured with a DJI camera on a Phantom 3 Advanced quad copter (aka drone or UAV) and a Canon Vixia HFS-100 camera.  Post production utilized Adobe Premier Pro 6.

items.title: September 11th Renner Fire Burnout Div W
items.description: Winds were favorable and fuels receptive for a burnout operation on the northwest corner of the Renner Fire. Firefighters will continue to take advantage of favorable conditions in order to secure areas that have unburnt fuel between the fireline and the fire's edge.

items.title: Live - Watch Firing Operations on the Renner Fire September 12th, 2015
items.description:
Ever wonder why firefighters intentionally set fire to fuels inside the control line, otherwise known as a 'firing operation' or 'burnout'? Watch live fireline footage from the Renner Fire on September 12th, 2015. Fire Information Officer Cory Wall from WAIMT1 explains how firing operations or burnouts consume fuels in the path of a wildfire in order to slow, knock down or contain a rapidly spreading fire. In this case, the Colville National Forest Type 2 Initial Attack handcrew has been working on the northwest corner of the Renner Fire for the past two days in order to methodically secure the containment line by removing unburnt fuels.

Filmed and edited by Fire Information Officer Kale Casey.
Media are welcome to use the footage in their news reports.

items.title: Firefighter's Perspective: Q&A with Local Firefighter Nolan Roth - USFS Colville National Forest
items.description:
Ever wonder how a local firefighter feels after a record-breaking season of fighting wildfires on his home district? Watch live fireline footage from the Renner Fire in near the Canadian border filmed on September 12th, 2015. USFS firefighter Nolan Roth from the Colville National Forest gives his honest perspective on the 2015 fire season. Nolan answers questions covering the initial attack of the Renner Fire, how it feels to save a residence doomed to burning down, what his biggest fear is a seasoned firefighter, and words he would say  to anyone who doubts the abilities and endurance of female firefighters. . 

Filmed and edited by Fire Information Officer Kale Casey.
Media are welcome to use this footage in their news reports.
Crews and Agencies are welcome to use this footage for training, educational and inspirational purposes.

items.title: Extreme Weather | Western Wildfires : 200 Active-Duty Soldiers Will Help Fight Blazes
items.description:
Subscribe       - https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCluDjPsMX_0ROJ240uOIxeQ

AZ News         - http://aznewsupdate.blogspot.com/

Facebook        - https://www.facebook.com/pages/AZ-News/1665331173754106

Google+         - https://plus.google.com/u/0/b/109896285574278310825/109896285574278310825/posts/edit/name?hl=id

Twitter         - https://twitter.com/AZNews_Update

The government will mobilize 200 active-duty soldiers to help fight the wildfires torching the West — the first time it has taken that step in nearly a decade.

The Defense Department said the soldiers would come from Joint Base Lewis-McChord, in Washington state. They will be divided into 10 crews of 20 soldiers each and sent Sunday to a wildfire to be determined.

An estimated 95 wildfires are burning across 1.1 million acres of land in seven Western states, taxing firefighters and budgets. 

 Before deployment, the soldiers will be trained as firefighters for one day in a classroom and two days in the field, the National Interagency Fire Center said.

Active-duty military personnel have been mobilized 35 times since 1987 to fight wildfires, the center said. The last time was in 2006, when a battalion from Lewis-McChord helped fight a fire in Washington state.

In the current wildfire outbreak, California, Washington and Oregon have also mobilized the National Guard.

items.title: 10 Tanker @ Chelan,WA
items.description:
Chelan Complex Fire August 14, 2015 DC-10 Air tanker loops the lake drops low eastbound over the south side of the lake drops 12,000 gallons of slurry and saves the town! for current info see http://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/4538/          DC-10 tanker site  http://www.10tanker.com/     The U.S. Forest Service has 33 large air tankers currently activated in the United States; 15 on multi-year, full time exclusive use contracts, 9 on call when needed contracts (part time), 6 borrowed from Canada, and 4 military Modular Airborne FireFighting System (MAFFS) C-130s.

This is the highest number of air tankers we have seen working in the United States at the same time in recent years — especially the 23 that are under some sort of U.S. Forest Service contract, full time exclusive use or call when needed part time. In 2002 there were 44 large air tankers on exclusive use contracts but that number declined over the next 12 years to a low point of 9 in 2013.

Here is the breakdown:

USFS Multi-year full time exclusive use (14)
T-118 HC-130H U.S. Forest Service
T-105 MD-87 Aero Air, LLC
T-101 MD87 Aero Air, LLC
T-161 RJ85 Aero Flite, Inc.
T-160 RJ85 Aero Flite, Inc.
T-260 CL-415 Aero Flite, Inc.
T-912 DC-10 10 Tanker Air Carrier, LLC
T-131 C-130 Coulson

T-44 P2V Neptune Aviation Services, Inc.

T-910 DC-10 10 Tanker Air Carrier, LLC
T-02 BAe-146 Neptune Aviation Services, Inc.
T-01 BAe-146 Neptune Aviation Services, Inc.

T-40 BAe-146 Neptune Aviation Services, Inc.

MAFFS 9 145th Airlift Wing, North Carolina Air National Guard

It is interesting that Aero Flite has five RJ85s converted, certified, staffed, and actively fighting fires, and Neptune has five BAe-146s doing the same. A few days ago three DC-10s began working at the same time, which is a first for 10 Tanker Air Carrier.  For all fires active see http://www.nifc.gov/nicc/sitreprt.pdf

items.title: Thank You FireFighters/Chelan, WA First Creek/August 2015
items.description:
08/14/2015 lightning started fires in Chelan, WA. On 08/15 the Yacht Club was evacuated and by 08/19/15 the fire moved very close to the Yacht Club Villa with 100 homes. New Fire lines were cut and old ones were cleared and widened. Many retardant drops were made above the homes and firefighters spent 24 hours a day keeping watch on our property. In the early hours of 08/20/15 the fire exploded and it looked like our homes would be gone. Firefighters stationed themselves throughout the Villa and watered things down to help keep our property safe. The fire stopped right where the fire line was made and where retardant was dropped. The fire moved its way north. Without all the firefighters and National Guard we would have lost all 100 homes.  The club members and other area residents began serving evening meals to all the fire crews as they changed shifts. As many as 180 firefighters have been fed each evening to thank them for saving our homes and working to get this fire out. The dinners were served for a week starting 08/23/2015.  THANK YOU ALL FIREFIGHTERS !!!
Thanks to The Coleman Brothers for recording the song and Thank You to Judy Kellersberger and Mike Black for writing this great song!!!

items.title: Barter Faire OFF 2015
items.description:
In 1974, the Barter Faire was created to help a community connect and barter surplus harvest and goods for other goods needed for winter. Through the years, the Okanogan Family Faire (OFF) has become an annual event attracting vendors, musicians, artists and crafts people from communities, near and far.
 
 The Okanogan Family Faire is a non-profit organization registered in the state of Washington, Okanogan County. The purpose of this charitable corporation is to provide community events which support public education on a broad range of traditional, rural, economic, and spiritual values that reflect respect for the diversity of all people, wildlife and earth.
 
 The Okanogan Family Faire, along with Okanogan Neighbors, whose holdings include the Barter Faire site, are all composed of volunteers.  OFF/ON is the source from which has sprung the Community Cultural Center of Tonasket (CCC) & the Okanogan Community Consciousness Fund (OCCF).  Also it has provided much of the funding for the Tonasket Natural Foods Co-op.

items.title: Mount Fagan Burns 2015-08-20
items.description:
On the afternoon of Thursday, August 20, lightning struck Mount Fagan, the northeast end of the Santa Rita Mountains south of Tucson, Arizona. It does this all the time, but this time, it started a wildfire. That night, I noticed the fire, and started shooting pictures for a timelapse. I didn't know at that time that I'd be doing that for the next four nights and three days.
It quieted down and flared back up again several times, but Sunday night, a thunderstorm came through, and finally put it out for good.

"Shamanistic" Kevin MacLeod (incompetech.com)

items.title: Kelly Island from the Air - Missoula, Montana MT
items.description:
We are all alone at Kelly Island, just outside the city limits of Missoula, MT.  Serenity surrounds us on this gorgeous weekday in early September.  Located at the confluence of the Bitterroot River and the Clark Fork River, Kelly Island is a day-use area that was reserved just for us.  

The habitat of this large 648-acre, undeveloped island is a unique mix of cottonwood bottoms, large meadows, and ponderosa pine forests with remarkable wildlife populations.  The air was not as crisp and clear as it normally is in western Montana due to smoke from unprecedented forest fires burning in the Pacific Northwest. 
 
This area is home to many species of birds and other wildlife. The site is open to the public and is used for day hikes, dog walking and wildlife watching. 

Kelly Island fishing access site has just been upgraded with paved roads, defined parking, boat launch and restrooms.

Please see my other video “Stunning Change of Seasons on Kelly Island” captured in October a few years ago:  https://youtu.be/V6i8kR-dc2I

This sequence was captured with an aerial camera system on a DJI Phantom 3 quad copter, AKA drone or UAV (Unmanned Aerial Vehicle.)  The video was edited in Adobe Premier CS6.

Music used: "Dreams Become Real" Kevin MacLeod (incompetech.com) 
Licensed under Creative Commons: By Attribution 3.0
http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/

items.title: Grinnell Lake, Glacier National Park - Timelapse [4K]
items.description:
I hiked up to Grinnell Glacier Sunday morning, on the way back down I captured this. This is a timelapse I composed from pictures taken at a one second interval between 11:25 AM and noon, on Sunday, August 30, 2015. (Roughly 35 minutes to 1 minute speed-up.) The video pretty much speaks for itself, but the view was stunning. I loved watching the sun cast the clouds' shadows across the valley, and the glancing light across the lake (and even the complex wave patterns on the lake's surface [it was realllllly windy that day]). The music is "Wind Guide You" from the Skyrim soundtrack.

P.S. Yes, I know screwed up the title on the video. It's "Grinnell" and it was Sunday, August 30th not 31st.

The government of the Dominican Republic has extended the Tropical
Storm Watch southward to Isla Saona.

SUMMARY OF WATCHES AND WARNINGS IN EFFECT:

A Tropical Storm Warning is in effect for...
* Anguilla
* Saba and St. Eustatius
* St. Maarten
* St. Martin
* St. Barthelemy
* Montserrat
* St. Kitts and Nevis
* Puerto Rico
* Vieques
* Culebra
* U.S. Virgin Islands
* British Virgin Islands

A Tropical Storm Watch is in effect for...
* Guadeloupe
* Dominican Republic from the northern border with Haiti eastward
  and southward to Isla Saona
* Southeastern Bahamas
* Turks and Caicos Islands

A Tropical Storm Watch means that tropical storm conditions are
possible within the watch area, generally within 48 hours.

Interests elsewhere in the Dominican Republic should monitor the
progress of Erika.

For storm information specific to your area in the United
States, including possible inland watches and warnings, please
monitor products issued by your local National Weather Service
forecast office. For storm information specific to your area outside
the United States, please monitor products issued by your national
meteorological service.


DISCUSSION AND 48-HOUR OUTLOOK
------------------------------
At 200 PM AST (1800 UTC), the center of Tropical Storm Erika was
located near latitude 16.5 North, longitude 63.8 West.  Erika is
moving toward the west near 16 mph (26 km/h).  A turn toward the
west-northwest is forecast later today, and this general motion
should continue for the next 48 hours.  On the forecast track, the
center of Erika will move near the Virgin Islands later today,
move near or over Puerto Rico tonight, and move near or over the
Dominican Republic on Friday.

Maximum sustained winds have decreased to near 45 mph (75 km/h) with
higher gusts.  Little change in strength is forecast during the next
48 hours.

Tropical storm force winds extend outward up to 140 miles (220 km)
to the east of the center.

The estimated minimum central pressure is 1006 mb (29.71 inches).


HAZARDS AFFECTING LAND
----------------------
WIND: Tropical storm conditions are expected to continue over
portions of the warning area in the Leeward Islands for the next
few hours, and reach the Virgin Islands later today and Puerto
Rico tonight.  Tropical storm conditions are possible in the watch
area in the Leeward Islands through early this afternoon.  Tropical
storm conditions could reach portions of the watch area in the
Dominican Republic on Friday, and the southeastern Bahamas and Turks
and Caicos Islands late Friday and Friday night.

RAINFALL: Erika is expected to produce total rainfall accumulations
of 4 to 8 inches with maximum amounts of 12 inches possible across
portions of the Leeward Islands, the Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico,
the Dominican Republic, the Turks and Caicos Islands, and the
southeastern Bahamas through Saturday.

items.title: Evacuating The People of Petite Savanne By Boat #767 #Dominica\
items.description:
One of the nine villages which was declared ‘special disaster areas’ on Saturday 29 August 2015 following the passage of Tropical Storm Erika is being evacuated.

Government, on the advice of the Disaster Management Coordinator, decided to evacuate all residents of Petite Savanne on Sunday 30 August 2015.

According to the Disaster Management Coordinator, Don Corriette, one hundred and nine (109) residents have voluntarily evacuated. Of that figure, twenty-five (25) are males, thirty-eight (38) females and forty-six (46) children.

The evacuation process will continue early on Monday 31 August 2015. Those who wish to evacuate, as this is not a mandatory order, are asked to gather at the area of the Roman Catholic Church and Morne Towpis to facilitate transfer with priority consideration given to children, elderly and the physically challenged.

Family members in Roseau and environs are asked to receive evacuated residents at the Dominica Grammar School. Residents with no family accommodation will be provided for them at the Dominica Grammar School.

Family members in Roseau and environs are also asked to contact the Emergency Operations Office at Tel: 767-266-3148/3221 for further information.

Government continues to ensure that the welfare of citizens of all affected communities is safeguarded. Let us continue to pray for protection and quick recovery.

items.title: Preliminary Damage Assessment post Erika #Dominica
items.description: Watch the Prime Minister of Dominica Roosevelt Skerrit announce the  preliminary damage to Dominica assessed to date following the passage of Tropical Storm Erika. PM Skerrit updates on the homes destroyed in Petite Savanne, the hardest hit village which has now been evacuated. Issues of resettlement now up for discussion to cover schools, etc. PM Skerrit also mentions Dubique in the assessment stating that all residents of Dubique do not wish to return. PM Skerrit said that the State would take full responsibility to provide for those dramatically affected. Jungle Bay hotel was affected severely. PM Skerrit said the proprietor of the hotel said he would need to find a new site for the construction of a new hotel. The main Douglas-Charles airport has been affected. Estimated cost to restore is $39.4 million. All equipment at Douglas-Charles airport destroyed. Infrastructure (roads, bridges only) damage tallied at $612.7 million. Clearance of usable roads will cost $12 million. Agriculture is still being assessed as limited access to farms in Delices and Boetica. Infrastructure - a team from the World Bank is on the ground assessing...they are expected to prepare an independent assessment of damage to infrastructure.

items.title: Update on water supply in Dominica, one week post Erika
items.description:
Bernard Ettinoffe is the General Manager of DOWASCO, the sole water supply company on the island of Dominica. On Thursday night, Ettinoffe provided a report on water supply, as it stands, one week post Tropical Storm Erika. Tropical Storm Erika devastated several villages on Dominica by unleashing over 10 inches of rainfall which caused landslides and in excess of 30 are presumed dead.

Prior to Erika, 98% of the island had potable water. T.S. Erika affected 100% of water supply. To date, water to 70% of population of Dominica restored. Indiscriminate use of fire hydrants to clean roads, driveways of concern to water supply company; appealing to communities to cease this practice. 

No word on restoration of water supply to the community of Coulibistrie. Supply to the community of Grand Bay has been affected. Only 35% of the community in that area receiving water supply. Water supply to the community of Calibishie should be restored by Saturday September 5.

Areas where no progress: Bagatelle, Fond St. Jean, Petite Savanne, Dubique. Access is a problem. Delices and Boetica have no damage to lines, restoration likely in two days time. Colihaut, Dublanc, Bioche should have water supply restored by September 7.

Water supply to the community of Giraudel affected severely. Work required. Water supply to the communities of Wesley, Woodford Hill, Marigot affected; targeting September 7 to make progress in these areas.

Water supply to Salisbury still affected. Temporary intake being worked on. Villagers offering their assistance. Hoping by September 6, some water supply to Salisbury can be restored.

Sewage network damaged in Roseau, Canefield, and Jimit. Pipeline under Bath Estate bridge being replaced; 50% complete. Access to sewage system in the community of Jimit prohibitive. 

Asking customers to be patient as restoration is being worked on.

items.title: Jerusalem, Israel in haze - A massive Middle East sandstorm
items.description:
Zahi Shaked A tour guide in Israel and his camera zahigo25@walla.com +972-54-6905522 tel  סיור עם מורה הדרך ומדריך הטיולים צחי שקד 0546905522
My name is Zahi Shaked
In 2000 I became a registered liscenced tourist guide.
My dedication in life is to pass on the ancient history of the Holy Land.

Following upon many years of travel around the world, which was highlighted by a very exciting emotional and soul-searching meeting with the Dalai Lama, I realized that I had a mission. To pass on the the history of the Holy Land, its religions, and in particular, the birth and development of Christianity.

In order to fulfill this "calling" in the best way possible, I studied in depth, visited, and personally experienced each and every important site of the ancient Christians. I studied for and received my first bachelors degree in the ancient history of the Holy Land, and am presently completing my studies for my second degree.(Masters)

 

Parralel to my studies, and in order to earn a living, I was employed for many years in advertising. What I learned there was how to attract the publics attention, generate and, increase interest, and assimilate information.  All this I use as tools to describe, explain and deepen the interest in the sites that we visit. From my experience, I have learned that in this way, the Holy Land becomes more than just history, and that the large stones that we see scattered about in dissaray, join together one by one until they become - a Byzantine Church. This also happens when I lead a group of Pilgrims in the Steps of Jesus. We climb to the peak of Mount Precipice, "glide" over the land to the Sea of Galilee, land on the water and "see" the miracle which enfolds before us. This is a many faceted experience. Not only history which you will remember and cherish, but an experience which I hope will be inplanted in your hearts and minds, and will accompany you all the days of your life.

items.title: At least 111 killed by falling crane at Grand Mosque in Mecca
items.description:
At least 111 killed by falling crane at Grand Mosque in Mecca
At least 111 people were killed when a crane toppled over at Mecca's Grand Mosque on Friday, Saudi Arabia's Civil Defence authority said, less than two weeks before Islam's annual haj pilgrimage.

At least 238 people were wounded, Saudi Arabia's Civil Defence body said.

"All those who were wounded and the dead have been taken to hospital. There are no casualties left at the location," General Suleiman al-Amr, director general of the Civil Defence Authority, told al-Ikhbariya television. Strong wind and rains had uprooted trees and rocked cranes in the area, he said.

A statement by a spokesman for the administration of the mosques in Mecca and Medina said the crane smashed into the part of the Grand Mosque where worshippers circle the Kaaba - the black-clad cube towards which the world's 1.6 billion Muslims face to pray.

Pictures circulating on social media showed pilgrims in bloodied robes and debris from a part of the crane that appeared to have crashed through a ceiling.

Saudi authorities go to great lengths to prepare for the millions of Muslims who converge on Mecca to perform the sacred pilgrimage. Last year, they reduced the numbers permitted to make the haj pilgrimage on safety grounds because of construction work to enlarge the Grand Mosque.

The haj, one of the largest religious gatherings in the world, has been prone to disasters in the past, mainly from stampedes as pilgrims rush to complete rituals and return home. Hundreds of pilgrims died in such a crush in 2006.

Saudi authorities have since spent vast sums to expand the main haj sites and improve Mecca's transport system, in an effort to prevent more disasters.

Security services often ring Islam's sacred city with checkpoints and other measures to prevent people arriving for the pilgrimage without authorization.

Those procedures, aimed at reducing crowd pressure which can lead to stampedes, fires and other hazards, have been intensified in recent years as security threats grow throughout the Middle East.

items.title: Down crane in Tel Aviv
items.description:
Stormy winds blow down Tel Aviv crane.
First winter storm blows down crane, leaves thousands in darkness.
Strong winds and rain battered Israel on Sunday (October 25), causing power outages across the region and toppling a crane in Tel Aviv.

In central Tel Aviv, Israel's business capital, a crane at a construction site was blown down by the strong winds and fell towards a main highway, causing no injuries or damage.

According to Israeli media, tens of thousands of people remained without power as a result of flooding and trees that collapsed. The rainstorm is expected to last until Thursday (October 29), according to the Israel meteorological service.

items.title: Sand River in Iraq, All you need to know about it, a rare phenomenon Viral Video 2015
items.description: The video footage shows a river of hail running through the desert following a storm on November 16, 2015. It has been named as the 'sand river'. As per the online reports, heavy rains over the past few weeks triggered floods that killed dozens of people in Iraq and caused widespread damage in Egypt, Israel, Jordan and Saudi Arabia.                                      In arid environments, it is common for flash floods to travel rapidly downstream to areas which usually do not receive any rainfall. So, the river appears in the downstream area despite any local indication of the rainfall. Reportedly, in this case, the illusion is compounded by the fact that a significant hail has fallen upstream.

items.title: Spruce Fire Time-lapse
items.description:
This time-lapse video shows the lightning-caused Spruce Fire burning through mature, lodgepole pine forest. Much of the fire is burning through accumulated dead and downed trees and other vegetation (white smoke). When the fire picks up enough energy to climb into the tops of the trees, the smoke becomes black. You can see isolated torching of groups of trees in the beginning of the video and then a crown run, with visible flames, towards the end of the video. Some areas burn hotter and more intense, others areas are skipped entirely, leaving pockets of unburned vegetation. This "mosaic" pattern of burning is typical in wildland fires.

Fire has shaped the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem for thousands of years. Fire promotes habitat diversity by removing forest overstory and helps return nutrients to the soil more quickly. Learn more at http://www.nps.gov/yell/learn/nature/fireconsequences.htm.

items.title: hilights :Japan hit by flooding and landslides
items.description:
Areas of Japan are on high alert as heavy rains and flooding continue for a second day, following Typhoon Etau.
Hundreds of thousands of people have been advised to evacuate their homes, amid reports of landslides and flooding - one person has been reported missing.
Typhoon Etau brought winds of up to 125km/h (78mph) to central Aichi prefecture on Wednesday before moving out to sea.
But heavy rain continued to drench eastern Japan on Thursday.
"This is a scale of downpour that we have not experienced before. Grave danger could be imminent," the chief forecaster at the Japan Meteorological Agency, Takuya Deshimaru, told an emergency press conference.
The hardest-hit area on Thursday was north of the capital, in Ibaraki and Tochigi prefectures.

items.title: Typhoon Etau slams into Japanese mainland
items.description:
Typhoon Etau slammed into Japan on Wednesday causing injuries as torrential rain sparked landslides and flooding with more than half a million people advised to evacuate, including in suburban Tokyo.

Rail and air services were also disrupted after the storm, packing winds of up to 125 kilometres (78 miles) per hour, landed in central Aichi prefecture shortly after 10:00 am local time (0100 GMT).

Television footage showed cars sloshing through flooded streets and houses submerged, as pedestrians waded through water that reached their knees.

Some areas had power outages and parts of Tokyo saw flooding as authorities advised about 900,000 people in the capital and other parts of the country to leave their homes because of the risk of landslides, public broadcaster NHK reported.

Local media said more than a dozen people were injured, including a 77-year-old woman who broke her leg after falling in strong winds.

DRAMATIC MOMENT: Aerial Rescue Over a Floods Hit House in Joso, Japan (AMATEUR VIDEO) 09.10.2015

https://youtu.be/0XipuzSvZ4Q


Japan's Typhoon Etau sparks flooding and evacuations

Areas of Japan are on high alert as heavy rains and flooding continue for a second day, following Typhoon Etau.

Hundreds of thousands of people have been advised to evacuate their homes, amid reports of landslides and flooding - one person has been reported missing.

Typhoon Etau brought winds of up to 125km/h (78mph) to central Aichi prefecture on Wednesday before moving out to sea.

But heavy rain continued to drench eastern Japan on Thursday.

"This is a scale of downpour that we have not experienced before. Grave danger could be imminent," the chief forecaster at the Japan Meteorological Agency, Takuya Deshimaru, told an emergency press conference.

The hardest-hit area on Thursday was north of the capital, in Ibaraki and Tochigi prefectures.

The Fire and Disaster and Management Agency said 15 people had been injured, two seriously, both of whom were elderly women knocked over by strong winds.

Local media has reported one person missing after a landslide hit a house in Kanuma, Tochigi prefecture.

Some areas had power outages and parts of Tokyo saw flooding as authorities on Wednesday advised about 900,000 people in the capital and other parts of the country to leave their homes.

The extreme weather also disrupted transport links, with dozens of flights cancelled and bullet train services partially suspended.

Last month, powerful Typhoon Goni hit Japan's southernmost main island of Kyushu, killing at least one person and injuring 70 others.

"This is a scale of downpour that we have not experienced before. Grave danger could be imminent," the chief forecaster at the Japan Meteorological Agency, Takuya Deshimaru, told an emergency press conference.

The hardest-hit area on Thursday was north of the capital, in Ibaraki and Tochigi prefectures.

The Fire and Disaster and Management Agency said 15 people had been injured, two seriously, both of whom were elderly women knocked over by strong winds.

Local media has reported one person missing after a landslide hit a house in Kanuma, Tochigi prefecture.

Some areas had power outages and parts of Tokyo saw flooding as authorities on Wednesday advised about 900,000 people in the capital and other parts of the country to leave their homes.

The extreme weather also disrupted transport links, with dozens of flights cancelled and bullet train services partially suspended.

Last month, powerful Typhoon Goni hit Japan's southernmost main island of Kyushu, killing at least one person and injuring 70 others.

Ministerpräsident Shinzo Abe erklärt, dass die Regierung ihr Bestes tun wird, um mit der Katastrophe umzugehen. Nach einem Taifun kam es durch heftige Regenfälle zu schweren Überschwemmungen, Erdrutschen und Dammbrüchen im Osten Japans. Ein Sprecher des japanischen Wetterdienstes sagte, dass es um ein bislang unerreichtes Ausmaß handele. Hunderte Häuser wurden aus ihren Fundamenten gerissen. Etliche Menschen müssen mit Hubschraubern gerettet werden. In Josu, nur 50 Kilometer von Tokio entfernt, herrschen die gleichen Bilder. Im havarierten Atomkraftwerk Fukushima kam es ebenfalls zu Überschwemmungen und laut der Betreiberfirma Tepco wurden hunderte Tonnen radioaktiv verseuchtes Wasser ins Meer gespült.

items.title: Japan floods Hundreds trapped as floods sweep Japan raw video
items.description:
Tens of thousands of people have been evacuated from the flood affected areas of Japan. Heavy rain pounded the country and caused floods, sending waters polluted by radiation into the ocean at the Fukushima nuclear plant.

Floods were waist-high in some areas and rescuers had to rush to get people to safety as a wide area was overflowing with the wake of Typhoon Etau.

Takuya Deshimaru, a forecaster told an emergency press conference on Thursday “This is a scale of downpour that we have not experienced before. Grave danger could be imminent.”

Special warnings were issued by the Japan Meteorological Agency for Tochigi and Ibaraki regions, north of Tokyo, asking caution against mudslides and flooding. More than a dozen people were injured. Amongst them was a 77-year-old woman who broke her leg after falling in strong winds.

Etau smashed into Japan on Wednesday and moved out into the eastern Sea of Japan by the end of the day. Rain kept pouring in the country. 60 centimetres of rain has been measured in parts of central Tochigi.

items.title: Dramatic Rescue Footage: JAPAN FLOOD Ibaraki Ken - 9/10/2015
items.description:
Heavy flooding over eastern Japan washed away houses and forced residents to their rooftops, desperate for rescue by military helicopters. The raging brown floodwaters spawned from Tropical Storm Etau, which has dumped 60 centimeters (2 feet) of rain over some areas since Monday. Combine that with several weeks of near-daily rainfall, and Ibaraki and Tochigi prefectures are now deluged and unrecognizable. "Tochigi Prefecture is facing a grave danger and is in an emergency situation," Japan Meteorological Agency Spokesman Takuya Deshimaru said. "It is experiencing unprecedented downpour."
More than 170,000 people have been evacuated, officials said. Those who didn't leave found their houses submerged within minutes. The latest evacuation advisory came for the city of Sendai, where more than 200,000 residents in three wards were warned they may need to leave their homes due to rising water.
Members of the Japanese Self Defense Forces dropped from helicopter lines to pluck stranded residents from their roofs. Two by two, they swung precariously over the raging currents as they were pulled back up to the aircraft.
The Self Defense Forces had rescued 101 people by Thursday afternoon, a spokesman said.
Ibaraki prefecture said 70 people out of the 176 there who had called for help had been rescued.
Additionally, local firefighters rescued 20 people, an official from Joso City's Information Office said. Nine people were reported missing in that city, authorities said.

items.title: Japan floods: Rescue work continues after deadly disaster

At least two people have been confirmed killed and 25 people are still missing across the regions worst hit.
Many people had to wait overnight to be rescued from the roofs of their homes near Joso city, after the Kinugawa River burst its banks on Thursday

Amateur Videos | Valley Fire in Lake County, California | Raw Footage

COBB, Calif. (KCRA) —In less than six hours, a raging wildfire in Lake County haThe so-called Valley Fire, which broke out about 1:24 p.m. Saturday off Highway Valley Road and Bottle Rock Road in Cobb, remains zero percent contained.

Additional evacuations have been ordered for Butts Canyon Road to the Napa County line, including Berryessa Estates and Highway 29 from Tubbs Lane, Calistoga to highways 29 and 53 in Lower Lake. Evacuations are also in place for High Valley Road, Bottle Rock Road and Big Canyon Road.

Four firefighters suffered second-degree burns while battling the wildfire and were taken to the UC Davis Medical Center where they remain in stable condition, Cal Fire spokesman Daniel Berlant said.

Officials issued a mandatory evacuation order for the Cobb, Hidden Valley Lake, High Valley Road, Bottle Rock Road, Harbin Hot Springs communities Saturday afternoon.

There are also several road closures in the area, including Highway 29 at Lower Lake to Middletown.

No structures have been damaged or destroyed, according to Cal Fire.

The Valley Fire is zero percent contained and the cause is under investigation.

Stay with KCRA 3 News for more on this developing story. s grown to 10,000 acres Saturday as additional evacuations have been issued, according to Cal Fire.

items.title: Escaping Anderson Springs during Valley Fire
items.description:
Driving out of Anderson Springs 9/12/15 at 8:30 pm

We were the last house at the very back of the Springs, down in a gulch, so we had no views of the surrounding mountains. There was no smoke or ash coming our way, and there were no sirens or air support nearby, so we honestly didn't know how close it was. Once we drove up out of our gulch, we realized how close it was. There were no sirens or air support because there was zero firefighting effort in Anderson Springs. (This is NOT a dig at the firefighters, by the way! There was just way too much fire in every direction, and they didn't have the resources to send to Anderson Springs. I have no hard feelings against the firefighters, they were busy risking their lives elsewhere! Anderson Springs) So anyway, that is how we ended up leaving WAY too late. In retrospect, we should have gone out for a drive to find out what was going on, but we were a little preoccupied with packing.

items.title: Valley Fire in Cobb, CA
items.description: I was in Cobb at a house we own when the Valley Fire erupted on September 12, 2015 less than four miles away.  The wind was gusting 20 miles an hour for much of the day and lots of pine cones and needles had been raining down.  Looking up into the trees I saw how stressed many of them were from years of drought and an infestation of beetles.  Not realizing the extent and rapidity of the fire's spread, I stayed in Cobb until 5:30 pm, and found my way down blocked in all but one direction.  It sounded at times like a battle zone with helicopters overhead and explosions from bursting propane tanks and pine trees.  The high winds broadcast burning embers in every direction, making it very difficult for any kind of effort to contain the explosive growth of the inferno.  Firefighters had to make difficult choices about which houses to defend. It is hard to grasp the absolute devastation to our extended community.  So far I've not been able to get into the area to see what is left, but we assume our house and many more in the area are gone.

items.title: Valley Fire 2015
items.description: This is footage of the Valley Fire in Lake County CA 2015. I brought the family over the Hopland grade then into Clearlake Oaks to the Moose Lodge. The Red Cross had tried to bully their way in, which was happening alot unfortunately. They threatened to shut camps down if Red Cross wasn't allowed to take over, then they don'y help with clothes and other things, only food, and they are the first to stand in line for food themselves. I saw many facebook posts of personal stories that aligned with this type of behavior, sad. I noticed none of those stories made it to the news. We brought clothes, water, blankets, and kids toys. I didn't take footage of the camp because I thought it may be embarrassing to those staying there as it was chaos and sadness. I have several friends that lost everything to this devastating fire. I thought it was important to see first hand what was happening, and for my kids to see it and feel what it was like to see something like this and be able to help, if only a little. The video does not do justice the experience we had, seeing melted cars in between the houses down the sidestreets, the burnt smell, black hills right behind all the businesses and houses, all the emergency workers, a huge sense of loss in general.  Anyway I added the music to enhance the effect, and my actual narration I feel is terrible.  I hope these people get back on track soon and return to life as they knew it.

items.title: LIVE Typhoon Dujuan Hits Zhuangwei Township Taiwan
Hurricane Typhoon Day｜What Do People Do？｜Taiwan Vlog 颱風天：大家都做什麼？
items.description:
From typhoon Soudelor, I've come to realize that when it comes to typhoon/hurricane day, people in Taiwan actually don't stay coped up at home waiting for winds and rain to pass. They, on  the contrary, utilize the day to help out the economy by shopping, going to movies and dining out. I guess typhoons/hurricanes just happened way too often that the people are immune to the danger this nature could bring.

But I can't help but blame those greedy business people who authorize their employees to risk the safety coming into work on typhoon days in order to make extra cash. It's because the malls and the theatres are opened that draw the people out or they would have be content staying home watching TV! This would therefore save the government a lot of troubles since there would also be fewer accidents on the road.

Anyway, thanks for watching! xx stay safe!

items.title: Super Typhoon Dujuan Taiwan || 24 injured, hundreds of thousands without electricity
items.description:
Super Typhoon Dujuan has battered Taiwan with torrential rain and fierce winds leaving 24 injured, while China issued its top alert as the storm approached the mainland.

The storm struck the island's north-eastern tip earlier than expected after picking up speed as it approached, with more than 7,000 people evacuated in advance.
Key points

    Super typhoon Dujuan hits Taiwan early
    24 are injured, hundreds of thousands affected
    China also braces for storm just weeks after Typhoon Soudelor damaged both countries 

Most of the 24 people hurt suffered minor injuries, the island's Emergency Operation Centre said, many of them hit by flying debris.

More than 330,000 homes are without electricity after almost 1 million lost power at the height of the storm, the emergency centre said.

About 2,000 people were spending the night in temporary shelters
GIF: Super Typhoon Dujuan approaching Taiwan at 3:00pm AEST on Monday. (Supplied: Japan Meteorological Agency)

Waves crashed along the east coast and the capital Taipei was swept with wind and rain.

At 9:00pm local time (11:00pm AEST) Dujuan was 30 kilometres south-east of central Taichung city, the Central Weather Bureau said.

The bureau said "virtually the whole island" was at risk of severe wind and rain, with authorities warning downpours could trigger landslides.

"It picked up speed in the past few hours, but will slow somewhat after hitting the mountains in the east," an official from the bureau said.

Dujuan made landfall in the northern county of Yilan, where some areas have seen more than 500 millimetres of rain in the last 24 hours.

Panicked visitors to the island's east — many of whom had headed there for the Mid-Autumn Festival long weekend — crammed onto trains away from the eastern cities of Hualien and Taitung before services were suspended.

High-speed rail services in the west were also cancelled.

Authorities warned that coastal areas could be particularly dangerous as tides are affected by the current "supermoon" — a rare astrological event in which the moon appears brighter and larger.

This is because the moon has reached its closest orbital point to Earth and therefore has a stronger gravitational pull than usual.

The storm intensified as it approached Taiwan, with gusts of 227 kilometres per hour.

items.title: Super Typhoon lashes Taiwan, killing 2, injuring more than 300
items.description:
A typhoon struck mainland China on Tuesday after lashing Taiwan, where it killed two, injured hundreds and left hundreds of thousands without power or water.

Typhoon Dujuan passed through Taiwan for three hours on Monday night, bringing high winds and rain. Several domestic and international flights and trains were suspended as the storm approached.

Taiwan's Central News Agency, citing the government's emergency operations center, said Tuesday that the typhoon had left two people dead, 324 injured and six mountain climbers missing. A total of 710,000 households were without electricity and 370,000 without water.

Bon Jovi canceled concerts planned for Monday and Tuesday in Taiwan because of the storm, which were to be the first ones there by the American rock band in 20 years, event promoter Live Nation Taiwan said on Facebook. Bon Jovi had added the second date in Taiwan earlier this month along with a new concert in Bangkok after performances in Beijing and Shanghai were abruptly canceled, reportedly over the band's inclusion of a picture of the Dalai Lama in a video that angered Chinese authorities.

Typhoon Dujuan made landfall in southeastern Fujian province Tuesday morning, packing maximum wind speeds of 119 kilometers per hour (74 mph) near its center, before weakening into a tropical storm, according to the National Meteorological Center. It was moving northwestward at a speed of 20 kph (12 mph) and was due to reach neighboring Jiangxi province by Tuesday night.

Ahead of its arrival, thousands of fishing boats returned to shore, ports were closed and in one city classes at middle schools, primary schools and kindergartens were suspended, according to the official Xinhua News Agency.

Hurricane Joaquin from Hell -- Bermuda : 10-04-2015
items.description:
As seen live on http://PortBermudaWebcam.com

Looking and sounding more like a scene from James Cameron's movie ALIENS, this video clip was from around midnight on Sunday 10-4-2015 as now Cat 1 hurricane Joaquin passed by Bermuda. Earlier in the evening, our host building -- Commissioner's House at the National Museum of Bermuda -- took a direct hit to the roof, part of which was destroyed. Our camera pole appeared to fall to the roof floor, only giving us a view inside the now open roof space. Screaming winds of 60+ mph continued to rage and amazingly, our equipment continued to stream both video and audio. This is what you see a glimpse of here!

Extent of the damage is unknown at this time but could be severe. Morning light will reveal all.

items.title: After the Rain
items.description:
We had over 15" of rain over the last week. Other areas are in an emergency state with 1000 year historic flooding. We are good.

The road is washed out a little, muddy but passable. Water level of the stream and pond is down 18" or more, but it's still a bit high.

Anyway, there is no danger of flooding at the house. Water would need to get another 4 to 6 feet higher before there was a problem for us. Some folks had worried about us considering the rain.

This is a just a record of how we have fared. We can use this as a comparison when we get a tropical storm or hurricane.

items.title: Issues Of The Day - Hurricane Joaquin Survivor Account
The 3 little kittens abandoned during Hurricane Joaquin.
items.description:
Hurricane Joaquin's heavy weather arrived (Oct.2015) with three days straight of heavy rain, that caused flooding. We live in the area of the Waccamaw River (SC) and we had some flooding ourselves, but not as terrible as those that live right on the river.

Once the rain and water subsided and the first rays of sunlight shined through, we opened up our crawl space to let air get to it, checked for damages around the house and under.

While we were busy with that, Sara, our beagle, ran up under the house and wouldn’t come out. She was barking and yelling the entire time.

Into an hour of her barking, my husband finally decided to check it out. She ignored any demands from him. 

Over the course of an hour, she finds a way to get under the porch, still under the house. She barked until my son came home from work; which was about an hour. He was the only one that could fit inside the small box like hole where she was. When he finally got to her, he brought her out, but also found something else …three little kittens.

We do not know where the mother is. We plan on keeping them.

Please subscribe to stay up to date with their story. I'm sure they'd love that!

items.title: Hydroplaning | Hurricane Joaquin 2015 | Driving Instruction [U.S.]
items.description:
Hurricane weather idiots ..hydroplaning and not learning from it, in Myrtle Beach, SC, Hwy 501; extremely high conditions, during Hurricane Joaquin 2015. Can't explain stupid.

How to avoid hydroplaning?

- Keep your tires properly inflated
- Rotate and replace tires when necessary
- Slow down when roads are wet: the faster you drive, the harder it is for your tires to scatter the water
- Stay away from puddles and standing water
- Avoid driving in outer lanes where water tends to accumulate (not completely true for those states that have roads built for hurricanes/tropical storms.)
- Try to drive in the tire tracks left by the cars in front of you
- Turn off cruise control
- Drive in a lower gear
- Avoid hard braking
- Try not to make sharp or quick turns

via: http://www.safemotorist.com/articles/Hydroplaning_Basics.aspx

items.title: Tornado strike Guangzhou Canton video of lightening explosion several death dozens injury 颱風十月掠嶺南
items.description:
Five people were killed and at least 168 injured on Sunday as rare tornadoes ravaged several parts of southern China’s Guangdong province, mainland media reports.

Typhoon Mujigae – reportedly the most powerful tropical storm in history to have struck Guangdong during October – reached landfall on the mainland near the city of Zhanjiang, in Guangdong, just after 2pm on Sunday.

Mujigae brought with it powerful tornados, which were recorded in Shunde district in Foshan, Panyu district in Guangzhou and Haifeng of Shanwei city by the Guangdong Provincial Meteorological Bureau, the Xinhua news agency said.
Two of those who died were killed in Panyu and another two died in Shunde as tornados ripped apart houses in the area. 

In the provincial capital, Guangzhou, plans for emergency power and water supplies were introduced on Sunday after tornadoes brought down several power lines and left thousands of residents in the districts of Panyu and Haizhu without electricity.

Thousands of people had flocked to Guangdong and Hainan over the weekend during the week-long National Day holiday.

items.title: FOOTAGE : Mujigae Typhoon wreaks havoc in China
items.description:
At least seven people have been killed after a typhoon with winds in excess of 180km/h battered the coast of south China. The storm also unleashed a rare tornado, which ravaged Guangdong province, bringing down buildings and knocking out power grids.
Typhoon Mujigae is reportedly the most powerful tropical storm in history according to the Guangdong Provincial Meteorological Bureau. It made landfall in the province of Guangdong and also unleashed tornados, which were recorded in Foshan and Guangzhou.

items.title: Terrifying moment - Typhoon Mujigae unleashes tornadoes across Guangdong China
items.description:
Huge tornadoes prompted by Typhoon Mujigae yesterday ripped through several cities in the province of Guangdong,  southern China.

Videos taken by local residents show swirling columns of wind more than 330 feet high sweeping through residential areas and farmlands in the cities of Foshan, Panyu and Shanwei, picking up houses and cars like toys.

The tornadoes were brought by Typhoon Mujigae, which made landfall at around 2pm on Sunday on China's southern coast, reported People's Daily Online. At least six were killed and more than 200 were injured in howling winds of up to 112 miles per hour.
Huge tornados formed after Typhoon Mujigae landed near the city of Zhanjiang in Guangdong, southern China, yesterday afternoon - with winds of up to 112 miles per hour.

As of 10am today local time, six people have been reported dead and 215 injured in the extreme weather. Large areas have been left without electricity, water or telecommunications networks, according to Xinhua News Agency.

Chinese authorities have issued the highest 'red alert' emergency response in southern coastal provinces.

High winds caught several fishing vessels stranded out at sea, with 16 fishermen missing and one dead.

Three more people were killed and 80 injured by the tornado rampaging through the city of Foshan.

items.description: This video shows paddling a displacement race board downwind in 10 knot (down breezing) conditions. Once you get up to speed, and trim the board correctly (weight back from the centre) it is possible to paddle fast, glide and cut through the waves in front without pearling. Filmed using 3rd Person Mount and GoPro 4 in Repulse Bay, Hong Kong

items.title: SUP Upwind - Downwind in Typhoon Mujigae
items.description:
There is a lot posted about awesome downwind runs, but sometimes it is a battle just to get to the start of the downwind leg..

In this vid shot in the aftermath of Typhoon Mujigae, I had to use every trick in the book to get to the upwind point, waiting for squalls to blow through and then doing sprints between moored boats, then hanging onto them, walking along the shore, kneeling, choking down etc etc. It took me 20 minutes to go the first 1km / 0.625 mile.  The key is conserving energy, and using every possible advantage, natural or man-made, to get you to the destination. The 2nd km was easier and then it was a wild downwind run in blown out conditions. 

Sometimes it is the journey that is more memorable than the destination...

items.title: SUP Downwinding - Cape D'Aguilar - Hong Kong
items.description:
SUP Downwinding from Cape D'Aguilar - Nov 2015. 

One of our favourite places to downwind is a place called Cape D’Aguilar where the Easterly swell gets squeezed between the south eastern-most tip of Hong Kong and Beaufort Island, pushing the swell upwards for a while and then releasing it into some glorious runners which are hard to get into. We call it the Cape D'Ag run and “Our little piece of Maui”.

Speeds vary considerably depending on which way the tide is running.. On this day it was running against us and with a 19 knot  / 35kph / 22mph easterly wind, the runners were hard to get into.

Board: SIC F16v3
3rd Person Mount
GoPro 4 Black

items.title: SUP Downwinding - The L2CC Run Part 2 - (Lamma - Cheung Chau Island)
items.description: This video shows the second 2/3rds of the 10.4 km / 6.5 mile Lamma Island - Cheung Chau (L2CC) downwinding Run from Kat Tsai Wan near the Lamma Power Power Station to the Po Yu Wan on the SW Tip of Cheung Chau Island. This is the first time this route was tried by SUP on Dec 5, 2015 in winds gusting to 30 knot, 55kph, 34 mph. The beginning of the run is in the lee of the wind and the waves start out relatively groomed and lined up. Very quickly they start to grow and by 1/2 way are joined with ground swell that sweeps round from the Southern Side of Lamma. This is challenging run at the end, where the start is only reachable by boat. Whilst there is relatively little shipping between Lamma and Cheung Chau it is still necessary to be aware of ships, and a safety boat is recommended. Boards used in this crossing are a SIC Maui F16v3 and SIC Bullet 14v1 TWC. Leashes, and PFDs worn. PLBs, Phones and whistles carried.

items.title: Collecting Megalodon Teeth after the South Carolina Flood of 2015
items.description: We had a pretty dramatic weather event here in South Carolina - a thousand year flood that dropped as much as 2 feet of rain on much of the Charleston - Dorchester - Berkeley County and Columbia corridor. Hundreds of roads were closed, many bridges washed out, government offices closed, curfews in effect to keep motorists away from dangerous floods. Most rivers are well above flood stage. As you might expect from watching this channel, rain usually brings fossil hunting success so I have been itching to get out for days and collect. I knew there had to be some really good stuff exposed in my favorite creeks, so I hit one of them today and it was a home run. The entire thing has been swept clean and the bottom changed completely. Teeth were exposed everywhere! I found angustidens, mako, and even a rare megalodon tooth - my first complete big one from this site ever.

items.title: Umauma Falls & Zipline eXperience on the Big Island of Hawaii
MISSED GT ULUA USING CRAB!
items.description:
It was a very windy day at West Loch's Chocolate Beach all day as the approaching Storm Oho was just upgraded this morning to Hurricane status. I decided to use whole Blue Pincher Crab as my dominant bait for today. I brought frozen crabs, and squid for bait for my crab nets so i could replenish my frozen crabs for live crabs. Today my bowling partner Alric Kutara joined me for a relaxing day of fishing.

After baiting my all Penn rig (Battalion rod with a Fierce 5K reel spooled with Power Pro 30lb Spectra braid) with a whole frozen Blue Pincher Crab an estimated 30lb White Trevally Jack (known as an Ulua in Hawaii) violently swallowed the whole crab bait and took off. The hit was extremely powerful! The rod came crashing down on the initial hit and looked like it was going to snap in 2. By the time i got to the rod the fish was covering a lot of ground swimming at a high rate of speed. 

The fish tried to run the mangroves to shake off the hook. I had to set the reel to max drag to pull it out, almost ripped the rod out of my hand. All this time the fish was changing directions & i could feel it shaking it's head. It was all i could do just to reel in the slacked line as the fish's speed was impressive running in only 4-5ft. Finally the fish spun around and came directly at me. It dove under the pier i was standing on and busted the 30lb Spectra main line after it snagged like it was nothing.

When the fish ran at me i looked down and saw how large it was through that silty water when it shot underneath me for a split second. The length was roughly 4ft and the body was thick. The back was upright and blueish/white. This fish was hooked before. It knew that either running the mangroves or going under the pier would most likely cut the line. It knew this because that's exactly what it did as it was obviously hooked before and knew how to escape. Smart fish!

This is the 3rd GT i've hooked here, all using whole crab as bait. Alric had a blast participating in this short fight and now he wants his turn at catching a big fish. Goes to show the CRAB WORKS BABY!

items.title: Powerful Super Typhoon Koppu Bringing Life-Threatening Flooding, Damaging Winds to Philippines
items.description:
Super Typhoon Koppu will put lives and property across Luzon Island of the Philippines in danger through early next week.

Koppu developed into a typhoon early Friday morning local time and is currently approaching the northern Philippines. Disruptive wind shear had prevented Koppu from any significant strengthening through Thursday; however, Koppu has moved into an area of low wind shear prior to its expected landfall in Luzon late Saturday evening or Sunday morning, allowing it to strengthen into a super typhoon. With the increased strength, Koppu remains a very dangerous cyclone as it moves through Luzon this weekend.

"Rapid intensification is likely to occur right before Koppu reaches Luzon," stated AccuWeather Meteorologist Adam Douty on Friday. "Koppu will be the equivalent of a Category 4 hurricane by landfall."
In addition to Koppu's increased strength as it approached the Philippines, the system also has slowed down significantly. The combination of a powerful and slow-moving typhoon could spell a disastrous situation for residents and communities in its path, which will be northern Luzon Island in Koppu's case.

Koppu crawled toward towards northern Luzon Island throughout the day Saturday, local time. Koppu is expected to make landfall around midnight, Sunday morning, local time, and then slowly begin to turn northward. How quickly Koppu tracks north will determine the duration of life-threatening conditions for northern Luzon.
While damaging winds are a concern, the greatest threat will be life-threatening flooding from days of torrential rainfall.

"A total of 300 to 600 mm (12 to 24 inches) of rain is expected to be widespread," stated Douty. There will even be localized amounts upwards or in excess of 900 mm (36 inches). Such rain is sure to trigger severe and life-threatening flooding and mudslides.

"The most significant rain will fall in the mountainous terrain of northern Luzon," added Douty.

Residents in Baguio, Bangui, Aparri, Tuguegarao and Pagudpud are among those across northern Luzon who are being urged to prepare for the impending severe flood danger. Heed all evacuation orders and begin making plans to seek shelter away from areas prone to flooding and mudslides.

items.title: flash flood in San Luis, Philippines, as Typhoon Koppu continues to dump rain
items.description:
Heavy downpour has triggered a flash flood in the hard-hit province of Aurora, forcing residents to evacuate from their homes amid the onslaught of typhoon "Lando" in San Luis.

This came after the Diteki river has overflowed, trapping some of the residents of Barangay San Isidro in their homes as they struggle with heavy rains and winds brought by Lando early Sunday morning.

With the flood's rapid current and considerable depth, the residents are having a hard time moving out of the danger zone, even with rescuers reaching out to them with ropes and rubber boats.

When asked why the residents did not evacuate earlier despite the threat posed by typhoon Lando, they said it was the first time that the river has reached their houses.

Local authorities are now focusing on the barangay as they send trucks to transport the residents from the area to evacuation centers.

Meanwhile, the provincial government of Aurora has yet to establish contact with the towns in the province after communication lines were downed in the past hours. Foremost of these towns is Casiguran, which is isolated due to landslides.

Authorities said no casualty has been recorded in the province so far as they hope for the best in line with the 'zero casualty' goal.

items.title: Typhoon Lando Philippine Weather Video Bulacan Luzon
items.description:
I knew Typhoon Lando was entering our area of Bulacan, Luzon Philippines. As you may have seen in our last video everything was in disarray after the wall's new paint job. I had wanted to make a before and after video. When I started the video it was so nice outside I never even mentioned a typhoon was coming. When I started rearranging the plants I never thought typhoon Lando would effect my project. As you see the weather looked beautiful. I never thought the weather could change so rapidly as to effect my project and provide me with a weather video. The arranging did not get completed before the typhoon hit. In fact it will take four days before it is completed, we are finishing it today. Typhoons are amazing storms, the larger typhoons are much like hurricanes are in the USA. The big difference is the Philippines experiences about 20 per year,


My retirement in the Philippines began in Sept 6, 2012. I filled a backpack with drawing/art material to write and headed overseas to live a dream. I play and make videos of my life in the Philippines. My life overseas has been the adventure of my lifetime. This Vlog of life here is for my memories and show my friends and family back in the USA the Filipino lifestyle and show the world the joy of overseas retirement..
