items.title: PHILIPPINES: PROTESTS AGAINST CONSTITUTIONAL CHANGES
items.description:
Tens of thousands of people have protested against changes to the Philippines' constitution proposed by President Joseph Estrada. 



The president says he wants to change the constitution to attract more foreign investment but the protestors say that sets a dangerous precedent for more political amendments to be made. 



The wife of former President Benigno Aquino addressed the protestors at a rally in the capital Manila after protestors marched through the city's financial district.



Protestors burn an effigy of President Joseph Estrada in the heart of Manila's financial district, Makati.



Twenty-five-thousand people gathered to protest in Manila and another 50-thousand around the country.



The Makati demonstration was reminiscent of the People Power phenomenon that

deposed President Ferdinand Marcos in 1986. 



Then, protestors also had the backing of both the former President Corazon Aquino and Catholic church leaders.



But this time, protesters acknowledged that the issues are much less clear since Estrada, who won a landslide victory just 15 months ago, still remains highly popular. 



Demonstrators object to changes Estrada has proposed to the country's constitution, which the president says is too protectionist and discourages much-needed foreign investment. 



The protestors fear the planned economic amendments might lead to politicians making other changes to the constitution, such as revisions by members of Congress to extend their terms in office.



Corazon Aquino, the wife of the former president and former leader herself, and the protestors say they want to prevent a slip back into dictatorship before it occurs.



SOUNDBITE: (English)

"The issue is not whether the president can extract a promise from a Constituent Congress not to tinker outside the economic provisions. The concern is whether they will define the economic to include everything that is to their advantage."

SUPER CAPTION: Corazon Aquino, former Philippines president



The issue of constitutional change has sharply divided Filipinos and has also dented the financial markets. 



Earlier in the week, stocks slumped to a six-month low while the country's currency, the peso, hit a nine-month low. 



Stocks, however, later made up some of their losses.



Similar rallies to the one in Manila the first mass protests against Estrada - were also held in Cebu, Davao, Baguio, Bacolod, Iligan and other cities. 



Critics also claim that Estrada is attempting to silence a critical press and has allowed a return of cronyism, in which close presidential friends receive special favours. 



Estrada has denied the accusations and insists that he only wants to lessen the divisions between rich and poor by drawing foreign investment to Philippines' money chests. 



SOUNDBITE: (English)

"We need to adjust our constitution with global realities. The constitution that we have was framed in a different time where the economy of nations was based on protectionism and where competition was not as intense as it is today."

SUPER CAPTION: Joseph Estrada, Philippines president



The adjustments would lift the bar preventing foreigners from owning land and would allow them to own more than 40 percent of important businesses. 



It's those restrictions which Estrada says are causing the Philippines to lose out on investment to its neighbours.



His proposed changes are generally backed by big business, but some smaller companies fear they may be overwhelmed by foreign competition. 



The amendments have have also split the Catholic church. 



While church leaders helped organize Friday's protests, more than a (m) million members of a large Catholic charismatic group, El Shaddai, held a rival rally in Manila.



It celebrated the 60th birthday of its leader, Mike Velarde, who is Estrada's spiritual adviser.



Aquino and Catholic Church officials led rallies two years ago which forced the

then-President Fidel Ramos to halt constitutional amendments aimed at extending his term.

items.description:
Boracay is a small island in the Philippines located approximately 315 km (196 mi) south of Manila and 2 km off the northwest tip of Panay Island in the Western Visayas region of the Philippines. Boracay Island and its beaches have received awards from numerous travel publications and agencies. The island comprises the barangays of Manoc-Manoc, Balabag, and Yapak in the municipality of Malay, in Aklan Province. The island is administered by the Philippine Tourism Authority and the provincial government of Aklan. Apart from its white sand beaches, Boracay is also famous for being one of the world's top destinations for relaxation. It is also emerging among the top destinations for tranquility and nightlife.

In 2012, Boracay was awarded as the best island in the world from the international travel magazine Travel + Leisure.

items.title: Huracan Patricia ya toco suelo Mexicano / Hurricane Patricia and touched Mexican soil
items.description:
Mexico, in October. 23, 2015.- The Patricia landfall at 17:40 hours Friday in the vicinity of the bays of Tenacatita, Cuestecomate and Christmas, where the towns of El Estrecho, La Manzanilla and Melaque are located in the municipalities of La Huerta and Cihuatlan, Jalisco, the National Weather Service.
 
When Patricia was assigned hurricane category 5, the highest level on the Saffir-Simpson scale, but has broken all ratings due to the intensity of its winds.



México, oct. 23, 2015.- El huracán Patricia tocó tierra a las 17:40 horas de este viernes en las inmediaciones de las Bahías de Tenacatita, Cuestecomate y Navidad, donde se ubican las poblaciones de El Estrecho, La Manzanilla y Melaque, en los municipios de La Huerta y Cihuatlán, Jalisco, informó el Servicio Meteorológico Nacional.
 
Al huracán Patricia le fue asignada la categoría 5, el máximo nivel en la escala Saffir-Simpson, pero ha roto todas las calificaciones debido a la intensidad de sus vientos.
 
Especialistas en meteorología catalogan a 'Patricia' como el huracán más peligroso y poderoso en la historia mundial.
 
"El más poderoso que haya existido en el planeta en toda la historia. No hay un huracán en todo el planeta en toda la historia que haya llegado en la velocidad de sus vientos a 325 kilómetros por hora, afirmó el director de la Comisión Nacional del Agua (Conagua), Roberto Ramírez.
 
Este meteoro es "sumamente violento" y "puede ser muy catastrófico", afirmó en una conferencia de prensa la mañana de este viernes.
 
El ojo de Patricia tiene un diámetro de 10 kilómetros. En el transcurso de la próxima hora, seguirá internándose en el sur de Jalisco. Los efectos de vientos de huracán y oleaje elevado son extremadamente peligroso y alcanzan también a Colima.
 
Se recomienda a la navegación marítima menor, localizada en las cercanías del sistema, no realizar actividades náuticas, turísticas, recreativas y comerciales en el mar y zonas costeras, durante las próximas horas.
 
Debido a que las precipitaciones recientes reblandecieron el suelo, podrían registrarse deslaves, deslizamientos de laderas, desbordamientos de ríos y arroyos o afectaciones en caminos y tramos carreteros, así como inundaciones en zonas bajas y saturación de drenajes en sitios urbanos.

items.title: Hurricane Patricia - Strongest Storm Ever Measured to Hit Mexico
items.description:
Hurricane Patricia became the strongest storm ever measured on the planet early Friday, with experts warning it could trigger 40-foot waves along southwestern Mexico and "life-threatening" flash flooding.

More than 7 million residents — and an estimated tens of thousands of U.S. citizens visiting or living there — were told to prepare for the "worst-case scenario" as the ferocious storm was expected to race ashore on Mexico's Pacific coast between 6 to 10 p.m. ET Friday.

At 5 p.m. ET, Patricia was about 60 miles west of Manzanillo, and about 110 miles south-southeast of Cabo Corrientes.

The U.S. National Hurricane Center said Patricia was expected to make landfall "in the next several hours." A hurricane warning was in place for San Blas to Punta San Telmo.

The tourist magnets of Puerto Vallarta and Manzanillo were directly in the Category 5 storm's projected path, and Puerto Vallarta's airport was closed Friday out of precaution as some stranded vacationers described their inability to fly out of a "nightmare."

By 5 p.m. winds had weakened slightly to 190 mph, the Hurricane Center said. Winds of 200 mph were measured earlier, and the Hurricane Center labeled Patricia as the "strongest hurricane on record" in the Atlantic and eastern North Pacific Basins.

Mexico has not formally requested help from the U.S., but State Department spokesman Mark Toner told reporters Friday that America "stands up to offer any assistance that we can in the aftermath of what at least appears to be a pretty epic event in terms of the intensity and size of the storm."

items.title: Hurricane Patricia 2015 Hits Mexico - strongest hurricane ever recorded
items.description:
Hurricane Patricia is one of the most rapidly intensifying tropical cyclones on record.
Hurricane Patricia intensified as if the storm were a match thrown onto a pool full of gasoline.

The storm was only a Category 4 with winds of 150 miles per hour as of Thursday evening, after intensifying from minimal tropical storm status a day earlier. This means that Hurricane Patricia is one of the most rapidly intensifying tropical cyclones on record, and it's occurring in a year that has featured several intensifiers in various parts of the world.

The fact that the storm became so intense, so quickly, may be an example of how global warming is raising the intensity of the strongest tropical cyclones.

Se prevé que origine lluvias de muy fuertes a intensas en el noreste y occidente de México, así como rachas de viento y oleaje elevado en los estados del Pacífico Central y noreste del país.                         

Patricia se manifiesta en vientos sostenidos de 400 kilómetros por hora y podrá dejar fuertes lluvias en la parte oeste del país.

Las autoridades evacuaron a los habitantes de localidades de los estados de Colima, Nayarit y Jalisco, cerraron los puertos de Manzanillo y de Puerto Vallarta y exigieron a los turistas cancelar sus viajes por temor a una catástrofe.

items.title: Hurricane Patricia nears Mexico at record strength 2015
items.description:
Hurricane Patricia nears Mexico at record strength:
Over the past day or so, a phenomenal episode of strengthening has pushed Hurricane Patricia into the record books. Now, as the strongest hurricane ever measured—with 200 mph sustained winds—Patricia is just hours from making landfall in Mexico.
The National Hurricane Center, with official forecasting responsibility for the Atlantic and eastern Pacific, all but ran out of words to describe the storm’s ferocity, labeling it “potentially catastrophic” and “incredible.” On Twitter, professional weather watchers went a step further, marveling at the storm’s record-breaking ability and fearing for Mexico’s coastal cities. Such a scenario—a quickly strengthening storm of unprecedented strength headed straight for land—is the stuff of meteorologists’ nightmares.

As of Friday morning, Patricia was a strong Category 5 hurricane—after strengthening from just tropical storm strength a day earlier. Still, calling Patricia a Category 5 underestimates just how ferocious this storm is.

Patricia is headed for a landfall between Manzanillo and Puerto Vallarta on Mexico’s southwest coast on Friday. The storm threatens to be the strongest ever to hit Mexico’s Pacific coast, surpassing a 1959 hurricane that also ranks as the deadliest in that part of the Pacific. As it moves inland, Patricia is expected to produce up to two feet of rain in Mexico’s coastal mountain range, creating a risk of flooding and mudslides over a vast area including Guadalajara, the country’s second-largest city.

As of Friday morning, Mexico is scrambling to prepare for Patricia. Three states—Jalisco, Colima, and Nayarit—have declared states of emergency. In Colima, officials handed out sandbags. Nearly 400,000 people are in the storm’s path.

items.title: Guest testimonials after Hurricane Patrice - Puerto Vallarta
items.description: Garza Blanca Preserve in Puerto Vallarta is pleased and grateful to announce it is fully operational following the threat of Hurricane Patricia to Mexico’s Pacific coast on Friday October 23, 2015. By 8am on Saturday October 24th, 2015, the beachfront infinity pools were open once more and a delicious buffet breakfast was being served to guests at Garza Blanca Preserve Puerto Vallarta as if nothing had happened following a tension-filled day during the passing of Hurricane Patricia several miles south of Puerto Vallarta on Mexico’s Pacific coast.   Breaking records with over 200 mph winds for the strongest hurricane to make landfall in the America’s, Hurricane Patricia was a force to be reckoned with on Mexico’s Pacific coast this past Friday October 23rd. Having escalated to a Category 5 hurricane in less than 4 days and making the record for the lowest pressure in any Pacific hurricane, Patricia made landfall near the town of Cuixmala, Jalisco, more than a 100 miles from Puerto Vallarta

items.title: Les effets du cyclone #MEGH seront ressentis à Djibouti à partir du 10 novembre, selon l’Agence nati
items.description:
"Les effets du cyclone #MEGH seront ressentis à Djibouti à partir du 10 novembre", selon l’Agence nationale de la Météorologie Par ADI

"Le cyclone tropical MEGH se déplace en s’intensifiant vers l’Ouest-sud-ouest en direction du Cap Gardafui et le Golfe d’Aden avec un léger décalage de sa trajectoire vers le sud (Corne d’Afrique)."

C’est ce qu’a indiqué l’Agence nationale de la Météorologie dans un communiqué qu’elle vient de publier, ajoutant que "le cyclone MEGH, actuellement sur l’ile de Socotra (Yémen), touchera de plein fouet la pointe de la Corne de l’Afrique le 9 novembre 2015".

"En ce qui concerne notre pays, les effets du cyclone seront ressentis à partir du 10 novembre avec le maximum d’intensité prévue pour le 12 novembre", peut-on lire dans ce même communiqué.

Même s’il est de plus faible intensité, le cyclone MEGH va générer, selon l’Agence nationale de la Météorologie, une instabilité météorologique qui sera certainement plus significative pour la République de Djibouti que le cyclone Chapala.

L’Agence nationale de la Météorologie a demandé enfin à toutes les institutions du pays et particulièrement celles de la gestion des risques de catastrophes naturelles d’observer et de prendre toutes les mesures de prévention de risques nécessaires pour la sécurité de la population.

Texte de ADI

items.title: flooding in Baghdad1 30-10-2015
items.description:
After a dry summer, heavy rains fell on Baghdad, Iraq on October 29, 2015 resulting in major flooding.

According to a spokesman for the meteorological department more than 2 inches of rain fell on the city in a 24 hour span. Some motorists were forced to leave their cars when they became stuck in deep water.

In a camp for displaced people north of Baghdad a three year old was killed when she was swept away by flood waters.

items.title: Heavy flooding in Al Mukalla, Yemen, Cyclone Chapala 2015 landfall [ video ]
items.description:
Cyclone Chapala is headed for an extremely rare landfall at hurricane strength along the coast of war-torn Yemen late Monday or early Tuesday (mainland U.S. time). While wind damage will be a threat near the point of landfall, the bigger concern will be extremely heavy rainfall in a normally arid region, leading to life-threatening flash floods in a country already suffering a major humanitarian crisis stemming from years of violent conflict.

According to the India Meteorological Department, the agency sanctioned by the World Meteorological Organization for issuing official tropical cyclone bulletins for the Arabian Sea, the center of Chapala was located about 50 miles (80 kilometers) south-southwest of Al Mukalla, Yemen, as of 7 p.m. EST Monday, or 3 a.m. Tuesday Yemen time.

At that time, IMD estimated the cyclone's maximum sustained winds at 75 mph (120 kph) while the U.S. military's Joint Typhoon Warning Center estimated them at 85 mph (140 kph). Either way, Chapala was a Category 1 equivalent storm on the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale as it closed in on the coast of Yemen's mainland on the Arabian Peninsula.

The IMD forecast calls for Chapala's core of hurricane-force winds to graze Yemen's fifth largest city, the coastal, war-ravaged port of Al Mukalla, with a population of roughly 300,000. Landfall is expected to the southwest of that city near the border between the governorates of Hadramaut and Shabwah.

On Sunday, the eye of Chapala passed north of the Yemeni island of Socotra, where flooding rain and damaging winds were reported. The island has likely not experienced a cyclone of hurricane-equivalent intensity since 1922.

items.title: CYCLONE CHAPALA 2015 landfall || Heavy Flooding in AL MUKALLA, YEMEN
items.description:
Tropical Cyclone Chapala is barreling toward Yemen's coast, bringing the threat of fierce winds and potentially several times the amount of rain that the impoverished country usually gets in an entire year.

The storm -- the second strongest ever recorded in the Arabian Sea -- is expected to make landfall on Yemen's central coast Tuesday.

Chapala was already dumping light to medium rain in Al Mukalla, where wave heights swelled between 1-4 meters (3-13 feet). The storm was some 117 kilometers (72 miles) south of the port city early Tuesday local time.

Chapala was packing maximum sustained winds of 195 kph (120 mph) Monday, but was expected to weaken somewhat as it gets closer to the dry air of the Arabian Peninsula.

The storm is still forecast to pack a punch when it hits Yemen with the strength of a Category 1 hurricane. The major concern is the extraordinary volume of rain it's going to dump on the country's dry, rugged terrain.

items.title: Saudi coalition airstrike on strawberry farm in Safia Tamesh, Sanhan, Yemen, 4 Nov 2015
items.description: The following information was passed on to activist @jamilahanan by the neighbour of the family who were injured in the video (who Jamila knew prior to the incident): On 4th November 2015 at 8.45 am, the Saudi led coalition airstrikes hit a strawberry farm in the village of Safia Tamesh in the Sanhan region, Sana'a Governorate, Yemen, where a poor family were picking strawberries to earn a living. 9 people were reported to have been injured, of which 2 were women and 4 were children. 2 of the injured children were reported as seriously injured. Apparently the rocket was clearly seen fired from a plane by most of the villagers due to the time that it was dropped in the morning. In the video the children are about to be driven to the hospital shortly after the incident. The man is repeatedly saying 'they striked in the middle of strawberry farm' and he also says to the children 'don't be scared, God shall take our revenge'. The neighbour also sent photos of the crater in the field after the airstrike, commenting that it was a surprise that nobody died.

items.title: Catamaran Sail & Snorkel in Nassau Bahamas... Tropical Storm Kate Edition!!
items.description:
Catamaran Sail & Snorkel in Nassau Bahamas... Tropical Storm Kate Edition!! (11/10/2015)

GoPro Hero 3+ Black Edition 1080p 60fps Protune CAM RAW WIDE FOV (50% Speed)
Color Corrected in GoPro Studio 2.5

The songs "Sand Castles" by "The Green Orbs", The Bluest Star" by "The 126ers" and "Suns Rise" by "Silent Partner" provided by YouTube Audio (https://www.youtube.com/audiolibrary/music)

Snorkeling starts @1:29

This is some footage from our catamaran sail & snorkel Nassau Bahamas excursion while traveling on the Carnival Fascination cruise ship... hugely hilarious back story later. This was mine and my wife's 17th wedding anniversary and my Daughter and Son in Law's honeymoon... we decided to go on a cruise together and had a blast. We were heading straight for tropical storm Kate as it was passing Nassau and really thought our day in Nassau was going to be ruined. When we arrived that morning the storm had moved out and away and the weather was perfect. The only noticeable affect was that the water was slightly hazy, but still managed to get some incredible footage. The ride out to the reef was fantastic and when we arrived at the reef I was so excited to get in the water. We saw lots of species of fish, rays, coral etc (some included in this videos). I will be posting a fish only video later that will highlight the many fish we saw. On the way back from the reef we indulged in the complementary rum punch that seemed to flow endlessly. Needless to saw, by the time we got back to the dock we were felling mighty good. Now for the back story....

When we were exiting the ship in Nassau they stated the requirement a photo ID as well as your sail and sign card and my wife and I had left our licenses in our room safe. My wife, daughter and son in law exited the ship and I immediately ran back to my room to get our licenses with our excursion tickets in hand. I was in such a hurry that I got flustered and mis-remembered our room number. I must have ran the length of the ship four times trying to find my room until I came to ours. I then had to locate my wife's wallet and I am terrible at looking for things. I came to the apparent  realization that I was going to miss the excursion, but right then I found my wife's wallet and was off again to find the ship's gangway exit.. had to slow down to keep from hyperventilating. Found the exit, but it was not our original exit and started getting panicky again. I pass the second exit and my wife saw me and we began our long trek up to the docks and for those that have been there know how long it is. I made it to the main entrance to Nassau and saw no transports so I really thought we were done in at that point. I then looked over towards the water and saw a fenced gateway leading to a catamaran so I ran over to see if it was ours and it was! I waited briefly for my wife and then she said, "Do you have the tickets?" In all the hustle and bustle I had left our tickets in our room when looking for my wife's wallet. Fortunately we left them our ship and room information and they were able to verify that we had paid for the excursion. After all that we were now boarding the catamaran and breathing a large sigh of relief. Now that deserves a huge LMAO!!!

items.title: Snorkeling at Junkanoo Beach in Nassau Bahamas... Surprises and Close-Ups!!
items.description:
Snorkeling at Junkanoo Beach in Nassau Bahamas... Surprises and Close-Ups!! (11/10/2015)

This was mine and my wife's 17th Wedding Anniversary and my Daughter and Son in Law's Honeymoon... we decided to go on a cruise together and had a blast. We were heading straight for tropical storm Kate as it was passing Nassau and really thought our day in Nassau was going to be ruined. When we arrived that morning the storm had moved out and away and the weather was perfect. The wives went shopping and my Son in law Jamie (https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCrv1bN8eCEMRHAnEc3qnATA) and I visited Junkanoo Beach. The beach is walking distance from the cruise ships, free and the beach bar had a special 3 beers and 3 shots for $10... so you got to love that, huh? The only noticeable affect from the storm was that the water was slightly hazy, but still managed to get some incredible closeup footage. There were several things I caught on film and did not even realize it due to my line of sight and camera position. Many sweet surprises!

items.title: Reef Snorkel in Nassau Bahamas... Under The Sea!!
items.description:
Reef Snorkel in Nassau Bahamas... Under The Sea!! (11/10/2015)

This was mine and my wife's 17th Wedding Anniversary and my Daughter and Son in Law's Honeymoon... we decided to go on a cruise together and had a blast. We were heading straight for tropical storm Kate as it was passing Nassau and really thought our day in Nassau was going to be ruined. When we arrived that morning the storm had moved out and away and the weather was perfect. The only noticeable affect was that the water was slightly hazy, but still managed to get some incredible footage. The ride out to the reef in Nassau Harbor was fantastic and when we arrived at the reef I was so excited to get in the water. The amount of fish and different  species was massive and the surrounding underwater scenery was absolutely beautiful. We only had about 45 min, but I could have stayed out there much longer. I took full advantage of our limited time and captured as much footage as I could and grabbed some really spectacular shots. On the way back from the reef we indulged in the complementary rum punch that seemed to flow endlessly. Needless to saw, by the time we got back to the dock we were felling mighty good...

Here's a list of some of the fish I could identify...

items.title: Many many Whale Sharks - November 2015
items.description:
Cabo Trek your BEST option for in Cabo San Lucas!

http://www.cabotrek.com

Snorkeling with whale shark today was just incredible! We counted at least 25 different shark, at a certain point we were surrounded, no need to move they were everywhere! The drone shows 8 sharks in a very small area: they were feeding! The best part was that this tour was about to be cancelled for bad weather, and yes the sun was not out, the wind was blowing, the swell was big...but sometimes you have to take your chances...we did and we were rewarded with a memorable day!

Although I wasn't able to catch them on video, on this same day we run across mobula mantas (evil rays), turtles, sea lions and further at distance in the background there were humpback whales breaching out of the water! All in one day, all in one tour!

items.title: Philippines hit by massive Typhoon Melor
items.description:
MANILA, Philippines (AP) — About 725,000 people fled their homes and communities braced for heavy rain and coastal floods of up to 13 feet as Typhoon Melor slammed Monday into the eastern Philippines, officials said. Classes, flights and ferry trips were suspended.

The government's weather bureau said the typhoon was packing winds of 95 mph with gusts of up to 115 mph, and heavy to intense rain within its 185-mile diameter. It made landfall Monday morning on tiny Batag Island in the eastern Philippines, and a second landfall was expected in Sorsogon province.

The National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council said 724,839 residents of three eastern provinces were evacuated Sunday and early Monday before the storm's arrival.
The largest numbers of evacuees were in Sorsogon and Albay provinces.

Bernardo Alejandro, a regional civil defense official, said many residents of Sorsogon voluntarily went to shelters Sunday night, but the provincial governor then ordered evacuations Monday for residents who had refused to leave their homes despite the risk of floods and landslides.
In Albay, about 590,000 residents were evacuated as a precaution, including tens of thousands from around Mount Mayon volcano, where volcanic mudflows are an added threat, the national council said.
Edgar Posadas, a civil defense official in the Eastern Visayas region, said parts of Allen town in Northern Samar province were flooded, and strong winds tore off roofs and felled coconut trees.
He said no casualties had been reported even in the northern tip of the province, where the typhoon first made landfall, and that the evacuation of residents and preparedness of local officials had so far proved effective.
About 20 storms and typhoons hit the Philippines each year. In November 2013,Typhoon Haiyan, the strongest typhoon on record to make landfall, left more than 7,300 people dead and missing as it leveled entire villages and swept walls of seawater into parts of the central Philippines.

items.title: Pilipinas Bagyong, Lando Intensifies Further Interacts With New Typhoon
items.description:
Pilipinas Bagyong, Lando Intensifies Further Interacts With New Typhoon
Metro Manila (CNN Philippines) — Typhoon Lando intensified further as it threatened the provinces of Aurora, Isabela, and Northern Quezon on Saturday (October 17).
It was spotted 230 km east of Baler, Aurora, packing winds of 175 kph, as of 4 p.m.
State weather bureau PAGASA's acting Director Espie Cayanan warned that Lando might stay longer in the Philippine area of responsibility (PAR) because it was interacting with Typhoon Champi, which was spotted outside the PAR.
"Habang hindi siya [Champi] tumataas at lumalayo, hindi makakagalaw si Lando," she said.
[Translation: "Lando won't be able to move away as long as (Champi) remains near it."]
It was likened to the weather conditions of 2009's Typhoon Pepeng, but PAGASA hoped it wouldn't be as devastating.
The rainfall was expected to be heavy to intense within the 650 kilometer diameter of the typhoon.
Lando is expected to make a landfall over Aurora area by Sunday morning (October 18).
Possible storm surges may reach to a maximum of 3 meters in Aurora and neighboring provinces, with wave height in open sea may reach up to 14 meters or higher.
The National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC) warned that Lando was turning out to be unlike previous ones.
"Hindi ito karaniwang bagyo, nakikita nating tatagal ito hanggang Martes (Oct. 20)," Executive Director Alexander Pama said.
[Translation: "This is no ordinary typhoon, we expect it to remain here until Tuesday."]
Pama said that, as of early Saturday evening, provinces affected by the typhoon remained in manageable condition.
It is usually up to the local government units to decide when their constituents should leave their homes for safer grounds.
However, in the coastal areas of Aurora, Cagayan and Isabela, the NDRRMC strongly advised local officials to carry out forced evacuations.
Pama said the government had over P94-million worth of food items in the areas affected by Lando.
Source: http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2015/10/17/Typhoon-Lando-LandoPH-Champi-PAGASA.html

items.title: Typhoon Melor (video) 3 people de@d as storm lashes the Philippines
items.description:
Typhoon Melor carved through the central Philippines on Tuesday, bringing heavy rain and strong winds that left millions without power and at least three people dead, officials said.
One person died of hypothermia while two others drowned in floods in the fishing town of Catarman in Northern Samar province in the Visayas region south of Manila, municipal disaster officer Jonathan Baldo told DZMM radio.

The storm toppled trees and cut electricity to at least seven provinces, the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC) said.

Christmas lanterns and lights, tin roofs and branches littered the streets of the city of Legazpi, which was battered by strong winds.

People who fled from their coastal homes spent a sleepless night in evacuation centres, sprawled on classroom tables and chairs as flying debris swirled around outside.
Melor whipped the vast Bicol peninsula, with a population of 5.4 million people, overnight before slamming into the Romblon islands on Tuesday morning.

Gusts had weakened somewhat by Tuesday morning but were still recorded at 170km (106 miles) per hour, from 185km per hour on Monday. The storm was expected to weaken further as it heads to Mindoro island and out into the South China Sea later Tuesday, state weather forecaster Aldczar Aurelio said.

There were no immediate reports of casualties in the typhoon-prone Bicol region, where 720,000 people were evacuated as early as the weekend.

“We have zero floods, zero deaths, zero casualties,” Albay governor Joey Salceda told ABS-CBN television.

“What we are asking for is the early restoration of electricity,” he said, adding the entire province of 1.2 million people was without power.

Authorities were assessing Melor’s damage while bracing for another typhoon brewing east of Mindanao, the country’s main southern island, said NDRRMC spokeswoman Mina Marasigan.
